<1ST_LINE>r i AM-RockMusicAuction     08-24 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rock Music Auction,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elvis Costumes Fetch Top Dollar at Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stage costume worn by Elvis Presley sold
Wednesday at a rock'n'roll and film memorabilia auction for
$43,700, a record price for a piece of the late singer's clothing,
auctioneers said.
   Bidding was also fierce for another Presley costume, for a 1964
telegram from former Beatle Ringo Starr and for a four-foot wall
thermometer featuring Marilyn Monroe, officials said at Phillips
auction house.
   Warren Stone of the Hard Rock Cafe in Los Angeles bought
``Shooting Star,'' a suit Presley wore at a 1972 concert at Madison
Square Garden in New York, the auctioneers said. Hard Rock cafes
are decorated with rock music memorabilia.
   Commission costs raised the total purchase price of the costume
to $48,050, a Phillips statement said.
   Former country music singer Jimmy Velvet bought for $23,500 a
Presley stage suit nicknamed ``Good Luck'' by the singer and worn
on a 1972 tour of Hawaii.
   ``This makes six jump suits which were once worn by Elvis which
I now own,'' said Velvet, who plans to exhibit the outfit at an
Elvis Presley museum he runs in Nashville, Tenn.
   The costumes were the highlights of 550 items on sale, said
Wendell Milton, rock and pop memorabilia specialist for the London
auction house.
   ``They very rarely come up for auction,'' said Milton. ``Most of
them are in Graceland,'' the Nashville mansion Presley owned before
his death in 1977. It now is a museum.
   Former Beatle drummer Starr sent his telegram to a Dutch
newspaper to apologize for pulling out of a Beatles tour of Holland
because of tonsillitis.
   ``I'm very sorry I couldn't come to Holland and hope to see all
my Dutch fans on the next trip. Ringo Starr,'' it said.
   It had been expected to fetch $336. But Stone bid against Brian
Murphy of London's Hard Rock Cafe and won with an offer of $3,000.
   ``I bought it because I liked it,'' Stone said. ``I know it was
a lot to pay.''
   Stone estimated he spent about $74,000 at Wednesday's auction.
He said he will exhibit all his purchases.
   A private collector paid $7,700 for the bright-orange
thermometer featuring Marilyn Monroe to promote her 1959 film
``Some Like It Hot.'' The collector was not identified.
   Phillips said it had been expected to sell for $1,340.
   ``I think people go crazy for anything to do with Marilyn
Monroe,'' Milton said. ``She's so in vogue right now.''
   Milton said the auction raised $287,300, but had its
disappointments _ including handwritten lyrics by Bruce Springsteen
and stage clothing worn by Michael Jackson.
   Six sets of singer and guitarist Springsteen's lyrics were
offered for auction, but only two lyric sheets for the songs ``I've
Got A Fever'' and ``Cancel My Tomorrows,'' found buyers, Milton
said.
   A shirt Michael Jackson wore at the Jackson Brothers' first
concert after the group left the Motown label in 1976 sold for
$1,680, about half the estimate, he said.
   Four glittery stage suits worn by the Osmond Brothers on their
1975 European tour sold for a total of $4,370. Each suit was marked
with the name of the brother who owned it: Donny, Merrill, Alan and
Jay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
