<1ST_LINE>u a AM-North-Arrests     08-24 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North-Arrests,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protests At Oliver North Appearance Result In Arrests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAUKESHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A face-off between demonstrators
supporting and opposing Oliver North resulted in a dozen arrests
Wednesday night outside a Republican fund-raiser where the
Iran-Contra defendant appeared.
   Twelve anti-North demonstrators were taken into custody for
disorderly conduct, Lt. Terry Martorano of the Waukesha County
Sheriff's Department said. He said two were also cited for
resisting arrest and one for possession of a controlled substance.
No injuries were reported
   By 10 p.m., most of those arrested were free on bail, he said,
adding that they would face court dates in about two weeks.
   Martorano said most of the arrests involved demonstrators who
were ``generally not adhering to rules set up out there for the
protesters to follow.'' Police required the anti-North
demonstrators to stay within a specific area preventing any
intermingling of the two protest groups.
   Reporters at the scene said there were about 125 anti-North
protesters and 60 pro-North demonstrators.
   Ardelle Hough of Madison, who described herself as an officer of
the Women's International League for Peace and Freedom, contended
the police rules and the arrests violated the protesters'
constitutional rights of free speech and free assembly.
   North, a former National Security Council aide, retired earlier
this year as a lieutenant colonel after 20 years in the Marine
Corps. He was among four people named in an indictment sought by a
special prosecutor who investigated the sales of U.S. arms to Iran
and diversion of funds to aid rebels in Nicaragua.
   The protesters gathered outside the Waukesha Exposition Center
in the Town of Pewaukee where North was appearing at a fund-raiser
for former state Republican Party Chairman Steve King, who is
seeking the GOP nomination for U.S. Senate.
   Hough said King is a former FBI agent with a national security
background.
   ``The issue isn't Ollie North,'' she said. ``The issue isn't
even George Bush. The issue is U.S. foreign policy, pushing around
all the rest of the people of the world.''
</TEXT>
