<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BeachWastes     08-24 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beach Wastes,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assembly Strengthens Infectious Waste Dump Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Assembly Tuesday night gave final
legislative approval to a measure that would stiffen penalties for
those caught illegally dumping infectious medical wastes.
   The bill, which passed 142-0 without debate, also provides more
money for enforcement and needs only the signature of Gov. Mario
Cuomo to become law.
   It's designed to stem the flow of medical debris that washed
ashore on several New York City and Long Island beaches, closing
them to bathers on some of the hottest days of the year.
   The bill would provide penalties of up to 10 years in jail and
fines of $100,000 for people convicted of disposing of ``red bag''
wastes, so named because the waste is required to be thrown out in
specially marked containers.
   New York state will also provide $2 million to add new illegal
dumping patrols.
   State Environmental Conservation Commissioner Thomas Jorling
concluded last month that there was no single source for the waste
washing up on New York beaches. He said the waste may have come
through the New York City sanitation system, through illegal
dumping, casual dumping from boats or some combination of all of
these.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
