<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CraterVents     08-24 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crater Vents,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dives End With No Vents Seen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRATER LAKE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists finished a series of dives
in the nation's deepest lake Tuesday without fulfilling their hope
of finding hydrothermal vents.
   Peter Thompson, the chief ranger at Crater Lake National Park,
said the dives, which began Aug. 5, nevertheless yielded a wealth
of information.
   ``A variety of hydrothermal information, clues as it were, were
seen _ bacterial mats, temperature anomalies, manganese deposits,
which are all in association with hydrothermal activity,'' Thompson
said.
   ``A great deal of biological and geological information is going
to be derived from the samples taken,'' he added.
   Oregon State University scientists Jack Dymond and Robert
Collier took turns making dives in the one-man submersible ``Deep
Rover.'' They are in the second year of a three-year study, funded
by the National Park Service, on the possible effect of hot springs
on the lake.
   The work is part of a larger 10-year study launched when the
1,932-foot-deep lake began to lose some of its famous clarity.
   The work also could produce information for use in the debate
over whether California Energy Co. should be allowed to develop
hydrothermal energy close outside the park.
   Dymond and Collier are scheduled to return next summer for the
last series of dives.
</TEXT>
