<DOCNO> AP880824-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     08-24 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: `K' in 2nd graf of 1st item is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several of the Democrats from last month's
national convention still haven't left town.
   ``Neither Dukakis nor Bentsen has been claimed. I think Jesse
Jackson's still there and I think Grits and Fritz are still there,
too,'' said K Thweatt, public relations manager for Georgia's Stone
Mountain Park.
   Dukakis, Bentsen, Jackson, Grits and Fritz are among the 11
donkeys the state park acquired for publicity purposes during the
Democratic National Convention. They have yet to find a new home.
   The park plans to keep two of the donkeys, but the others are
available for $150 each.
   Thweatt said the animals got around quite a bit during the
convention.
   ``They probably went to more prestigious parties and events than
any of us, so we feel like they're very well-traveled donkeys,''
she said. ``They know all the right people. I'm not saying how many
parties they could get their owners into now, but they did all
right during the convention.''
   Thweatt said she's happy the GOP chose New Orleans for its
convention.
   ``I shudder to think what would've happened to the park if we
had had the Republican Convention,'' she said. ``I can't imagine
all those elephants.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PLAINVIEW, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Police Chief Roy Osborne explains it,
there just wasn't enough crime in this West Texas town of 25,000 to
justify keeping a patrol officer who worked like a dog.
   ``There was no sense wasting his talent,'' the chief said of
Lazer, a 3-year-old Belgian shepherd. ``He needed to be moved
someplace where he can be used.''
   Lazer recently was shipped to an El Paso security firm.
   ``Our burglaries have been down to the point that we hadn't had
much call to use an animal in building searches. We'd like to have
used him more, but we're glad we didn't have to,'' said Osborne,
who added that he missed Lazer.
   Osborne's decision also was prompted by the request of Lazer's
regular handler that he be transferred from his 8 p.m. to 4 a.m.
shift. The chief couldn't find anyone in the 29-person department
to replace Lazer's keeper.
   But Osborne said that while the canine unit has been disbanded,
his force still has another employee with a nose for sniffing out
crime. Sonny, a golden retriever, will continue to live with one of
the department's detectives and work on drug investigations.
</TEXT>
