<2ND_LINE>AM-Election Rdp, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0755,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Primaries in Oklahoma, Alaska; Olympics Vote in
Anchorage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with later returns, Glassco
winning, quotes. Picks up 7th graf pvs `In Alaska...' Material
below dash will stand. Polls close at midnight EDT in Alaska.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Mike Synar defeated a primary challenger Tuesday who
labeled the five-term Democrat too liberal for his Oklahoma
district, while Anchorage, Alaska, voters decided whether to keep
the city in the running for the 1994 Winter Olympics.
   One congressional primary contest was on the ballot in Alaska
and seven in Oklahoma, including a five-person fight for the
Democratic nomination in the district that is comprised largely of
Tulsa.
   In that race, Kurt Glassco, 32, a former prosecutor and onetime
aide to former Gov. George Nigh, won without a runoff over four
other Democrats seeking the right to challenge Rep. James Inhofe,
who was unopposed in the GOP primary.
   Glassco said he was ``ecstatic'' with his success in his first
run for public office.
   ``It means those of us who are mainstream, conservative
Democrats are the majority party here,'' he said. He said he was
confident that the ``Ronald Reagan Democrats will be with us on
Nov. 8.''
   Synar, who describes himself as a moderate not a liberal, said
of his victory, ``It should put these labels to bed once and for
all _ Oklahomans are tired of it.''
   With 348 of 467 precincts reporting in Synar's largely rural
northeastern Oklahoma distrcit, the incumbent had 48,314 votes, or
69 percent, and state Sen. Frank Shurden had 21,730, or 31 percent.
   In the Republican race to challenge Synar, Ira Philips, 50,
director of business development for the Cherokee Indian Nation,
led with 4,895 votes, or 53 percent, to 4,258, or 47 percent, for
Marshall Farrier, 60, a rancher.
   As expected, incumbent Democratic Reps. Dave McCurdy and Glenn
English won re-nomination overwhelmingly, as did Republican Rep.
Mickey Edwards.
   In Alaska, voters selected candidates for the state's lone
congressional seat. Rep. Don Young, a Republican seeking his ninth
term, and Democrat Peter Gruenstein, a former state prosecutor
making his first try for statewide office, were both expected to
win their respective primaries handily.
   Voters in Anchorage decided a ballot issue crucial to the city's
bid for the 1994 Olympic Games _ whether the city government would
agree to cover losses if the local Olympic organizing committee
does not raise enough money to stage the games.
   Passage of the Olympics measure would not assure selection of
Anchorage for the games, but defeat would effectively eliminate the
city from the list of finalists when the International Olympic
Committee chooses the host city next month. The other finalists are
in Norway, Bulgaria and Sweden.
   In 1985, Anchorage voters endorsed the Olympics bid by a 2-to-1
margin, but were not told that the city would have to sign a
financial agreement. In July, a poll sanctioned by the Anchorage
Organizing Committee, which is seeking to stage the games, showed
voters evenly divided on financial guarantees.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   In Oklahoma's 2nd District, the winner of the Democratic primary
is heavily favored in the general election because no Republican
has been elected from the district since 1920.
   Shurden, 47, cited Synar's relatively high ratings from liberal
groups and a vote against a federal death penalty for major drug
traffickers. Synar calls himself a moderate, particularly when
compared with congressmen from other states.
   Synar, 37, gained national attention two years ago with his
successful lawsuit to force changes in the Gramm-Rudman
balanced-budget law. He refuses money from political action
committees and has sought legislation banning advertising of
cigarettes.
   When he was in the state House, Shurden gained wide attention
for winning passage of a bill calling for the castration of
convicted sex offenders. The measure died in a Senate committee.
   In the 3rd District, Democratic Rep. Wes Watkins was unopposed
for re-election in the Democratic primary and there was no one
running in the Republican primary. Oklahoma's four other incumbent
congressmen were also heavily favored in primary races.
</TEXT>
