<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0702 08-24 0853</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0702,0869</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cool Overnight Temperatures, Calm Winds Slow Spread of Fires</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with new fire acreage figures, Oregon and
Washington fires, and Alaska firefighters moving south to help
Western states. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM BUERKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cooler weather and relatively calm winds helped firefighters and
Army regulars as they forged new battle lines against fires in
Yellowstone and Grand Teton national parks Tuesday.
   Firefighters also made progress against the Warm Springs Creek
fire, which has destroyed more than a dozen structures southeast of
Helena, Mont. Some of the 2,900 firefighters battling the blaze
were scheduled to go home Tuesday and officials predicted
containment by Wednesday evening.
   In Wyoming, no significant rainfall has been reported in
Yellowstone or Grand Teton since June, but temperatures dipped to
the mid 30s early Tuesday, slowing the spread of 10 fires burning
on about 375,000 acres.
   ``Overnight it (fire acreage) didn't seem to increase too much.
The weather has been cooperative,'' Yellowstone spokeswoman
Michelle Rotter said.
   Fire officials hoped temperatures would dip below freezing
Tuesday night, which, combined with the trace of moisture in the
air, could create frost that could slow the fires' advance.
   More than 1,200 soldiers flown in from Fort Lewis, Wash., have
joined almost 4,000 firefighters who have spent weeks on the front
lines of blazes all over the West.
   Half the soldiers were based at the Shoshone National Forest
near Yellowstone's eastern border to keep the 156,502-acre
Clover-Mist fire from burning into commercial stands of timber,
while the others went to the 4,310-acre Hunter fire in Grand Teton
National Park, said Rotter.
   Yellowstone officials reopened 41 miles of park roads, but the
park's south entrance remained closed Tuesday, forcing visitors to
travel about 150 miles to enter the park through its west entrance,
Rotter said.
   The Grant Village complex, which includes a hotel, campground,
visitor center and staff dormitories, also remained closed and
officials restricted overnight backcountry use in all but the
park's northeastern corner, she added.
   The stubborn Clover-Mist fire shifted to the east, away from the
Montana state line towns of Cooke City and Silver Gate, but
firefighters continued protecting the towns, Rotter said.
   In the Bridger-Teton National Forest and Grand Teton National
Park, the 6,000-acre Huck fire kept the Flagg Ranch and Rockefeller
Memorial Parkway that links Yellowstone to Grand Teton closed. The
fire ``crowned,'' burning treetops on either side of the road, said
fire information officer Ed Waldapfel.
   In the forest's Teton Wilderness, the 46,750-acre Mink Creek
fire continued to burn, but firefighters hoped to contain the
1,500-acre Emerald Lake fire by Thursday.
   Crews also hoped to contain the 9,000-acre Lost fire in the
Bighorn National Forest Wednesday night, he said.
   In Montana, about 2,900 firefighters strengthened fire lines on
the northeast and southeast flanks of the 37,000-acre Warm Springs
Creek fire southeast of Helena, where it was burning actively. They
also were putting out ``hot spots'' that could flare if winds pick
up again.
   ``All in all, the fire is looking very good,'' fire information
officer Bob Krepps said. ``As long as we don't have the wind, I
think we're going to do OK.''
   Firefighters have built more than 75 miles of lines around the
two-week-old blaze, which destroyed 13 homes and several ranch
buildings last week.
   Firefighters made progress on fencing in two fires in the
Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness in southern Montana, just north of
Yellowstone, while forest officials used helicopters to locate and
warn backcountry hikers.
   About 70 firefighters were depending on natural barriers like
lakes and rocky areas to halt the spread of the 24,000-acre Storm
Creek fire about nine miles north of Cooke City, said Leroy White
of the Custer National Forest. Crews also were burning out timber
stands in areas where the fire might escape.
   Fifteen miles to the west, about 500 firefighters sought to
prevent the 27,000-acre Hellroaring Creek fire from spreading to
the northeast, said Phil Cowan of the Gallatin National Forest.
   In southeast Montana, crews had constructed about 18 miles of
lines around the 12,000-acre Kirby fire and hoped to contain it by
nightfall, said Don Kendall of the Department of State Lands. The
fire is sought of the Northern Cheyenne Indian Reservation.
   More than 300 firefighters who have helped battle blazes in
Alaska have headed south to help out in Western states, and more
were on their way Tuesday.
   The Alaska Fire Service still classifies 31 fires as active, but
by Tuesday, only one was manned. At the peak of the season, some 50
fires raged, and the service dispatched crews to one-third of them.
   Forest and brush fires broke out across Oregon on Tuesday during
record heat, including at least 20 fires caused by lightning, said
Doug Decker, a spokesman for the state Forestry Department. The
largest was a 200-acre fire at a logging operation 20 miles north
of Wallowa in northeastern Oregon.
   An airplane crashed Tuesday afternoon in the Malheur National
Forest in east-central Oregon, killing three people and starting a
forest fire, the Federal Aviation Administration said. No
information on the fire's size was available.
</TEXT>
