<DOCNO> AP880824-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0236EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Denmark-Mermaid     08-24 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Denmark-Mermaid,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little Mermaid Honored on 75th Birthday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUNILLA FARINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Little Mermaid, staring longingly
out to sea from her rocky perch in Copenhagen harbor, was honored
with a 21-gun salute and a laurel from the mayor as she turned 75.
   She has been beheaded, had an arm cut off, and suffered various
other indignities, but the bronze statue created in honor of writer
Hans Christian Andersen was treated like royalty at Tuesday's
celebration.
   Mayor Egon Weigekamp led the party, placing a wreath of flowers
around the neck of ``Den Lille Havfrue,'' as she is known in Danish.
   Children of 40 nationalities from the Copenhagen International
Junior School waved flags on the quay. Older visitors were offered
free beer by the brewery that financed the statue in 1913.
   The mermaid is one of Copenhagen's most popular attractions,
drawing about 500,000 visitors a year. Pouring rain kept Tuesday's
crowd down to about 100.
   The statue, which sits on a small rock outcropping at the
entrance to Copenhagen harbor, is based on Andersen's tale of the
daughter of the sea king who fell in love with a prince and was
doomed to wait 300 years before she could turn human.
   She leans on one hand, her fish tail stretched behind her, and
she is half turned toward the sea so visitors must strain to see
the wistful look on her face. She has often been used as a symbol
of Denmark, and anti-nuclear activists have depicted her as a
skeleton.
   Visitors often are surprised at her small stature _ about the
size of a small girl _ and artists have debated her artistic value.
   The mermaid was beheaded in 1963 and a new head was cast from
the original mold. The police department called on its homicide
division to handle the case, even though the squad was dealing with
16 unsolved murders. The head was never recovered.
   Twenty years later, hooligans amputated an arm, which also was
replaced. Grafitti and paint splotches are a recurring problem for
city cleaners.
   She was created by Edvard Eriksen, who took the face of Danish
ballerina Ellen Price and modeled her upper body from his wife.
   Eriksen, who lived from 1867 to 1959, attached little artistic
importance to the mermaid. He authorized the manufacture of about
50 half-sized replicas of his mermaid to be placed in public areas
around the world, including Salt Lake City, Stanford University in
California, San Francisco and Solvang, Calif.
   Eriksen's heirs reportedly earn royalties of about $750,000 a
year on trinkets and souvenir models.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880824-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SentencingGuidelines Bjt   08-24 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sentencing Guidelines, Bjt,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Guidelines Ruled Unconstitutional On Separation-Of-Powers
Grounds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. appeals court struck down new
guidelines establishing a range of sentences for federal crimes,
ruling the standards are unconstitutional because they were drafted
by judges as a political act.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, the highest court to rule
on the issue, said Tuesday that placing three federal judges on the
seven-member sentencing commission violated constitutional
separation of powers.
   In a 2-1 vote, the court decided the use of judges on the
commission interfered with the ``aura of judicial impartiality'' by
allowing the president to appoint and remove members, said the
opinion by Judge Alex Kozinski.
   ``Congress may not, under our system of separated powers,
require judges to serve on bodies that make political decisions,''
Kozinski said.
   The decision affects only the region covered by the 9th Circuit,
comprising nine Western states, Guam and the Northern Marianas.
However, the court is the nation's first on the appellate level to
rule on the validity of the guidelines.
   Other federal judges nationwide have issued numerous conflicting
rulings on challenges to the guidelines, mostly based on the
separation-of-powers issue.
   The guidelines were challenged by public defenders, who were
displeased with provisions that lengthened sentences for many
crimes and restricted judges' authority.
   The chairman of the sentencing commission, Judge William Wilkins
of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court in Appeals in Richmond, Va., said he
was disappointed by the ruling but added, ``We'll be having a
definitive and final answer from the U.S. Supreme Court real soon.''
   Wilkins, interviewed from Washington on Larry King's syndicated
radio talk show, said courts have decided about 200 cases based on
validity of the sentencing guidelines, with the rulings about
evenly divided.
   The Supreme Court has scheduled arguments on the issue for Oct.
5 in a Missouri case, he said.
   Tuesday's ruling on two consolidated challenges from San Diego
said the commission violated the constitutional limit on the role
of the judiciary because ``its function is political and not
judicial in nature.''
   Kozinski said the commission had to make rules and policies
having the force of law, ``tasks that only the legislative or
executive branches, and not the judiciary, may constitutionally
perform.''
   The guidelines, which took effect in November, recommend minimum
and maximum sentences for each crime, requiring the judge to state
unusual circumstances for imposing a sentence outside the range.
   The appeals court also found invalid the 1984 sentencing law
that created the Sentencing Commission and abolished parole in
post-November 1987 cases. Such a ruling would restore the entire
previous law, which generally gave judges wide-ranging sentencing
discretion and provided for parole eligibility after one-third of a
sentence.
   ``We're very happy with the guidelines being thrown out,'' said
Geoff Hansen, an assistant federal public defender in San
Francisco. ``We're just ecstatic that we don't have to deal with
this nightmare any more.''
   But he said lawyers will be ``in some state of uncertainty'' in
dealing with many recent cases, including some where the guidelines
helped individual defendants and others involving plea-bargains
based on the guidelines. The status of parole is also unclear, he
said.
   Kozinski said the commission's detailed rules on sentences for
each crime invade the executive and legislative policy-making roles
in many ways. For example, it said sentences for white-collar
crimes were too short, that all defendants except the poorest must
pay fines. The commission also refrained from issuing any
guidelines on the death penalty, he said.
   Kozinski said the decision on the death penalty, a 4-3 vote of
the commission, apparently resulted from a fear that controversy
over the issue might prevent congressional approval of the
guidelines.
   While the decision leaves the issue of capital punishment with
Congress, it illustrates that ``the commission's work was indeed
substantive and political, not procedural and impartial,'' he said.
   Judge Charles Wiggins, in dissent, said judges' participation in
a commission that drafted sentencing guidelines did not overstep
the boundaries of the judicial role or tarnish judicial
impartiality. He said Congress had set overall sentencing policies
and could properly leave their implementation to a commission that
included judges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880824-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonCondoms     08-24 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Condoms,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philadelphia Prison Board Turns Down Condom Distribution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of Philadelphia's AIDS program
says he'll push for distribution of condoms in city jails even
though the city prison board rejected the idea, saying it
encouraged homosexuality.
   ``I am totally confident they will change their minds,'' David
Fair, director of AIDS programs for the Health Department, said,
acknowledging that could take years.
   Meantime, Fair said, he will continue with an AIDS education
program for prisoners that encourages abstention.
   The board Monday night rejected the distribution program by 3-2,
with one abstention.
   Fair said the proposal would have made condoms available to
inmates on request _ not, as some board members thought, through
mass distribution.
   ``It makes me very sad,'' Fair said, noting that infected
prisoners can spread the deadly disease after release from jail.
``Somebody is getting infected with AIDS.''
   Board member M. Mark Mendel, a lawyer who strongly opposes
condom distribution, said the policy would have condoned
homosexuality in jails.
   ``This jail isn't a sex factory,'' he said. ``It isn't a place
to shoot up (drugs). This is not proper conduct.''
   During a two-hour discussion before the vote, Public Health
Commissioner Maurice C. Clifford urged approval of the policy,
saying sexual activity was rampant in the city's jails.
   ``We are not condoning sexual activity,'' Clifford said. ``We
are saying it is taking place ... and the best protection against
AIDS is using a condom.''
   Board member Allen Hornblum, who voted in favor of the
distribution, said the issue will not disappear as long as acquired
immune deficiency syndrome spreads.
   ``There will be more pressure to adopt condom distribution,''
Hornblum said.
   Hornblum said he knows of three other prison systems that have
programs allowing distribution of condoms: in Vermont, Mississippi
and New York City.
   Fair said eight prisoners in Philadelphia have been diagnosed as
having AIDS and two prisoners have died from the disease while in
custody.
   He said the number of prisoners infected with the AIDS virus is
hard to estimate, but could be more than half of the 3,700 in
custody.
</TEXT>
