<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Gdansk     08-24 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Gdansk,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Birthplace Braces For Hardships Of Strikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Poland, Bjt
^By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents in this Baltic port where
Solidarity was born stocked up on sugar, flour and bread, fearing
shortages during Poland's worst outbreak of labor unrest since 1981.
   ``I'm making sure I'm prepared,'' said one elderly woman.
   State-run media, in a campaign to erode public sympathy for the
striking workers, on Tuesday quoted factory workers as blaming the
strikers for long lines and shortages.
   ``We are scared by the lines in the stores,'' Warsaw Radio
quoted a textile worker in Lodz as saying. ``Poland went through a
very hard time in 1980 and we should have learned from this.''
   Goods were in short supply during the tide of strikes eight
years ago the spawned Solidarity, the only independent labor
federation ever allowed in the Soviet bloc.
   Although there was no evidence of panic-buying in Gdansk stores,
residents said many people had rushed out to buy basic staples
early Tuesday.
   But the stores were later restocked and even supplies of scarce
commodities turned up on store shelves after a long absence,
residents said.
   ``Now you can get cheese and ham,'' said a 20-year-old native of
the country's largest port. ``They have been in short supply or
missing for two months.''
   The government pledged to increase distribution of staples and
other goods during the strikes, which began Aug. 16 and seek higher
wages and reinstatement of Solidarity, which was outlawed after
being crushed in a December 1981 military crackdown.
   The government contends Solidarity activists are exploiting
Poland's economic woes and strikes are creating unnecessary
hardships for citizens.
   Residents of Gdansk, where strikes have idled the port and the
Lenin shipyard, expressed surprise at the announcement Monday night
by Interior Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak empowering officials to
impose curfews in areas hit hard by strikes.
   ``People were surprised by the curfew announcement because the
media have only reported that there were rallies, and no strikes in
Gdansk,'' said one young resident.
   The radio quoted a worker who said he approved of Kiszczak's
curfew order.
   ``The only criticism I have is that it should have come
earlier,'' the worker said.
   Strikers at the Lenin shipyard, where Solidarity was founded,
said the threat of curfews was meant to intimidate strikers and
their families and scare the population into turning against them.
   ``We are not afraid,'' said an 18-year-old worker at the yard.
   Most doubted a curfew would be imposed in the city.
   ``We have thousands of tourists here,'' said a resident. ``How
do you think a busload of German tourists is going to react when
you tell them to be in by 9 p.m.?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
