<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Valentino Memorial,0119</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fans Mark Death of Silent Film Star</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rudolph Valentino, the silent film idol who
died 62 years ago, was remembered by a few dozen people who
gathered at his crypt.
   Valentino was eulogized Tuesday by actor Joe Wagstaff as a man
``whose strength of personality transcends time and decay.''
   The Italian-born actor was 31 when he died Aug. 23, 1926, in New
York of a perforated ulcer.
   Thousands, especially his female fans, mourned his death, and
for years the anniversary drew large crowds to his crypt at
Hollywood Memorial Park.
   Among Valentino's films were ``The Sheik,'' ``The Four Horsemen
of the Apocalypse,'' ``Blood and Sand'' and ``Monsieur Beaucaire.''
