<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Honduras-Contras     08-24 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras-Contras,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras: Contras Will Be Restricted To Border Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will restrict to a
border area Contra rebels who have in the past four months entered
the country in a mass exodus from Nicaragua, the foreign minister
said.
   The government is keeping the rebels near the Nicaraguan border
to prevent instability in Honduras, Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez
Contreras said Tuesday.
   Contra officials have said more than 14,000 rebels and civilian
supporters of their campaign against Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista
leaders entered Honduras in the past four months, seeking refuge
and humanitarian aid distributed by the United States.
   Lopez Contreras said Honduras was allowing the U.S. aid to reach
the Contras as part of the peace plan signed last year by five
Central American presidents.
   He said the Contras cross the frontier frequently because, under
the plan, they were to be assigned to a zone in Nicaragua that
borders Honduras. But he acknowledged that some Contras were
``entering Honduras as refugees, then later returning to their
country to fight.''
   Since 1981, the U.S.-supported rebels have maintained base camps
in Honduras in their fight to overthrow the Sandinistas. A
provisional cease-fire has been in effect in Nicaragua since March
21.
   Lopez Contreras noted that anti-communist rebels from Nicaragua
and leftist guerrillas from El Salvador have used frontier
territory for their war bases, damaging Honduras' social stability.
   He said the superpowers had created ``peculiar'' problems for
Honduras, with the United States supporting the Contras and the
Soviet bloc backing Nicaragua's Sandinista government and the
Salvadoran rebels.
   There have been several anti-American demonstrations this year
in Honduras, which is considered one of Washington's strongest
allies in the region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
