<HEAD>Congressmen Urge New Rules On Defense Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven senior members of the House Armed
Services Committee want the Pentagon to add provisions in future
defense contracts to ensure that any illegally gained profits can
be recovered by the government.
   The call arises from the current investigation into allegations
that private consultants illegally bought information about future
contracts from Pentagon employees.
   ``There is an urgent need to protect both the national security
and the interests of the U.S. taxpayer in defense procurement,''
the congressmen said in a statement issued Tuesday.
   ``A clause in all future contracts allowing the Defense
Department to recover the profit from illegally obtained contracts
would go a long way toward doing that,'' it said.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and other top Pentagon
officials have said the Pentagon can use existing laws to recover
the profits if any of the contracts involved in the investigation
turned out to have been won on the basis of illegal information.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>School Costs: $4,810 Per Pupil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Education says the cost of
sending America's children to public elementary and secondary
schools is expected to be $4,810 this year, up more than $2,000
since 1980.
   The new estimate puts spending on education well ahead of
inflation in this decade, department statistics released Tuesday
show.
   The $2,762 per pupil spending of the 1980-81 school year would
have risen to $3,462, if simply adjusted for inflation. Yet the
department expects spending to top that by nearly 39 percent.
   Increased spending by state and local governments in an effort
to improve schools was cited by statistician Vance Grant as a major
reason for spending being ahead of inflation.
   Overall, the agency expects education spending at all levels,
public and private, to rise to $328 billion for the coming school
year, a record. That is up from $308.8 billion last year and $182.8
billion in 1980-81.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Administration Accused of Using `Excuse' To Break ABM Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the private Arms Control
Association says the Reagan administration is using a disputed
Soviet radar facility in Siberia as an excuse to undercut the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
   A five-year review of compliance with the treaty, which
restricts U.S. and Soviet anti-missile defenses, opens on Wednesday
in Geneva.
   President Reagan has authorized American negotiators to accuse
the Soviets of a ``material breach'' of the pact with the radar
facility at Krasnoyarsk. Such a charge would give the United States
the right to break out of the treaty.
   Spurgeon Keeny, who heads the Arms Control Association, said
Tuesday he agrees the facility violates the treaty. But, he said,
``a material breach can only be claimed by a country seeking an
excuse to suspend or terminate the ABM treaty.''
   Keeny, a former deputy director of the U.S. Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency, said ``it may set in motion a series of events
that could have a very serious impact.''
</TEXT>
