<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-24 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Fall; Dollar Rises On Tokyo Markets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell, while the dollar gained against
the Japanese yen in Tokyo trading Wednesday.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
159.23 points Tuesday, closed at 27,799.67 for a loss of 120.28
points, or 0.43 percent.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar, which jumped over
the 134-yen level to start the day at 134.25 yen, closed at 134.30
yen, up 0.37 yen from Tuesday's close.
   The dollar was stronger despite of dollar-selling by the U.S.
central bank and several European banks aimed at curbing the
currency's recent rise, exchange dealers said.
   ``The yen's value fell because investors here sold yen to buy
government bonds, which led the dollar to jump up this morning,''
said a dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Traders at the Tokyo Stock Exchange said the market remained in
a wait-and-see mood following the Nikkei index's 159.23-point loss
on Tuesday.
   Some traders said the Tokyo markets were awaiting a scheduled
meeting Thursday of the West German Federal Reserve Bank, in light
of the mark's recent weakness against the dollar.
   ``Until investors find out what happens to interest rates in
West German banks on Aug. 25, the stock market is unlikely to be
active,'' the dealer said.
</TEXT>
