<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PreachingKids     08-24 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Preaching Kids,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Preaching Children May Attend School At Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: note language in grafs 10, 16, and final grafs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three siblings whose parents have fought
with school officials since spring because the children were not
allowed to preach at the school gates will be taught at home, a
mediator says.
   ``We pretty much got what everybody wanted,'' said Dan Rodden,
president of Caleb Campaign of Chicago, a non-profit Christian
rights organization negotiating with school officials on the
family's behalf.
   Rodden said Tuesday that David and Robin Strode of McDowell
County had signed a statement asking that their children be removed
from Eastfield Elementary School and be taught at home.
   But the county school superintendent, David Ricketts, said he
was not sure an agreement had been reached.
   Who would teach the children and what arrangements would be made
were not disclosed to reporters. Strode, who is unemployed, said
his family could not afford to hire a teacher or to pay for at-home
instruction.
   Rodden said his organization would help with the education and
even help the 40-year-old Strode find a job.
   On Monday, the children's first day of school lasted less than a
minute, ending with 11-year-old Duffey being suspended for 10 days.
   Duffey, and his 6-year-old brother, Matthew, began shouting
Bible verses while at the gate and their 7-year-old sister, Pepper,
yelled ``Repent.''
   ``We were there to welcome them to school,'' said Eastwood
Principal Jim Gorst.
   ``Duffey stuck his Bible in my face and he said, `You go to
hell.'''
   The Strodes did not meet with school officials Tuesday but
allowed Rodden to shuttle between the school and the Strode home 1{
blocks away for negotiations.
   Richard Schwartz, an attorney for the North Carolina School
Boards Association, said he hoped to reach an agreement that would
result in both sides waiving the right to future litigation.
   Rodden, the superintendent and Schwartz met with Eastfield
Elementary Assistant Principal Shirley Ramsey and Assistant
Superintendent Shearon Crawford.Further meetings were planned for
today.
   Tuesday morning, Rodden said, he was ``working to save the
marriage'' between the children and the school. But by noon, he
said, ``I realized the marriage was unsavable and we went for a
divorce.''
   Although Rodden said the agreement satisfied everyone, Strode
left the house late in the day with his eyes red, apparently from
crying.
   ``As the world builds bigger and better schools and bigger and
better churches, the children are going to hell by the thousands,''
he said before turning away.
   The children were suspended repeatedly last spring when they
stood behind the school screaming Bible verses and refusing to
enter the building when asked.
   Their favorite verse is Hebrews 13:4: ``Marriage is honorable in
all and the bed undefiled. But whoremongers and fornicators God
will judge.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
