<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PLO-Israel     08-24 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-Israel,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat: PLO Will Pay Salaries Of Those Laid Off By Jordan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO says it will pay the salaries of
the more than 20,000 educational, health and administrative workers
in Israel's occupied lands who Jordan says it will no longer pay.
   But PLO leader Yasser Arafat, in a statement Tuesday, did not
say where the salaries would come from or how they would be paid.
   Jordan early this month announced it was letting go the 21,200
employees in phases, gradually eliminating payment of about $45
million in salaries a year.
   King Hussein said his decision to abandon his claim to the
occupied West Bank and to sever financial links with the Gaza Strip
was aimed at giving greater responsibilities to the PLO.
   ``The PLO shall shoulder full responsibility for the employees
and workers as regards rights entitled to them, salaries and wages,
on the basis of the regulations and lists of their appointments to
office,'' Arafat said in the statement, which was made available by
the PLO office in Nicosia.
   The statement was referring to the Jordanian government salary
scale, used to pay many of the employees who worked in schools,
hospitals, government offices and other institutions.
   Although Jordan laid off or retired the employees, Arafat said
they would remain in their current positions.
   The statement added that ``all law and regulations in force in
the occupied territories shall remain in force until such time as
they are amended or abrogated by the Palestinian legislative
authorities.''
   It did not elaborate. The PLO has been debating the possible
formation of a provisional government or government-in-exile for
the territories.
   In addition to severing administrative links to the territories,
Hussein canceled a $1.3 billion development plan for the
territories and dissolved the lower house of Parliament, half of
whose members were Palestinians.
   Jordan later announced it would issue temporary two-year
passports for West Bank residents that would no longer confer
Jordanian citizenship but could be used as travel documents.
   Hussein has said the changes are in response to the PLO's desire
to ``secede'' and form its own state with its heart in the West
Bank. The occupied territories have been wracked by an 8{-month-old
uprising against Israeli rule.
   The PLO has substantial, although largely secret, financial
resources provided by Arab countries and the Palestinian diaspora
outside the Arab world.
   Israeli leaders have vowed to prevent the PLO from taking over
any of the salaries or services on the West Bank and in the Gaza
Strip.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
