<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     08-24 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Down, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange lost ground today for the
third consecutive day, while the U.S. dollar edged up in trading on
the foreign exchange market to close at 134.30 yen.
   The 225-share Nikkei Stock Average shed 120.28 points, or 0.43
percent, to end at 27,299.67. The main market indicator had lost
130.24 points on Monday and another 159.23 points Tuesday.
   Although the Nikkei average quickly gained 55.40 points in early
morning trading to reach 27,975.35 points, share prices fell toward
the end of the afternoon.
   ``Share prices today were lower across the board,'' said a
dealer at a major securities firm, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   ``In addition to the strong wait-and-see mood among investors,
the protectionist U.S. trade bill just reported Tuesday led
investors to sell export-related issues, such as Toshiba and
Sony,'' he added.
   Other dealers said the stock market lacked energy because many
institutional investors were cautious ahead of West German banks'
scheduled decision on interest rates.
   Volume traded in the first section was 600 million shares, up
100 million shares from Tuesday.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar opened above the
134-yen level and never went lower. Opening at 134.25 yen, the U.S.
currency moved in a range of 134.17-134.70 yen to finish at 134.30,
up 0.37 yen from Tuesday's close.
</TEXT>
