<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea Wants Fourth Round Of Talks Friday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea wants to resume talks
Friday with North Korea on a non-aggression pact and on the north's
demand to co-host the Olympic Games, officials said today.
   The National Assembly made the announcement after its senior
delegate, Rep. Park Joon-kyu, held a private meeting with his North
Korean counterpart, Chon Kum Chol, at the truce village of
Panmunjom.
   Park refused to disclose details of the private meeting. He said
the south's decision on resuming talks would be relayed to the
north.
   Assembly officials were reluctant to say whether they believed
the deadlocked talks, which began Friday and collapsed Monday,
could be revived. But one senior official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said, ``Neither side wants to take the blame (for
breaking off the talks).''
   Although Park said he expected ``new proposals'' from North
Korea, he admitted he was not encouraged by North Korea's stand at
today's meeting.
   ``Isn't it meaningful that the talks would continue?'' he said
when asked about prospects of the upcoming meeting.
   Friday's meeting would be the fourth in talks between lawmakers
of the two Koreas on sharing the Olympics and various peace
measures, including a non-aggression pact.
   The talks ended in a stalemate on Monday, with both sides
failing to fix a date for further talks.
   South Korean delegates said after a third round of talks on
Monday that they hoped to postpone further contacts until after the
Olympics, scheduled for Sept. 17 through Oct. 2 in Seoul.
   North Korea called for urgent talks on the Olympics, but they
were not so enthusiastic in pursuing the subject. They seemed more
concerned about a non-aggression pact.
   In an effort to break the deadlock at Monday's meeting, South
Korea proposed a private meeting between the senior delegates of
the two sides. North Korea agreed to consider the suggesion.
   The talks were called to prepare for full-scale parliamentary
talks on North Korea's bid to co-host the Olympics, and on other
measures, including a non-aggression pact, to ease tension between
the nations.
   The two sides differed over an agenda and the size of the talks.
North Korea insists the main talks include the full legislatures of
both sides, involving nearly 1,000 members, but the south wants
delegations of up to 30 lawmakers from each side.
   North Korea also wants the two parliaments to publish a joint
declaration of non-aggression, which seeks, among other things, the
withdrawal of the 42,000 U.S. troops in South Korea and nuclear
weapons allegedly in their arsenal.
   The south sees the U.S. forces as vital to its defenses against
the communist north.
   North Korea said it will boycott the Olympics unless it can
co-host them. The International Olympic Committee has rejected the
North Korean demand, saying the Olympics are given to a single city
and cannot be shared.
   The two Koreas have been bitter rivals since their land was
divided at the end of World War II in 1945. They fought the Korean
War from 1950 to 1953.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
