<HEAD>Stars Shine At Emmy Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of television's new and old stars
celebrated 40 years of the prime time Emmy Awards, with the
festivities proving to be as much a party for NBC's celebrated
``L.A. Law.''
   Barbara Bain, Robert Cummings, George Gobel, Harvey Korman,
Edward James Olmos, Loretta Swit, John Ritter and Shelley Winters
were the former Emmy winners at Tuesday night's party.
   This year's awards presentation will be broadcast Sunday on the
Fox Television Network from 8 p.m. to 11 p.m. in the Eastern and
Pacific time zones.
   Nominees who attended the party included ``thirtysomething's''
Tim Busfield, Tim Reid of ``Frank's Place,'' Ann Jillian, star of
``The Ann Jillian Story,'' and Larry Drake, Alan Rachins and
Michael Tucker of ``L.A. Law,'' whose 19 nominations were the most
this year.
   Tucker, who was nominated along with co-star and real-life wife
Jill Eikenberry, said: ``It's very nice that both of us got the
nomination. ... It really saves on wear and tear on the homefront.''
   Ms. Jillian, who starred in a movie chronicling her battle with
breast cancer, said her nomination has ``been really exciting for
me. ... I'm very happy for the entire experience.''
   Miss Bain, winner of three Emmys for her role on the 1960s hit
series ``Mission: Impossible,'' said she was unhappy the program
was being revived for ABC's fall season. The show, which highlights
the adventures of a government covert action team, was brought back
as a replacement series caused by writers strike delays.
   ``I think it's unfortunate the way (the revival) came about,''
Bain said. ``I hope they do it well.''
</TEXT>
