<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hungary-Strike 1stLd-Writethru a0496 08-24 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary-Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0496,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miners Go On Strike in Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDds UPDATES thruout with details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 150 coal miners were on strike
in southern Hungary today, and many more miners were joining the
stoppage, official reports said. Reports on strikes in communist
Hungary are rare.
   The state news agency MTI said the stoppage near the town of
Pecs was over wages and had ``no political undertones.''
   It said a senior official from Budapest had gone to the Mecsek
coal mines near Pecs, just north of the Yugoslav border, to mediate
the dispute.
   The official, Laszlo Kapolyi, returned to Budapest today with
representatives from the miners' management and the work force to
negotiate with the government over wage grievances, MTI said.
   Laszlo Kovacs, head of the official mineworkers' union, was also
said to be taking part in the negotations. In media discussions in
recent months, he has criticized management of the mining industry.
   The relatively swift reporting of the stoppage appeared to
reflect the greater openness seen in the state-run media since
Karoly Grosz took over as Communist party leader and head of a
reform-minded Politburo in May.
   MTI said trouble started Tuesday evening when 150 miners refused
to start work on the evening shift. Budapest radio said ``many
more'' joined the strikers today, but it gave no numbers.
   The strikes came at a time of widespread labor unrest in Poland,
where coal miners, dockworkers and transit workers have gone on
strike to demand reinstatement of Solidarity, the only independent
labor federation ever allowed in the Soviet bloc.
   MTI said the workers in Pecs were complaining that the new
personal income tax introduced in Hungary on Jan. 1 has cut their
bonuses by up to one-third.
   ``It is especially irritating for the miners that miners on sick
leave often earn more than their colleagues on regular shifts,''
MTI said, describing this as ``another unwelcome byproduct of the
recently introduced personal income tax.''
   Radio Budapest said in its morning broadcast that miners were
also complaining that unspecified legitimate demands had not been
met ``for years'' and that other unspecified steps were taken
``over their heads.''
   The manager of the mine was said by the radio to have expressed
sympathy for the miners' grievances. One miner was quoted as
saying, ``We are seeking a solution of our problems. If that is
impossible, we accept the closure of the mine. But the present
situation must be changed.''
   Hungary's official trade unions have been highly critical of
recent economic policy, emphasizing that workers, pensioners and
the unemployed must be protected against price rises caused by
government efforts to curb the $18 billion foreign debt and
stimulate the stagnating economy.
   MTI said the mine management had promised to return to Pecs from
Budapest tonight to report on the outcome of negotiations in
Budapest with Industry Minister Frigyes Berecz and other government
officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880824-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0735EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Poland     08-24 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Poland,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Express Concern Over Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin says it is watching with concern the
situation in Poland, but it has not issued any official comment on
an 8-day-old strike wave in the Soviet Union's western neighbor.
   Soviet media today issued reports on a meeting of the Polish
Communist Party's Politburo, but offered no commentary.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov, at a regular
news briefing Tuesday, said, ``We closely follow the situation in
Poland.''
   ``We are, of course, very attentive and interested and we are
concerned by the events of Poland,'' he said.
   The Soviet news agency Tass quoted a statement by the Polish
Politburo saying that difficult living conditions and justified
criticism of authorities were not acceptable reasons for the
strikes plaguing the Soviet-bloc country.
   The strikes are the worst labor unrest in Poland since 1981,
when the Warsaw government stifled the Solidarity free trade union
movement with a military crackdown.
   ``Economic damage is piling up. Poland's prestige and economic
confidence in Poland in international relations suffered
substantially,'' the Tass report said of the current strikes.
   It reported that the Politburo approved a letter to party
members calling on them to counter the strikes.
   Asked if the strikes in Poland and protests Sunday in
Czechoslovakia on the 20th anniversary of the Soviet-led invasion
of that country helped Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
opponents find fault with his policy of greater openness, Gerasimov
said, ``I think you can find ammunition in any event.''
</TEXT>
