<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0900EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pakistan     08-24 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Tightened As Moslems Mark Holy Day A Week After Zia Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government tightened security in
several cities today to prevent sectarian strife among Moslems
observing a solemn holy day one week after the death of President
Mohammed Zia ul-Haq.
   Pakistan's Shiites, a Moslem sect that constitutes about 5
percent of the country's 107 million people, joined processions
through the streets of villages and cities to mourn the death of
the prophet Mohammed's grandson, Imam Hussain. Participants beat or
flog themselves to show devotion to the martyr.
   Sectarian friction between the Shiites and the majority Sunnis
typically increases on Ashoura, the holiday marking Imam Hussain's
death that concludes today. Hussain and a group of followers were
massacred in 680 in what is now the Iraqi province of Karbala in a
leadership fight between Moslem factions. Moslems later formed the
Shiite and Sunni sects of the faith.
   Since the assassination three weeks ago of a Shiite religious
leader in northwestern Pakistan, tension has increased between
Shiites and Sunnis, and authorities feared the observance could
lead to violence. Zia was a Sunni.
   In the southern port of Karachi, as many as 40,000 Shiites
marched through the main district in observance of the holiday.
   About 20,000 police, paramilitary units and army regulars
dressed in full battle gear lined the streets along the procession.
They drove vehicles mounted with machine guns and kept watch from
rooftops along the seven-mile route. No clashes were reported.
   About 30 people have died this year in Sunni-Shiite gunbattles
in northern Pakistan. New clashes were reported in the region after
Zia died Aug. 17 in a plane crash.
   The English-language newspaper The Muslim reported Tuesday that
at least 10 people died and 10 were injured the last few days in
Shiite-Sunni violence near Kohat, about 100 miles west of Islamabad.
   Pakistani officials say they believe Zia's plane crash was a
result of sabotage but have not said who they think is responsible.
Some officials have hinted at agents of Afghanistan's pro-Soviet
government.
   Pakistan, like the United States, supports the guerrillas trying
to overthrow the Afghan government.
   Opposition leader Benazir Bhutto said Tuesday that Pakistan's
intelligence services received information her life was in danger
following Zia's death.
   Ms. Bhutto, leader of the country's largest opposition party,
the Pakistan People's Party, said she was informed Tuesday that the
government had posted armed guards outside her home.
   ``They informed me that they had received some threats so they
wanted to post some guards,'' she said in an interview with The
Associated Press at her home in Karachi. ``They told my secretary,
`We used to follow her for intelligence purposes but now we'll
follow her to guard her.'''
   Ms. Bhutto said she had no other details.
   Ms. Bhutto said she was seeking to form alliances with other
opposition groups and reach agreements to prevent them competing
for the same National Assembly seats in Nov. 16 elections.
   She strongly criticized the current Cabinet, calling the
ministers ``dangerous'' holdovers from Zia's regime. Thirteen of
the 16 ministers were appointed by Zia.
   She called on new President Ishaq Khan to appoint a caretaker
government until elections. She expressed confidence that if
elections were conducted fairly she would win.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
