<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TreasureFind     08-24 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasure Find,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Galleon Yields 900 Silver Coins, Gold Rings, Artifacts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Bleth is cq in penultimate graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEBASTIAN, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A treasure-hunter who has spent three
years diving for riches from a Spanish galleon lost in a 1715
hurricane says a find of 900 silver coins has pointed him in the
direction of the mother lode.
   ``It was a very good sign as far as letting us know we're going
in the right direction. Who knows what's ahead now. We're very
excited about that,'' Roy Volker said Tuesday.
   The 63-year-old explorer from St. Louis hopes to find $200
million in gold that went down with the Nuestra Senora de la Regla,
the flagship of an eight-galleon fleet that left Vera Cruz, Mexico,
for Spain in July 1715.
   In addition to the coins, the ship yielded two gold rings, a
small silver statue of an angel holding a Christ child, several
shoe buckles, pottery and other artifacts.
   Volker estimated the value of the find, his largest, at
$250,000. However, a spokeswoman for treasure hunter Mel Fisher,
who owns the wreck, said the coins alone could be worth $400 to
$500 each, for a total of between $360,000 and $450,000.
   Twenty percent of the treasure and artifacts will go to the
state and an undisclosed percentage to Fisher.
   ``We've been expecting to find a pretty good, sizable pile of
coins somewhere along the line,'' said Volker, who made the find a
few hundred yards off Sebastian Inlet.
   ``We know there's a lot of treasure on the ship that's never
been found,'' he added.
   Carrying a cargo of treasure for the Spanish crown, the ships
were struck by a hurricane and sank along the central Atlantic
coast of Florida, killing 700 people.
   The Regla was smashed and its treasure strewn along the sandy
coast and buried by subsequent storms and tides, making its
discovery difficult, said Bleth McHaley, spokeswoman for Fisher's
company.
   Between 1964 and 1970, Fisher and his partners took about $20
million in treasure from the site, Ms. McHaley said.
</TEXT>
