<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Cugat     08-24 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Cugat,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Band Leader Xavier Cugat Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Band leader Xavier Cugat was
hospitalized today for heart and respiratory problems, his doctor
said.
   Quiron Clinic spokeswoman Inmaculada Cuenca said the 88-year-old
Spanish-born musician, who is credited with introducing tropical
rhythms into American dance music, was awake and talking in his
hospital bed.
   She said doctors had placed him in an intensive care unit but
hoped to move him to a regular unit later today if his condition
continued to improve.
   When he arrived at the hospital emergency room, Cugat told
doctors he was having difficulty breathing, Ms. Cuenca said.
   In his report, Dr. Jorge Ruis said the band leader was suffering
from ``a problem in the left ventricle probably secondary to a
respiratory infection.''
   Cugat and his family left his native Gerona, north of Barcelona,
for Cuba when he was four. He later became a U.S. citizen.
   The band leader gave up a 50-year band career in 1970 and handed
over his orchestra to Tito Puente.
   Ten years later, Cugat returned to Spain, where he was born Jan.
1, 1900. Since returning to the Barcelona area, Cugat has suffered
four heart attacks and a severe stroke. He was hospitalized in
February for lung congestion.
</TEXT>
