<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   08-24 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0501,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Demolishes Three Palestinian Homes; Israel Rejects U.S.
Criticism</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Shamir meeting with U.S.
ambassador. Pick up 5th pvs, `The Haaretz...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JELAZOUN, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army today demolished
three homes belonging to Palestinians who allegedly killed an Arab
collaborator and Israel sharply rejected U.S. criticism of its
deportation policy.
   Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip began a
two-day general strike to protest the deaths of four Arabs in
Israeli prisons.
   John Whitehead, the U.S. deputy secretary of state, urged Israel
to reconsider its policy of deporting Palestinian activists and
said continued expulsions would damage relations between the two
countries.
   The Israeli Foreign Ministry today responded: ``Israel does not
accept the American interpretation of international law regarding
deportations. ... The legality of deportations was checked recently
by Israel's Supreme Court, which ruled that deportations are legal,
according to both Israeli and international law.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir also explained Israel's policy on
deportations in a 90-minute meeting today with U.S. Ambassador
Thomas Pickering, said Shamir's spokesman Avi Pazner.
   Pickering refused to answer reporters' questions about the
meeting, and Pazner refused to elaborate.
   Israel has deported 33 Palestinians since the Palestinian
uprising began Dec. 8. Last week, 25 more were ordered expelled.
   Whitehead's statement marked the first time the U.S. has warned
that Israel's policies in the territories could threaten relations.
   The Haaretz and Jerusalem Post dailies said Whitehead spoke to
Israeli Charge d'Affaires Oded Eran in a meeting in Washington
Tuesday. An Israeli source in Washington confirmed the meeting.
   ``Whitehead's statement was sharp. I don't see it as an
ultimatum, but they definitely want us to stop the deportations,''
former Foreign Ministry director David Kimche told army radio.
   Israel has said it uses the measure ``only as a last resort''
and calls it an acceptable means of deterring violence.
   The latest strike was called in a leaflet issued Tuesday by
pro-PLO underground leaders of the uprising, who also urged
solidarity with 5,000 Arab prisoners and detainees in Israeli jails.
   In Jelazoun, a refugee camp of 5,000 north of Jerusalem,
soldiers ordered a curfew after destroying homes belonging to three
alleged members of grassroots committees that Israel outlawed last
week.
   The three allegedly beat an Arab youth to death while
interrogating him about suspected collaboration with Israel.
   An AP reporter saw two army jeeps blocking the entrance of the
camp. The streets were virtually empty.
   The pre-dawn demolition came several hours before 14 U.S.
Congressional aides were scheduled to visit the camp on a tour
organized by the Arab-American Anti-Discrimination Committee.
   In the West Bank town of Jenin, soldiers rounded up six
Palestinians suspected of belonging to the Palestine Liberation
Organization's mainstream Fatah faction, the army said.
   The suspects were accused of hurling three firebombs at Israeli
and Arab targets and throwing an explosive at an Israeli bus, the
army said. A bomb with a chemical charge was found in their
possession, it said.
   The general strike paralyzed transportation and commerce in at
least six major cities in the occupied West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
   In Hebron, Bethlehem and Gaza City, some Palestinians violated
the strike, the third in four days. Some shops were open and taxis
transported some workers to Israel.
   Masked Arab youths pelted rocks at some of the cars along a
five-mile strip connecting Bethlehem to Jerusalem.
   The latest strike was called to honor ``martyrs behind bars,''
including two Palestinians shot to death in a prison riot last week
and two who the army and police said committed suicide within the
last month.
   Relatives said one of those said to have committed suicide,
Nadil Mustafa Beduah of east Jerusalem, had his teeth knocked out
and several ribs fractured before his death.
   At least 252 Palestinians and four Israelis have been killed in
the 8{-month-old uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip against
21 years of Israeli occupation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
