<DOCNO> AP880824-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0948EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OzoneSettlement     08-24 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ozone Settlement,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Reached for $700,000 Settlement of Ozone Pollution Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A foam producer has agreed to pay a record
$700,000 in civil penalties to settle what is believed to be the
first lawsuit in the nation filed by a state to stop emissions
suspected of depleting the ozone layer.
   Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon announced terms of
the settlement Tuesday and said the company, PI Inc. of Hyannis,
also agreed to end its emissions by year's end.
   The settlement must be approved by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court
handling PI's reorganization and by Superior Court, where the suit
was filed.
   The state accused PI with emitting 1,300 tons of
chlorofluorocarbons a year in violation of state regulations. CFCs
are a class of chemicals implicated in the decline of the ozone
layer that protects Earth from solar radiation.
   The compounds are manmade chemicals used to create plastic
foams, for cleaning electronic parts and for refrigeration. The
chemicals were also used as propellants in aerosol cans until
banned by the federal government in 1978.
   ``Our action demonstrates that we can make a difference in
protecting the Earth's fragile environment,'' Shannon said. ``CFCs
have been directly linked to the destruction of the ozone layer and
consequently pose a threat to the Earth's survival.''
   The attorney general's office found no record of any other state
filing such a suit, said Shannon spokeswoman Mary Breslauer.
   Telephone calls to PI's president and attorney were not
immediately returned.
   Shortly before the attorney general filed suit in June, PI filed
for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal
bankruptcy code. According to news accounts, the company's insurer
had become insolvent, leaving PI with no protection from numerous
product liability suits.
   Daniel Greenbaum, commissioner of the state's top environmental
enforcement agency, said the resolution marks the first success by
the state Department of Environmental Quality Engineering in its
effort to stop unregulated emissions of CFCs.
</TEXT>
