<DOCNO> AP880824-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0959EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Phelan     08-24 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Phelan,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Board Chief Wants International Rules for Insider Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: A version on the financial wire</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Stock Exchange Chairman John Phelan today
called for common rules and definitions of insider trading among
world stock markets.
   Different rules and definitions of illegal dealing is hindering
control of unscrupulous trading practices in the increasingly
borderless equity markets worldwide, the chief of the leading U.S.
exchange told reporters.
   ``Everybody comes from different culture and corporate
background. But the users of those markets have to see those
markets are fair and that they are not disadvantaged to work in
them,'' Phelan said at the Foreign Correspondent Club of Japan.
   He urged each market to spell out its definition of insider
trading, then work together to set up common rules.
   ``Within the market place, everybody talks the same language.
But if it is perceived by any major participant that the market is
unfair, there will be a lack of use of the market and that will be
detrimental to everybody.''
   Phelan criticized the Japanese approach as ``a narrow
interpretation,'' but he declined to assess recent measures by
Japanese securities authorities. ``Their needs are different from
our needs,'' he said.
   Several cases of what Western finance experts charge are insider
trading deals _ buying and selling securities based on information
not available to all _ are raising questions in Japan's financial
community about the ethics of Japanese stock deals.
   In the most prominent case, several politicians' aides and
senior journalists admitted buying stock of a real estate concern
before the issues were made public, and making huge profits by
selling the shares after they were listed.
</TEXT>
