<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Bomb,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hamburger Restaurant Chain Hit By Another Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded outside a
Wimpy hamburger restaurant today, causing minor damage but no
injuries, police said.
   Three other Wimpy restaurants have been bombed since 1986,
including one on Tuesday.
   Police said the latest blast, in the farming and mining town of
Standerton east of Johannesburg, was caused by a limpet mine placed
in a travel bag. Officers were alerted by a passer-by and moved the
bag away from the restaurant into the middle of a cordoned-off
street before it exploded, police said.
   On Tuesday, 23 people were hurt when a limpet mine exploded at a
Wimpy restaurant in the coastal city of East London. A Wimpy outlet
in Johannesburg was bombed in June 1986 and one in nearby Benoni
was bombed last month.
   Police have blamed the attacks, as well as other recent
bombings, on the outlawed African National Congress guerrilla
movement. The ANC said last week that some civilian targets had
been attacked by guerrillas acting against instructions to hit only
government-related facilities.
   There has been no public explanation why Wimpy restaurants have
become a repeated target of bombs.
   The company's managing director, Vincent Hays, said after
Tuesday's bombing that police had been asked to help improve
security at the restaurants.
