<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Baltics 1stLd-Writethru a0451 08-24 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baltics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Newspaper Details Baltic Accord After Massive Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with Soviet newspaper detailing accord that led
to Baltic takeover. Incorporates correction a0481. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the Soviet Union's largest newspapers today
detailed an accord that led to the 1940 takeover of three Baltic
republics. The report appeared one day after hundreds of thousands
of residents protested the pact.
   The full-page article in Sovietskaya Rossiya, the newspaper of
the Russian republic, provided the first opportunity for many
Soviets to learn details of the agreement between Nazi Germany and
the Soviet Union.
   In the last two weeks, papers in the Baltic republics of
Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia also have published details of the
agreement, and on Tuesday people jammed parks and public squares to
mark the 49th anniversary of its signing.
   Many Baltic people are seeking greater independence from Moscow
for their relatively advanced and westward-looking economies, and
some radicals are agitating for independence.
   The small countries were independent after the Bolshevik
Revolution of 1917 until they were added to the Soviet Union in
1940.
   Lithuanian historian Robertas Zhyugzhda, writing in Sovietskaya
Rossiya of the developments in Lithuania, said Germany and the
Soviet Union violated principles of international relations and
that Josef Stalin's final contacts with the independent government
of Lithuania amounted to an ultimatum.
   But he said the Soviet Union's actions and concerns were
understandable in the tense atmosphere building up to World War II.
The pact signed Aug. 23, 1939, is commonly known as the
Ribbentrop-Molotov pact after German Foreign Minister Joachim Von
Ribbentrop and Soviet Foreign Minister Vyacheslav Molotov.
   Zhyugzhda revealed to Soviet readers that Estonia and Latvia
were assigned under the agreement to a Soviet sphere of influence
and that Lithuania originally was assigned to the German sphere.
   But in later negotiations after Germany attacked Poland on Sept.
1, Lithuania was assigned to the Soviet sphere, which Zhyugzhda
said was ``a gross violation of international principles and
norms.''
   Aside from recent publications in the Baltic republics, today
was the first time the Soviet press told its readers about the
spheres of influence.
   Soviet officials say the non-aggression treaty with Germany gave
their country a vital two years to prepare for an attack by
Hitler's forces, which finally came in June 1941.
   The historian said Lithuania's government tried to reorient
itself toward Germany after signing a mutual assistance treaty with
the Soviet Union and that Stalin responded by demanding a change in
the Lithuanian government.
   ``From the point of view of normal diplomatic relations, such
demands took the character of direct interference in the internal
affairs of a sovereign country,'' he said.
   Hundreds of thousands of people rallied in Estonia, Latvia and
Lithuania on Tuesday to demand greater autonomy on the anniversary
of the pact.
   Demonstrators waved the flags and sang the anthems of their
former nations and carried banners denouncing the secret agreement.
Authorities allowed the protests, and there were no reports of
violence or arrests.
   The demonstrations, unprecedented in size, were another
indication of foment in the area under Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
policies of greater openness.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, said in a report on the
gathering in the Estonian capital Tallinn, that historian Yuri
Afanasyev urged Estonians to cool their passion for independence.
Afanasyev, one of the most outspoken critics of Stalin, said:
``There might be various assessments of the 1939 pact, but one
cannot ignore present-day realities.''
   ``The reality is that the Estonian economy is so much
interconnected with the all-union economy that mechanical
separation will inevitably lead the republic to economic
disaster,'' Tass quoted him as saying.
   In a report from the Latvian capital Riga, Tass said city
officials had agreed to hoist the historic blue-and-white city flag
of Riga along with that of the Soviet Union and Soviet Latvia on
special occasions. The decision by Riga officals probably was meant
as a small concession to nationalist feelings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
