<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MspiKidnapping     08-24 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mspi Kidnapping,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Multimillionaire Receives Handwritten Note from Abducted Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A millionaire businessman whose ailing
wife was kidnapped a month ago paid a total of nearly $1 million to
12 people listed in the ransom note as having been wronged by him,
the FBI said.
   Robert Hearin paid the ransom a day after receiving a second
note, in his wife's handwriting, indicating for the first time
since the abduction July 26 that Annie Laurie Herrin is alive, said
Wayne Taylor, FBI agent in charge in Mississippi.
   At least one of the 12 returned the money, an attorney said.
   Mrs. Hearin, 72, suffers from an intestinal disorder that could
be fatal without daily medication.
   Taylor, who released the second letter Tuesday, said he wanted
to assure the woman's abductors that her husband ``has done
everything conceivably possible to meet their demands, considering
the vagueness of them.''
   Hearin had conferred with the FBI before deciding to pay the $1
million, Taylor said.
   Investigators have no leads in their search for the woman,
Taylor said.
   FBI analysis confirmed Mrs. Hearin wrote the letter dated Aug.
10; it was postmarked Aug. 12 and received at the Hearins' Jackson
home on Aug. 15, Taylor said.
   Taylor wouldn't disclose the city from which the letter was
mailed or discuss its contents other than to say ``it urged him
(Hearin) to comply with the demands of the kidnappers.''
   A vague note left at the Hearins' home the day of the kidnapping
demanded Hearin right alleged wrongs to 12 people. The 12 had been
sued by Hearin's company, School Pictures of Mississippi, for money
they allegedly owed.
   At a news conference, Taylor disclosed that Hearin paid the 12
nearly $1 million, which equals the court judgments against them.
   An attorney for N. Alfred Winn of St. Petersburg, Fla., said
Tuesday that Winn returned his check and wrote a letter saying he
hoped Hearin's wife would be returned safely.
   ``Mr. Winn has no dispute with Mr. Hearin,'' said attorney Joe
Donahey of Clearwater, Fla., who didn't disclose the amount of the
check.
   Hiram Johnson Stutts Jr. told The Clarion-Ledger that he
received a check for $17,800 and ``a nice letter'' from Hearin.
Stutts refused to say what he had done with his check.
   ``Mr. Hearin didn't owe me that much money. I settled mine out
of court for half of the amount. I was happy with the settlement,''
he said.
   Vic Hanneld of Oklahoma City also told the newspaper that he had
received a check and letter from Hearin but said he didn't want to
discuss it.
</TEXT>
