<HEAD>Execution Halted By State Supreme Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Buddy Roemer says he won't decide
whether to spare a condemned killer until the state Supreme Court
completes its review.
   Ronald Monroe, 33, had been scheduled to die in the electric
chair early Thursday for the 1977 stabbing death of a mother of two
but was granted a stay of execution Tuesday by the Louisiana
Supreme Court.
   Roemer said he would wait before acting on a Pardon Board
recommendation that Monroe's death sentence be commuted to life
imprisonment without parole. However, Roemer said Tuesday that he
was leaning against commutation.
