<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FerryRefloating     08-24 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ferry Refloating,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ohio Divers Work To Refloat The Ellis Island</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers working 15-hour days to raise a historic
ferry from the murky water off Ellis Island came close to their
goal before the deteriorated wreck sprang a leak and water rushed
back into the hull.
   The double-decker, which before its retirement carried 12
million immigrants to New York and New Jersey from Ellis Island,
had been pumped free of water and outfitted with pontoons Tuesday,
organizers said.
   ``We were going real well,'' said Naval Reserve Cmdr. Nick
Horney of Hudson, Ohio. ``Then a small portion of the deck
partially gave way. Over a period of years, it's just
deteriorated.''
   A series of Naval Reserve crews began working in April to
refloat the vessel, which began service in 1904 for what was then
the Bureau of Immigration, made its last run in 1954 and sank in
1968 while at dock.
   Bad weather forced another postponement today.
   ``We've been working very, very long hours for the past week and
a half,'' said Horney, commander of 17 Ohio divers who took on the
project as their annual, two-week tour of active duty. ``We need
something to occur to maintain the morale.''
   The 160-foot-long vessel could carry 1,000 immigrants in its
hold and was outfitted with a 12-bed sick bay and a padded cell for
violent mental patients.
   Named the Ellis Island after the site where immigrants to the
United States were once processed, the ferry is about 15 feet under
water at its lowest point. The starboard side juts out of the water
at low tide, mired in silt and mud.
   All that remains is its cast-iron hull.
   The National Park Service, which administers Ellis Island,
decided the wreck was a navigation hazard. The agency hasn't
decided what to do with the ferry but is dedicated to ``respecting
the ship's historical significance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
