<DOCNO> AP880824-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia-Stampede     08-24 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia-Stampede,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20 Hurt During Stampede On Bread Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers struggling to make ends meet
under Yugoslavia's rising inflation stampeded while waiting on line
to buy bread, and a newspaper said today that 20 people were
injured.
   The incident occurred in the town of Titov Veles in Macedonia,
Yugoslavia's southernmost province, the Vecernje Novosti daily in
Belgrade said.
   It did not say when the stampede occurred.
   Quoting the local newspaper, Nova Macedonia, Vecernje Novosti
said bakeries are told to make at least 60 percent of their
production cheaper varieties of bread but that many stores do not
follow this advice.
   As a result, ``many people ... wake up early in the morning to
form lines in front of bakeries'' to obtain the less expensive
loaves, the paper said.
   Southern Yugoslavia is the poorest part of the country, and many
people have to manage on wages that are the equivalent of $50 to
$100 a month. That is one-third to two-thirds of the average
Yugoslav income.
   Their task is made more difficult by 170 percent inflation.
   The International Monetary Fund, which is trying to help
Yugoslavia lower the inflation rate to 95 percent this year, says
stringent economic controls, including a ban on wage increases, are
necessary to win the fund's approval for rescheduling payment of
Yugoslavia's $21 billion debt.
  
</TEXT>
