<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Irish 4thLd-Writethru a0514 08-24 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0514,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs Injure Policemen, IRA Says It Will Step Up Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with arrests, IRA statement on bombing
techniques. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An IRA bomb hidden in a van
exploded today and hurled a passing patrol car across a road,
injuring two policemen. The blast followed an explosion in Belfast
that injured a pregnant woman.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility for
both attacks. The IRA also announced today it will step up its
attacks on commercial sites, in addition to British army targets.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary said this morning's bomb in
Maghera, about 40 miles northwest of Belfast, was planted in a van
parked on the side of the road.
   The blast lifted an armored police car into the air and hurled
it across the road, slightly injuring the two officers inside, said
a spokesman, who by custom was not identified. He said the officers
were treated at a hospital for cuts and bruises.
   Police said ``a number of people have been arrested for
questioning about serious terrorist crime.'' Police would not
elaborate.
   On Saturday, a bomb hidden in a vehicle parked on the side of a
highway near Omagh, about 30 miles from Maghera, exploded as a
British military bus was passing by. Eight British soldiers were
killed and 27 wounded.
   On Tuesday night, a bomb in a stolen car exploded near the Royal
Navy recruiting office in Belfast, slightly injuring a pregnant
woman and causing widespread damage to buildings, police reported.
   Police said those responsible for the attack had stolen the car
after bursting in on a children's party in west Belfast.
   While some assailants held five adults and four children hostage
in the house for several hours before releasing them unharmed,
others loaded the bomb aboard the family car and drove it to the
city center.
   Police said they received telephone warnings before the Tuesday
night blast and cleared the area of most residents.
   The explosion was on a side street near the recruiting office,
where Lt. Alan Shields had worked before being killed in an IRA
bombing on Monday. He died when an IRA bomb attached to his car
exploded as he drove into east Belfast.
   He was the 26th British military man to die this year in IRA
attacks, compared with three last year.
   The mostly Roman Catholic IRA has stepped up attacks recently in
its fight to end British rule in this Protestant-dominated province
and to unite it with the predominantly Catholic Irish Republic.
   British authorities say the IRA has acquired sophisticated new
explosives and detonators from Libya.
   ``It is our intention to begin using new devices in future car
bomb attacks against commercial and administrative property,
devices which will minimize the risk to the public,'' the IRA said
in a statement today.
   The statement unveiled a new car-bomb technique in which a smoke
grenade would go off before a blast, giving bystanders time to
flee. At the same time, a switch would be activated to immediately
set off the main charge if police attempted a controlled explosion
of the bomb.
   Tom King, secretary of state for Northern Ireland, said he
attributed the IRA's stepped-up violence to ``the fact that they've
received increased armaments in terms of explosives and weapons
from (Libyan leader Col. Moammar) Gadhafi.''
   King, in an interview on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,''
called the IRA ``a dedicated, vicious Marxist revolutionary group.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
