<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Submarine     08-24 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Submarine,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Chief Resigns After Sub Kills 30 Civilians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of Japan's military resigned today to
take responsibility for the deaths of 30 civilians killed when a
naval submarine crashed into a sport fishing vessel.
   ``I presented Prime Minister (Noboru) Takeshita with a notice of
resignation today, just now,'' Tsutomu Kawara said at a news
conference. ``Many innocent lives were lost in an extremely
regrettable accident ... in which the defense force was one of the
parties involved.''
   Kawara was the first Defense Agency director-general in 17 years
to relinquish his post in a controversy linked to the armed forces.
   Only 18 of the 48 passengers on board survived when their
fishing boat, the 154-ton No. 1 Fujimaru, collided with the
submarine Nadashio in Tokyo Bay on July 23.
   Public outrage flared when televised reports, backed by
survivors' accounts, showed the submarine's crew standing by as
people drowned.
   Kawara, speaking slowly and fighting back tears, urged his
successor to work to restore public confidence in the military.
   ``There have been a large number of incidents involving the
Defense Agency and it is my hope that under the new
director-general ... this problem will be dealt with.''
   Kawara's 10-month term as agency head was marred by accidents
involving the military, which even in the best of times is
unpopular. So far this year, eight ships and three planes were
involved in 11 military accidents, and two pilots were killed.
   Takeshita appointed Kichiro Tazawa, 70, the new Defense Agency
chief.
   Tazawa said at a televised press conference that he was taking
his new responsibility ``under very difficult circumstances.'' He
praised his predecessor's moves to investigate the submarine
collision and said his main goal was implementing measures to
prevent accidents.
   Takeshita, attending a memorial service for the 30 victims
today, also said the government would take steps to prevent
maritime accidents and promised compensation for the victims'
families.
   Kawara, 51, reportedly turned down the resignations of two other
defense officials _ Seiiki Nishihiro, deputy Defense Agency head,
and Adm. Shuichiro Higashiyama, chief of staff of the Maritime
Self-Defense Forces.
   In Japan it is customary for high-ranking business executives or
government officials to assume responsibility for a major incident
and step down from their posts in an attempt to restore public
confidence in the institution they represent.
</TEXT>
