<HEAD>Democratic VP Nominee Attacks Quayle's Voting Record</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Bentsen comments today; pick up 5th graf
pvs bgng ``The senator's...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd
Bentsen today criticized his Republican opponent as inexperienced
and young, saying ``I don't think America can risk'' having Dan
Quayle a heartbeat away from the presidency.
   Bentsen, who has shied away from attacking his Senate colleague,
dropped his reticence before the Southern Legislative Conference, a
bipartisan lawmakers' group that Quayle will also address later
today.
   Bentsen said he was surprised when Quayle, the Indiana senator
and GOP vice presidential nominee, suddenly announced his support
for making the Veterans Administration a cabinet-level agency.
   Quayle was one of only 11 senators to oppose the bill, but
before the Veterans of Foreign Wars on Monday night he ``made a
deathbed conversion,'' Bentsen said.
   Quayle told the VFW his vote against the bill was a ``youthful
indiscretion.''
   ``A youthful indiscretion? My friends, that vote occurred only
five weeks ago,'' Bentsen said.
   ``I don't think America can risk youthful indiscretion in
someone who could become our president at any moment,'' the
67-year-old Texan said of his 41-year-old opponent.
   Bentsen has been touring the South in a campaign to sell running
mate Michael Dukakis to Southerners skeptical of the Massachusetts
governor, and more of that was expected in today's speech.
   The senator's staff said he would stick to the theme he used
before a pair of union audiences on Tuesday, when he hit Quayle and
Vice President George Bush on specific issues and steered clear of
personal attacks and the controversies surrounding Quayle. ``It's
not his style to pile it on,'' said one staff member.
   Instead, the senator planned to hammer away at Quayle's voting
record.
   Bentsen attacked Quayle on Tuesday for fighting against the new
law requiring 60' days notice for plant closings.
   Quayle ``fought it tooth and toenail,'' Bentsen told a clearly
friendly crowd of some 500 members of the United Auto Workers who
packed a meeting hall in Taylor, Mich.
   ``I know in some years past some Democrats went off and voted
for Ronald Reagan,'' Bentsen told them, eliciting boos of
disapproval and then cheers when he said, ``Well, I'm telling you,
come on home.''
   Bentsen also chided Quayle on Tuesday for suddenly deciding to
support the bill creating a Cabinet-level veterans' department.
Quayle announced his support for the legislation at his speech
before the Veterans of Foreign Wars on Monday night. Quayle
attributed his earlier opposition to ``youthful indiscretion.''
   ``That was just a month ago,'' when Quayle voted against it on
the Senate floor, Bentsen said.
   One of the goals of the week, which will include Bentsen's own
speech to the VFW on Thursday, is to show that ``Republicans don't
have proprietary rights over patriotism,'' said Joe O'Neill, one of
Bentsen's top aides.
   In addition to his open campaign schedule, Bentsen's days have a
liberal sprinkling of private fund-raisers, including a
$1,000-a-person event at a private home in the ritzy Bloomfield
Hills suburb of Detroit on Monday night.
</TEXT>
