<2ND_LINE>PM-Bolivia-Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0547,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight Climbers Missing After Attack</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with quotes and details. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed men attacked a base camp of nine
French, Canadian and Bolivian climbers high in the Andes near the
Peruvian border, and eight climbers were missing today, officials
said.
   ``The first information indicates that it is a group linked to
the Peruvian Shining Path guerrillas,'' said Jorge Alderete
Rosales, Bolivia's undersecretary of the interior.
   Bernardo Guarachi, a Bolivian guide who was with the climbers
and escaped to La Paz, said Tuesday that 16 men carried out the
attack Monday on the camp about 15,000 feet above sea level. He
said he heard shots fired but did not see any victims before
escaping down a glacier.
   The Shining Path, which splintered off from the Peruvian
Communist Party 10 years ago, seeks to overthrow the Peruvian
government and set up a Marxist state. The Peruvian government has
said that since the group turned from propaganda to violence in May
1980, it has killed more than 15,000 people and caused more than
$10 billion in damage.
   Guarachi, an experienced climber, said the guerrillas used
walkie-talkies and that five wore khaki uniforms. He said the men
made references to a Peruvian when they surrounded the camp, but he
did not elaborate.
   Bolivian air force planes and helicopters today flew over the
snow-covered mountains about 50 miles north of La Paz. Police said
the aircraft found the camp but no evidence of the mountaineers.
   Guerrillas previously had not been reported operating in the
Bolivian Andean region. The camp is surrounded by snow and mountain
peaks, and no people live nearby.
   An American who was at a lower base camp and unaware of the
attack returned to La Paz on Tuesday after the other climbers
failed to show up. His name was not immediately available.
   One of the Canadians was identified as Victor Ballom of Toronto.
Officials did not release the names of the five Frenchmen and two
Bolivians with the group.
   The travel agency Paititi, which handled the expedition, said
the Frenchmen and Canadians were experienced mountaineers. Guarachi
and the other Bolivians worked for Paititi.
</TEXT>
