<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Netherlands-Apartheid     08-24 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Netherlands-Apartheid,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dutch Anti-Apartheid Activist Gets Five-Year Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch activist was sentenced to
five years in prison today for setting fire to two supermarkets and
a Shell service station to protest South Africa's apartheid policy.
   Rene Roemersma argued that he was acting in defense of South
Africa's 25 million blacks by setting fire to the facilities of
Dutch firms doing business in that country. But the court ruled
that no political motives were sufficient to justify such crimes.
   The attacks could ``easily have caused casualties,'' the court
said in sentencing the 30-year-old protester. They also caused
millions of dollars worth of damage.
   The fires at the two MAKRO supermarkets in Duiven and
Duivendrecht prompted the owner of the stores to sell its South
African factories. The firm that owned the markets, the SHV trading
company, complained publicly that the Dutch government could no
longer guarantee the safety of its stores.
   Although Roemersma never admitted to membership, a group called
Revolutionary Anti-Racist Action, or RARA, claimed responsibility
for each of the attacks for which he was convicted.
   They were among a spate of attacks by RARA, an acronym meaning
``Guess Who?'' in Dutch. All occurred in the pre-dawn hours when
few or no people were on the premises.
   RARA targeted a dozen Shell service stations across the nation
for arson and other vandalism to protest the Dutch-British oil
giant's operations in South Africa. The group claimed
responsibility for attacks on three MAKRO stores. Roemersma was
convicted in one of the gas station attacks.
   On April 11, police arrested eight RARA suspects after an
investigation by a special task force assigned to the attacks. They
released seven for lack of evidence within days. So only Roemersma
remained to stand trial.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in South Africa in which blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
