<2ND_LINE>PM-Rocket Contract,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Asks for Proposals for $1.2 Billion Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The space agency has invited proposals from
industry for a $1.2 billion project to design, develop and test the
next generation of booster rockets for the space shuttle.
   Firms have 60 days to submit their proposals.
   The first of the new rockets are to be placed into service in
1994, to be phased in over a three-year period. The contract award
is expected early next year.
   A total of $1 billion is for design and developing the boosters
and delivering six flight sets. An additional $200 million to $300
million is for construction of facilities on government-owned sites
at Yellow Creek, Miss., and NASA's Stennis Space Center near Bay
St. Louis, Miss.
   Five firms had study contracts for design and definition studies
for the rockets. One, Morton Thiokol, Inc., said it will not
compete for the contract. Thiokol, which makes all current shuttle
booster, will abandon that field when it delivers the last of the
redesigned rockets in the mid-1990s.
   The other firms are Aerojet Solid Propulsion Co., Sacramento,
Calif.; Atlantic Research Corp., Alexandria, Va.; Hercules
Aerospace Co., Salt Lake City, and United Technologies Chemical
Systems Divsion, San Jose, Calif.
</TEXT>
