<HEAD>More Than 10,000 No-Shows For Army Drill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When China's army calls, its soldiers don't
always show up.
   The official Liberation Army Daily said today that when 50,000
reservists were told to assemble for an emergency exercise within
three days, 11,500 of them failed to arrive.
   The three-day mock battle in northwest China's Gansu province
last week was China's first province-wide mobilization maneuver of
reserve forces under simulated battle conditions, the paper said.
   The report did not say whether one-quarter of the reservists
called had been unable to find transport or simply ignored the
order.
   Two days after Vice Governor Mu Yongji issued the order, 300 of
the 1,342 reservists in Tianshui prefecture were still hundreds of
miles away in the neighboring provinces of Shaanxi, Qinghai,
Ningxia and Henan, the paper said.
   Provincial army leaders concluded from the poor showing that
``the reserve forces are highly dispersed... And a more effective
way should be instituted to hasten assembly.''
