<DOCNO> AP880824-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-US-SovietArms 1stLd-Writethru   08-24 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet Arms, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0528,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Review Conference on ABM Treaty Opens</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 5th graf, `The ABM...' to CLARIFY that treaty allows
each side to deploy one system. Pick up 6th pvs, `The United...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Soviet Union today opened a
conference to review the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty, and
both sides linked progress at separate arms talks to the other
side's compliance with the pact.
   The conference began today at the Soviet diplomatic mission,
U.S. spokesman Terry Shroeder said. He declined to give details.
   The first full meeting of both delegations, headed by Soviet
disarmament official Viktor Karpov and the head of the U.S. Arms
Control and Disarmament Agency, Maj. Gen. William Burns, was
scheduled for Thursday.
   The conference is expected to last for one or two weeks. Under
the ABM treaty, such meetings must be held every five years to give
both sides a chance to list grievances.
   The ABM treaty allows each side to deploy only one ABM system
and limits the types of systems that may be deployed. The theory
for the agreement is that a potential aggressor would not launch a
nuclear attack if it faced the prospect of devastating retaliation.
   The United States has maintained a Soviet radar under
construction at Krasnoyarsk, in Siberia, violates the treaty and
must be dismantled. The Soviets contend the U.S. Strategic Defense
Initiative, a research program aimed at creating a space-based
missile defense, violates the treaty and should be limited.
   According to an information sheet distributed by the U.S.
mission, U.S. officials recently told the Soviets that unless the
radar is dismantled, no agreement is possible at negotiations on
reducing strategic nuclear forces, or START.
   The START talks have been going on in Geneva since March 1985.
Both sides agree in principle that strategic forces should be
reduced by 50 percent.
   As a condition for the START agreement, the Soviets have for
years demanded that the United States limit its Strategic Defense
Initiative.
   The ABM treaty review opened in a low-key atmosphere following
earlier U.S. statements which hinted at a showdown over the
Krasnoyarsk radar.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said this month that
after hearing the Soviet position on Krasnoyarsk at the ABM
conference, ``should the situation remain unresolved, the president
will consult with the Congress and our allies concerning next
steps.''
   One possible next step, according to the U.S. information sheet,
would be for the United States to declare the radar a ``material
breach'' of the treaty. This would open the way for the United
States to terminate or suspend the treaty and then go beyond its
limits on the Strategic Defense Initiative.
   A U.S. delegation statement issued Tuesday did not speak of
possible retaliatory action.
   Karpov, in an arrival statement Saturday, said his side ``is
prepared to discuss'' the Krasnoyarsk radar. He said his delegation
is ``ready to demonstrate in practice our consistent adherence to
the ABM treaty.''
   Moscow will insist on ``the preservation of the ABM treaty
intact as it was signed in 1972,'' he said, apparently alluding to
Moscow's position that the Strategic Defense Initiative threatens
the treaty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880824-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ForestFiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0500 08-24 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Forest Fires Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0500,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fires Force Hundreds of Tourists From Yellowstone</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with evacuation, park correction of fire
distance from 1 mile to 2, ADDS Idaho fire. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED ANDRIESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of tourists
packed their bags this morning and filed out of Yellowstone
National Park's Canyon area, forced from the cabin development by
flames from one of the park's 10 fires.
   Crews near Helena, Mont., aimed to contain a 37,000-acre blaze
by tonight; firefighters in Idaho tried to rein in a 750-acre fire
on the slopes of the nation's deepest gorge in Hells Canyon, and a
rash of wildfires broke out Tuesday in Oregon, including a small
blaze ignited by a plane crash that killed three.
   In Yellowstone, a finger of flame from a 91,700-acre fire in the
park's western section edged to within 2 miles of the Canyon area,
the largest development in the country's oldest national park.
   Park spokeswoman Robbie Blackwell said 306 tourists and as many
as 275 staff members spent Tuesday night in the development, which
also contains a visitors center, a general store and a campground.
   ``Nobody wanted to rattle beds and get people up. As the people
are getting up this morning they will start going through checkout
procedures, have breakfast this morning and then start leaving the
Canyon area,'' said the spokesman.
   The fire, one of 10 in the park involving some 350,000 acres,
was the only one to post major advances Tuesday despite winds
gusting to about 30 mph. Low temperatures aided some 4,000
firefighters and 1,200 soldiers battling flames.
   Several other areas in the park are closed, including its Grant
Village complex containing a campground, hotel, visitors center and
staff dormitories.
   Many of the guests who had reserved spaces at Canyon's 600
cabins were moved to other park lodgings Tuesday night, said Steve
Tedder of TW Services, Yellowstone's concessionaire.
   ``Everything has been very orderly,'' he said. ``This has almost
become business as usual, as we've lived with it (the fires) for
about seven weeks.''
   Reservations are off about 25 percent this summer, Tedder added,
almost certainly because of this year's fires, the worst in memory
in Yellowstone.
   In Idaho, 400 firefighters battled to keep a fire from moving
over a ridge and into area with 12 million board-feet of timber the
National Forest Service wants to sell.
   Firefighters at a 156,500-acre blaze in Yellowstone's
northeastern corner were aided Tuesday by about 600 soldiers from
Fort Lewis, Wash. Another 600 Fort Lewis soldiers were to help
clean up a 4,300-acre fire in Wyoming's Bridger-Teton National
Forest and adjacent Grand Teton National Park.
   In Montana, winds Tuesday pushed a blaze away from the towns of
Cooke City and Silver Gate, officials said.
   In mountains southeast of Helena, nearly 3,000 firefighters
gained a foothold in a two-week battle to contain the 37,600-acre
fire that destroyed more than a dozen structures.
   ``There are no problems on the line that we've heard of, and
we're still hoping for containment by 8 p.m.,'' said Gordon Gray, a
fire information officer.
   In the west-central Oregon town of LaPine, three families were
briefly evacuated Tuesday night because of one of a series of small
fires in the state. Lightning was blamed for at least 50 of the
blazes.
   Near Morton, Wash., gusty wind and 100-degree temperatures
allowed a forest fire to grow from 60 acres to 500 within a few
hours Tuesday, officials said. The blaze burned mostly on land
owned by the Murray Pacific Co., a timber firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
