<DOCNO> AP880824-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   08-24 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0834</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   Aug. 22
   Austin (Texas) American-Statesman on a national energy policy:
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, the No. 2 man on the Democratic ticket, is
perfectly right to decry the Reagan administration's lack of
interest in expanding the U.S. Strategic Petroleum Reserve.
   But it is also worth noting that an expanded reserve ... should
be only one part of an overall national energy policy, and neither
the Reagan administration nor the Congress has yet come close to
developing such a policy. ...
   Everything is partisan during an election campaign. ...
   But after the issue of the presidency is settled, it is to be
hoped that the new administration and the Congress will find time
to agree on a bipartisan national energy policy that will include
conservation, alternative and synthetic fuels, and incentives for
domestic oil and gas exploration _ a policy that will enable the
nation to become as energy self-sufficient as possible.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 21
   Sunday Sun-Journal, Lewiston, Maine, on the influence of
lobbyists:
   Influence peddlers on Capitol Hill spent more than $63 million
trying to persuade Congress in 1987.
   The total represents a 4.5 percent increase from 1986, when the
income tax changes caused a surge of lobbying efforts. ...
   The list of groups continues with a seemingly endless number of
causes.
   Lawmakers should be wary of the information supplied by special
interest groups.
   The inherent bias built into these organizations should raise a
red flag of suspicion and any statistics given could be
questionable.
   Hopefully, Congress evaluates each issue in isolation _ apart
from the arm-twisting that lobbyists exert.
   With any luck, lawmakers will not adopt barnyard appetites for
this type of slop.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 23
   Saginaw (Mich.) News on Dan Quayle and his National Guard
service:
   The issue of Dan Quayle's Vietnam-era National Guard service
ought to be put into perspective.
   In joining the National Guard, Quayle, the Republican nominee
for vice president, did precisely what all but the most rare of men
did in that day.
   He looked for the best deal. And so did just about everyone
else, including those who went to Vietnam. ...
   This is not to suggest any absence of dedication among those who
served. The evidence of Vietnam was just the opposite. ...
   How many of those who did heroically slog through the swamps and
jungles and froze in the mountains can say today that given a
choice and a chance, they would not rather have missed out on all
that fun and excitement? ...
   The question is whether Quayle did serve when his time came. He
did. So let's drop the hypocrisy, and the harping.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 18
   The Leaf-Chronicle, Clarksville, Tenn., on the penal system:
   Geraldine Ferraro says she can't understand what the fuss is all
about.
   Her son, John Zaccaro Jr., ... was sentenced to up to five years
in prison, with all but four months suspended, for selling cocaine
when he was a college student.
   As with many states, Vermont has an overcrowded prison system.
To get non-violent offenders out of the state institutions, a
program allows them to secure their own housing while under the
supervision of a corrections officer, who periodically checks on
them.
   Zaccaro was able to afford much better housing than his fellow
convicts. He's doing his time in a $1,500-a-month luxury apartment.
...
   The concept behind the house arrest program is sound. But it
shouldn't include drug felons or make a joke out of the penal
system by permitting those with money to buy a lockup that most
law-abiding citizens can only dream of living in.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 19
   The Tri-City Herald, Kennewick, Wash., on Congressional
honoraria:
   Our $89,500 per year members of Congress are being urged by no
less a figure than Speaker of the House Jim Wright to give up what
has become a disgrace: the honoraria that incumbents receive for
giving speeches.
   These appearances, for which the members may receive up to
$2,000 apiece, are essentially the gravy boats to go with their
pork-chopping ways.
   The money comes from special interest groups. In a word,
lobbyists. They think nothing of awarding the members of Congress
for any considerations that might be thrown their way.
   This is legal, but it is not right.
   Our Congress was envisioned as a noble body acting as a balance
against excesses in the executive branch, and the fashioner of our
laws.
   Instead, with this disgusting largesse, we are made witness to a
feeding spectacle of embarrassing proportions. ...
   Perhaps Wright's endorsement, coming as it does from one more
soiled than most in these sordid little deals, will succeed where
virtue and ethical behavior have not.
</TEXT>
