<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: have not.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 18
   East Oregonian, Pendleton, Ore., on George Bush's selection of
Dan Quayle:
   George Bush's choice of Sen. Dan Quayle to be his running mate
is uninspiring, ... but voters will make their decision basically
on the performances of the presidential _ rather than the vice
presidential _ candidates. ...
   Bush's selection of Quayle on the Republican ticket probably
tells voters something about Bush's political philosophy.
   Quayle's voting record in Congress is firmly on the conservative
right wing of the political spectrum.
   Bush will easily attract the votes of conservatives away from
(Democratic presidential nominee Michael) Dukakis this November
without a conservative running mate.
   So his selection of Quayle apparently says Bush feels
comfortable with someone from the right wing or wants to cater
strongly to right-wing voters.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 22
   The Honolulu Star-Bulletin on George Bush's selection of Dan
Quayle:
   Apart from whether family influence was used to get him into the
Indiana National Guard during the Vietnam War era, (Dan) Quayle
presents basic problems for the ticket.
   Quayle's presence reflects questionable judgment on the part of
Vice President Bush, a presidential nominee who had five months to
think about a running mate and who rushed to select someone he did
not know as well as he should have.
   To repair the situation, Quayle needs to answer the National
Guard question and others about his pre-political life, and to
begin campaigning in more serious settings.
   He should get away from rally scenes that require him to shout
political rhetoric and try other, smaller arenas where he can be
seen and heard in ways that may inspire more confidence in his
government skills.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 22
   The (Baltimore) Sun on the Vincennes report:
   The main effect of the Pentagon's investigation of the USS
Vincennes' downing of an Iranian civil airliner on July 3 is to
exonerate the equipment.
   Confidence is maintained in the complex Aegis radar tracking
system, and in the Ticonderoga class of guided missile cruisers.
... ``The equipment functioned as designed,'' said Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci.
   The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm. William Crowe,
upheld the action taken by Capt. Will C. Rogers III on the basis of
information available.
   The secretary rejected the recommendation of the panel headed by
Rear Adm. William Fogarty that an officer be censured. ...
``Mistakes are made in virtually every combat situation,'' Carlucci
said.
   An official who sends military personnel into combat must expect
that. So must an official who sends airliners over the area.
   The Reagan administration trusted in the perfection of American
boys when it sent them into treacherous waters. The Khomeini regime
in Tehran made the same mistake in thinking it could attack them
without risk to innocents nearby.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 21
   Albuquerque (N.M.) Journal on Nelson Mandela:
   It's been nearly 10 months now since the South African
government freed Govan Mbeki, the 77-year-old former chairman of
the outlawed African National Congress.
   Observers hoped that Mbeki's freedom signaled the imminent
release of Nelson Mandela, the charismatic ANC leader who, like
Mbeki and six other ANC members, was imprisoned in 1964 after being
convicted of conspiring to overthrow the government.
   But Mandela, 70 years old, is still in prison. And now his
lawyer and family report that he suffers from tuberculosis. That is
all the more reason for him to be freed.
   The time is ripe for countries such as the United States to step
up calls for Mandela's release.
   South Africa may be stubborn, but it is not totally deaf to
international sentiment _ or to its own best interests. Last year's
release of Mbeki proved that.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 17
   North Jersey Advance, Flanders, N.J., on limiting House and
Senate terms:
   Although Republican platform drafts are scripted in advance, an
unexpected plank swept the delegates.
   It called for a limit on the number of terms that House and
Senate members can serve.
   This harkened back to the 22nd Amendment, which limits a
president to two four-year terms.
   With Congress becoming a lifetime job, with members holding huge
advantages over challengers and with their increasing arrogance and
unaccountability, a limit in their ``service'' may be the best idea
on either platform.
</TEXT>
