<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-PCBsFire 1stLd-Writethru   08-24 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-PCBs Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0522,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burning PCBs Sends 3,000 Fleeing From Homes</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Updates throughout with warning not to eat vegetables grown
in eastern Montreal, CORRECTS length of evacuated area to 5 miles.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   ST-BASILE-LE-GRAND, Quebec (AP) _ Police today kept about 3,000
residents from returning to their homes after thousands of gallons
of oil laced with PCBs caught fire and released a poisonous black
cloud.
   The warehouse fire broke out at 8:30 p.m. Tuesday and was
extinguished after burning for more than six hours.
   Quebec provincial police sealed off a 1-by-5-mile corridor in
this suburb across the St. Lawrence River and 15 miles east of
Montreal. Officials warned people in a wide area including eastern
Montreal not to eat vegetables from their gardens.
   ``So long as we are not 100 per cent certain that the soil, air
and water are 100 per cent safe, we are not going to let people go
back into their homes,'' said Clifford Lincoln, Quebec's
environment minister. Technicians today examined the soil and water
around Montreal.
   Environment Ministry technician Alain Lavoie said at least 50
residents were treated in hospitals for skin and lung irritation,
but no serious injuries were reported.
   PCBs, polychlorinated biphenyls, are fire-retardant chemicals
that were used most often as insulating fluids or coolants in
heavy-duty electrical equipment suchthe community using loudspeakers to
order the
evacuation. Residents spent the night in local schools.
   ``Until the results of our tests, we are telling people not to
eat food from their gardens or drink tap water because 30 percent
of their water comes from a lake in the contaminated area,'' Lavoie
said.
   Montreal fire director Raymond Therrien also advised residents
of eastern Montreal not to eat fruit and vegetables from their
gardens until further notice.
   ``Because of the winds, the cloud of smoke from this fire spread
over east-end neighborhoods during the night,'' Therrien said.
   Jean-Guy Campbell, who lives near the warehouse, said he was
outside with his wife when the fire started with an explosion.
   ``There was a black cloud about three stories high,'' Campbell
said. ``I could feel it on my skin. It was very itchy.''
   Other evacuees complained of sore throats, itchy skin and
dizziness after inhaling the smoke.
   ``In two or three years, how many cancers will we have?'' said
resident Lise Sweeney.
   Eugene Jankowski, a St-Basile town councilor, said the
warehouse, owned by Marc Levy, stored 500 barrels containing about
23,000 gallons of oil laced with PCBs. Levy could not be reached
for comment.
   Gerard Latulippe, who represents the area in the Quebec
legislature and was among the evacuees, said the government had had
trouble getting the warehouse to conform to environmental standards.
   ``The company had to be forced to take some measures to improve
the safety of the site and some things were done,'' he said.
   Lincoln said the government had threatened to suspend Levy's
permit unless the company adhered to its specifications and that
Levy complied with most of the conditions.
   The only plant in Canada capable of destroying PCBs is in Swan
Hills, Alberta, but it does not accept PCB waste from other
provinces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
