<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Names SUB a0490 08-24 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names, SUB, a0490,0328</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES 1st item throughout with Tyson not appearing at
stationhouse. A version moving on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Undefeated heavyweight champion Mike Tyson,
wearing a cast on his right hand, says he tried to duck a street
fight with one of his former ring victims but ``had no choice''
when the man ripped his shirt.
   Tyson, who suffered a hairline fracture in his right hand during
the scuffle early Tuesday, said Mitchell Green started a fight as
the champion was getting into his car outside a 24-hour clothing
store in Harlem.
   Green ripped his shirt and ``hit me on the chest. He was upset.
I guess I hit him over the eye. I was nervous. I hadn't had a
street fight in seven years. I was scared,'' Tyson said.
   Tyson said Green was ``ranting and raving'' that Tyson and
promoter Don King owed him money.
   ``We fought one time. He had a bad deal on his purse and he
didn't make a great deal of money,'' Tyson said.
   Green, a former contender for the U.S. Boxing Association title
who lost a decision to Tyson in 1986, said Tyson ``popped him on
the bridge of his nose,'' requiring five stitches, according to
police spokesman Sgt. John Clifford.
   Green, 31, of New York, said Tyson punched him first after he
told Tyson he did not think the champ had beaten him in the ring.
   A summons charging Tyson with misdemeanor assault was issued.
But the boxer did not appear at the stationhouse today as expected.
His publicist, Howard J. Rubenstein, said it was because his hand
was hurting and he had to see a doctor.
   Rubenstein said the police agreed to postpone Tyson's appearance
until Thursday.
   Tyson's manager, Bill Cayton, said he did not know whether
Tyson's Oct. 8 fight against Frank Bruno in England would have to
be rescheduled because of the injury.
</TEXT>
