<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--China-Agriculture     08-24 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Agriculture,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Production Will Not Reach Quota, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's grain production is expected to fall
short of this year's government-set quota because of natural
disasters and rising production costs, a newspaper reported
Wednesday.
   The China Daily, quoting officials from the National Research
Center for Development of Science and Technology, said 28 million
acres of farmland, about 10 percent of China's total, have been hit
by a severe drought. It said another 17.3 million acres have been
inundated by floods.
   The report also said farmers were discouraged from planting
grains by low government-set prices and high production costs.
   Agriculture experts predict the 1988 grain output will fall
slightly short of this year's annual quota of 410 million tons.
   After a record 407 million tons were grown in 1984, grain output
fell to 379 million tons in 1985, then edged back up to 402 million
tons last year.
</TEXT>
