<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietInspectors     08-24 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Inspectors,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Arrive For Inspection of Last European Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten Soviets arrived Wednesday to carry out the last
inspection of a U.S. missile base before the end of a two-month
inspection period under the superpower treaty to eliminate
medium-and shorter-range nuclear weapons.
   The inspectors will stay at a hotel until they give official
notice _ within a 48-hour period _ that they intend to visit the
base in Comiso, in southeastern Sicily. According to U.S. and
Italian officials, 112 Tomahawk cruise missiles are deployed in
Comiso.
   A U.S. military officer, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the Soviets were expected to fly to the base in an American
military aircraft to Comiso on Friday.
   Under the terms of the treaty, the Soviets can take as long as
24 hours to inspect missiles, missile launchers and related
equipment. They can request an eight-hour extension, which U.S.
officials can grant or refuse.
   The Soviets will be escorted by 10 Americans, including military
officials, and by four Italian military officers and a
representative of the Foreign Ministry.
   At the end of the inspection, inspectors and escorts must
exchange reports.
   During the 60-day inspection period, which ends at midnight Aug.
29, the Soviets had 30 sites to visit in the United States and in
five Western European countries. U.S. inspectors had 133 sites to
cover in the Soviet Union and elsewhere in the East bloc.
   Three of the Soviet inspectors had visited sites in the United
States and a fourth had inspected U.S. and Western European
facilities. Previous Soviet inspections have taken place in West
Germany, Belgium, Britain and the Netherlands.
   The treaty calls for the elimination within three years of all
U.S. and Soviet land-based missiles with ranges from 300 to 3,400
miles.
   The head of the Soviet inspection team, Gennadiy Mikhailovich
Komogortsev, said in his arrival speech that the aim of the visit
is to verify that the number of missiles, launchers and other
related equipment corresponds to details provided by the Americans.
</TEXT>
