<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Panama-Families     08-24 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Families,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Families Move Inside Bases In Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department has reduced by 54
percent the number of military families living outside U.S. bases
in Panama over the past five months, officials said Wednesday.
   The effort to move as many military families as possible inside
U.S. bases in the troubled Central American nation has been aided
by a growing number of servicemen deciding to accept so-called
``unaccompanied tours'' rather than bring families with them.
   Pentagon officials say they have no precise statistics available
on that trend, but add that on-base housing has been freed up this
summer at an unusual rate compared to years past, making it
possible to move more families in from civilian homes.
   According to Maj. Kathy Wood, a Pentagon spokeswoman, there were
2,450 military families living off-post in Panama City as of March
1. That number had been cut to 1,134 as of Aug. 1, and efforts are
continuing to find space for as many more as possible, she said.
   ``We think we can do more,'' the spokeswoman said of the
movements. ``There are clearly people choosing not to take their
families to Panama, and that helps free housing.''
   Although the Pentagon has been working to move dependents to
base housing for months, the effort has taken on more momentum this
summer because of what the United States has described as a
deliberate campaign of harassing Americans.
   U.S. officials in Panama City reported last Sunday that
Americans had reported at least 240 incidents of harassment by
Panamanian authorities this year, including stoppage of mail and
attempts to extort bribes for traffic violations.
   The United States is continuing to press economic sanctions
against Panama in a bid to oust military leader Manuel A. Noriega.
Noriega has been indicted by two federal grand juries in Florida on
drug trafficking charges.
   Panama is the home of the U.S. Southern Command, the
organization responsible for all U.S. military forces in Central
and South America. There are about 10,000 American servicemen
stationed permanently in Panama, plus about 2,200 servicemen who
have been assigned there on a temporary basis since spring to
upgrade security at American bases.
</TEXT>
