<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--UtahQuake     08-24 0132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Utah Quake,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Quake Rattles Section Of Salt Lake City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small earthquake rattled a section of
northeastern Salt Lake City, but was not related to a series of
tremors which shook central Utah earlier this month, seismologists
said.
   The quake, measuring 2.1 on the Richter scale of ground motion,
occurred at 11:13 p.m. MDT on Tuesday, said Linda Hall of the
University of Utah Seismograph Stations.
   No damage or injuries were reported, she said.
   Hall said the temblor occurred along the Wasatch Fault, a series
of unstable geoological formations along the Wasatch Mountains
running from northern to central Utah.
   On Aug. 14, three quakes rolled through central Utah and western
Colorado, the largest measuring 5.6 magnitude. No injuries or major
property damage were reported.
</TEXT>
