<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cops-Robberies     08-24 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cops-Robberies,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Charged With Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Detroit police officer has been charged with
kidnapping and armed robbery in incidents two other officers were
suspected of earlier, authorities said.
   Brian David Crite, 20, was arraigned Tuesday on charges of
kidnapping, armed robbery and use of a firearm in commission of a
crime, a spokesman for Wayne County Prosecutor John D. O'Hair said.
   Magistrate Charles Hammons Sr. ordered him held on $100,000 bond
pending a Sept. 2 preliminary hearing.
   Crite, on the department for two years, was identified Tuesday
by three victims as one of two uniformed men who robbed them Aug.
16 after stopping them with a patrol car, police said.
   If convicted of either kidnapping or armed robbery, he could be
sentenced to life in prison.
   Investigators are looking into complaints that two uniformed men
driving a patrol car robbed at least 10 people Aug. 15 and Aug. 16.
   Two other officers detained in the case last week were suspected
because a patrol car they used the afternoon of Aug. 15 was
reported missing and believed used in the robbery spree. They were
released after victims failed to identify them in a lineup.
   Department spokesmen declined comment on Crite's arrest.
</TEXT>
