<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Eliana-AIDS 1stLd-Writethru a0529 08-24 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eliana-AIDS, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0529,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many Parents Concerned About AIDS-Infected Girl</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `Chief U.S. ...' to UPDATE with judge
allowing girl to stay at home while appeal is heard.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150 parents toured a specially built
glass booth where an AIDS-stricken girl is to be quarantined during
class, but many remained concerned that their children could catch
the deadly virus.
   ``If Eliana Martinez comes here, my daughter won't,'' Robin
Preston declared Tuesday, referring to the mentally retarded
6-year-old who is to attend the Manhattan Exceptional Center under
federal court order.
   ``There's too much unknown to say AIDS is not a communicable
disease,'' he said. ``I'm sorry she has the disease, but why put
all the other children in jeopardy?''
   Earlier this month U.S. District Judge Elizabeth A. Kovachevich
ruled that Eliana could attend classes with other children but must
stay in the 6-by-8-foot enclosure outfitted with a toilet and sink
until she becomes toilet-trained and stops sucking her fingers.
   Citing possible emotional damage to Eliana if she is so
isolated, Eliana's lawyers and mother have vowed to keep the child
out of the cubicle.
   Chief U.S. District Judge William Terrell Hodges ruled today
that until the case can heard by the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Atlanta, Eliana may stay in an at-home instruction
program rather than being put in the booth.
   ``Can you guarantee that the child will not infect our
children?'' one parent asked during Tuesday's forum organized by
the school district and health officials.
   ``No, I can't guarantee, but I can give you the medical
information,'' said Dr. Dennis Ledford, an allergist and professor
at the University of South Florida Medical School. ``A person
walking around with this disease doesn't send it out like
missiles.''
   The fatal acquired immune deficiency syndrome is transmitted
most often by blood or semen, usually through sexual contact or the
sharing of hypodermic needles.
   ``I don't know what I am going to do,'' said Lynette Green,
whose 11-year-old son is one of a dozen children scheduled to
attend class with Eliana. ``I guess I'm kind of scared.''
</TEXT>
