<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Prize     08-24 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Japan-Prize,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Indian Wins Japanese Literary Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The life story of an American Indian has won a top
non-fiction award in a contest sponsored by a Japanese magazine,
the magazine's publisher said Wednesday.
   Dennis Banks and Yuri Morita, co-authors of ``Sacred Soul,''
were given this year's $7,500 Asahi Journal Non-Fiction Award.
   Ms. Morita, 37, spent five years transcribing and translating
into Japanese the life story of Banks, leader of the American
Indian Movement, an Indian rights organization.
   The story details Banks' struggle for Indian rights and
culminates in his meeting with a fellow Indian in prison.
   Banks, 52, of the Ojibwa tribe in Minnesota, says he published
the story in Japanese because English is the language of the
conquerors of his people.
   He was a U.S. Air Force serviceman in Japan in the 1950s and
says he is inspired by the non-violent philosophy of Japanese
Buddhists.
</TEXT>
