<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0580 08-24 0995</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0580,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Gets AFL-CIO Endorsement, Raps Bush as Economic `Son of
Voodoo'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Dukakis speech; picks up pvs 2nd graf
bgng, The giant.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis picked up
organized labor's endorsement today, criticized the Reagan-Bush
record on creating jobs and said the nation needs ``an economic
leader, not a cheerleader'' for president.
   Dukakis criticized Republican candidate George Bush for failing
to mention budget and trade deficits in his acceptance speech at
the GOP National Convention in New Orleans last week.
   ``And to add insult to injury,'' Dukakis told AFL-CIO union
presidents, ``he wants to cut taxes for the wealthy again. You
know, if this was a movie it would be called `Son of Voodoo'.''
   Dukakis said that while more Americans are working today than at
any time in history, the majority of jobs created under President
Reagan have paid poorly. He said the average weekly wage for jobs
lost between 1979 and 1985 was $440, while the average wage of
replacement jobs was one-third less.
   ``That's the price American workers and families are paying for
eight years of voodoo economics,'' said Dukakis, borrowing a phrase
that Bush himself once used to describe Reagan's economic policies.
   Earlier, the AFL-CIO formally endorsed Dukakis for president, as
expected, with federation president Lane Kirkland charging that the
Reagan administration ``has favored greed over need'' for the past
eight years.
   The giant labor federation's endorsement of the Massachusetts
governor was nearly unanimous. Of its 91 affiliated unions, only
the 30,000-member Air Line Pilots Association, the 40,000-member
Marine Engineers Union and the 1.6-million Teamsters union
abstained from the vote.
   ``The Reagan-Bush administration came to Washington charging
that government itself was the problem,'' Kirkland said. ``Eight
years later we know that government is not the problem. The problem
lies with those who govern. This is an administration that has
favored greed over need.''
   Teamster President William McCarthy said his union had not
polled its members but is doing so through its monthly magazine.
Teamster officials said they expect to announce an endorsement in
mid-September.
   The airline pilots said their board of directors had not met on
the issue, and the marine engineers said they were following a long
tradition of not making presidential endorsements.
   The Newspaper Guild cast 21,390 votes or approximately 80
percent of its membership in favor of Dukakis but abstained on
4,000 votes in the membership-weighted tally.
   Guild President Charles Dale said the partial abstention
reflected the policy of the union's Wire Service Guild local in
``disassociating itself from any political endorsements.''
   Dukakis flew here from Boston to address the labor federation
later today, after reviving Republican George Bush's ``voodoo
economics'' line to criticize the vice president's own budget plan.
   Then Dukakis planned two days of campaigning in the big
industrial states of Michigan, Ohio and Pennsylvania.
   The Massachusetts governor spent Tuesday wrapping up his annual
trip to his state's northeast communities, but he took time to
deliver some of his harshest criticism to date of Bush, his
Republican rival.
   Dukakis called Bush's flexible-freeze budget plan ``the son of
voodoo economics.'' It was Bush who, during his 1980 GOP primary
campaign, referred to Ronald Reagan's economic proposals as
``voodoo economics.''
   The governor also questioned Bush's support for mandatory
recitation of the Pledge of Allegiance in schools, saying the vice
president was unfit to run for president if he would sign such
legislation after being told by a court that it was
unconstitutional.
   In addition, Dukakis reiterated that he was eager to debate
Bush, and there was an indication some progress was being made on
that issue. Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas was to meet
with his counterpart in the Bush campaign, James A. Baker III,
early next week to discuss a debate schedule.
   ``There is no Republican plan'' to erase the federal deficit,
Dukakis said after telling newspaper editors he would balance the
budget within five years by holding the line on defense spending,
cutting some domestic spending and collecting unpaid taxes.
   ``The vice president is talking about a flexible freeze,''
Dukakis said. ``That's like a melting ice cube. ... That's the son
of voodoo economics.''
   Dukakis also lashed back at criticism from Bush and other
Republicans who have attacked his 1977 veto of state legislation
that penalized teachers who refused to lead their students in the
Pledge of Allegiance.
   The governor vetoed the measure after the state's highest court,
citing U.S. Supreme Court precedent, advised him the legislation
was unconstitutional.
   ``I encourage children to say the Pledge of Allegiance,''
Dukakis said. ``I say the Pledge of Allegiance. That's not the
issue. The Republicans know it. ... That law was unconstitutional.
   ``If the vice president of the United States is saying that if
he was president and the United States Supreme Court said the law
was unconstitutional and the attorney general said it was
unconstitutional and he'd have signed it anyway, well, that raises
very serious questions about what it means to take the oath of
office,'' Dukakis said.
   ``You are under a constitutional oath to veto the bill, aren't
you?'' he said. ``Is the vice president suggesting something else?
Is he suggesting he'd sign the bill anyway, having been informed by
the highest court of the land that it was unconstitutional? If he
does that, he has no business running for this office.''
   Bush spokesman Mark Goodin criticized Dukakis for failing to
challenge the Massachusetts court's advisory opinion.
   ``Courts rule on constitutionality, not governors,'' Goodin
said. ``The point is if he felt strongly on the issue, he could
have challenged it in court and he decided not to do that.''
   Dukakis also applauded President Reagan for signing major trade
legislation Tuesday, but said Democrats deserved credit for the
measure. Dukakis was quick to point out that his running mate,
Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, was the co-sponsor of the Senate bill.
``He was the architect of it,'' Dukakis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
