<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     08-24 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Korean Talks May Resume</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of North Korea and South
Korea said Thursday they are willing to resume talks on sharing
next month's Olympics and a non-aggression pact.
   But there was no clear agreement: North Korea suggested meeting
on Thursday and South Korea proposed a session on Friday.
   Officials at the National Assembly said their chief delegate,
Prk Joon-kyu, met privately with his North Korean counterpart, Chon
Kum Chol, at the truce village of Panmunjom Wednesday. Later in the
day, Seoul telephoned Panmunjom to suggest reopening talks Friday.
   North Korea said in a radio broadcast monitored in Tokyo that
its delegation had proposed meeting on Thursday.
   Park refused to disclose details of Wednesday's meeting. He did
say he expected ``new proposals'' from North Korea, but he admitted
he was not encouraged by Wednesday's meeting.
   Assembly officials were reluctant to predict whether the
deadlocked talks could be revived. But one senior official,
speaking on condition he not be identified, said, ``Neither side
wants to take the blame.''
   Seoul officials say they believe North Korea does not expect a
dramatic breakthough. Instead, they think Panmunjom is trying to
distract world attention from the Sept. 17-Oct. 2 Olympics in Seoul.
   The two Koreas have been bitter rivals since their peninsula was
divided at the end of World War.
   The current round of talks, which began Aug. 19, ended in a
stalemate Monday. South Korean delegates said then they hoped to
pospone further contacts until after the Olympics.
   North Korea had called for urgent talks on sharing the Olympics,
but South Korean officials said they were not so enthusiastic about
pursuing the subject when the face-to-face meetings began. The
North Koreans seemed more concerned about a non-aggression pact,
they said.
   These preliminary talks broke up over such basic issues as the
agenda and the number of participants for later negotiations
proposed for the two parliaments. North Korea insists the main
talks include the full legislatures of both sides, which would
involve nearly 1,000 people. South Korea wants delegations of up to
30 lawmakers from each side.
   North Korea also wants the two parliaments to publish a joint
declaration of non-aggression calling for the withdrawal of the
42,000 U.S. troops in South Korea, as well as removal of the
nuclear weapons allegedly in their arsenal. Seoul sees the U.S.
forces as vital to its defenses.
   North Korea has said it would boycott the Olympics unless it can
be a co-host. The International Olympic Committee rejected the
North Korean demand, saying that the Olympics are given to a single
city and cannot be shared.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
