<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--SewerOrgans     08-24 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Sewer Organs,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Organs Found At Sewer Plant Believed Human</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMMOND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organs found floating in the city sewer
treatment plant are believed to be human, but should not pose a
public health threat, officials said Wednesday.
   The organs were found Tuesday in a filter designed to keep
solids from entering the treatment process at the Sanitary District
plant. They were taken to St. Margaret Hospital and Health Centers
for analysis.
   Dr. Tieh Wang, who heads the hospital's chemical laboratory,
said he was ``99.9 percent sure they are human organs,'' but said
they also could be from a deer or cow.
   Wang said the tissue did not appear to present a health threat.
   The organs, one colon and the others unidentified, will be
stored for three to six months at the hospital as a precaution and
then disposed of as solid waste. It was not clear how many organs
were found.
   Tom Gordon, acting superintendent at the treatment plant, said
it is not uncommon to find organs in the sewage treatment system.
</TEXT>
