<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Israel 1st-LdWritethru a0546 08-24 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Israel, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0546,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department `Shocked' by Deportations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with State Department comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said today it was
``shocked'' by Israel's decision to expel 25 Palestinian activists,
and a senior diplomat said that relations between the two countries
might be damaged if the expulsions continue.
   The warning was conveyed Monday by Deputy Secretary of State
John Whitehead to Israel's charge d'affaires Oded Eran, said an
Israeli source, declining to be further identified.
   Israeli Embassy spokesman Yossi Gal confirmed the meeting took
place but declined to discuss its contents.
   Eran, who is in charge of the embassy while Ambassador Moshe
Arad is on vacation, was summoned to the State Department after
Israel announced it would expel 25 Palestinians accused of fueling
the violence which has claimed more than 250 Palestinian lives in
the past eight months.
   Whitehead ``was emphatic about the U.S. position that it objects
to these expulsions,'' said the source.
   ``He said relations could be damaged if this goes on,'' the
source added.
   ``We are shocked by the government of Israel's decision to expel
an additional 25 Palestinians,'' said State Department spokeswoman
Phyllis Oakley.
   She said that if Israel carries out the deportation orders, it
will bring to 60 the number of Palestinians expelled this year from
the Israeli-occupied territories. The expulsions can be appealed to
the Israeli Supreme Court, although all the orders have been upheld
this year.
   The growing number of expulsions appears to indicate that
deportations ``are the norm rather than the exception,'' she added.
   Israel contends that it uses expulsions only as a last resort to
ensure public order is maintained in the territories. It has
accused those expelled of fueling the Palestinian uprising that
began last December.
   Israel argues that it is entitled to deport Palestinians in
accordance with international law governing occupying powers, as
well as under British emergency laws applied by the government in
the West Bank and Gaza.
   But Mrs. Oakley repeated the U.S. view that deportations are not
legal under the Geneva human rights accords, which govern the
conduct of occupying powers, and called on Israel to charge and try
Palestinians rather than expel them.
   Expulsions only exacerbate the situation and increase tensions
between Israelis and Palestinians, she said.
   Nonetheless, Mrs. Oakley reaffirmed the strong ties between the
two countries, saying ``our friendship and close association with
Israel continue.''
   Israel is the largest recipient of U.S. foreign aid, getting $3
billion annually in economic and military support funds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
