<DOCNO> AP880824-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ArmsTalks     08-24 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Talks,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Superpowers Open Review Conference on ABM Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-Soviet conference reviewing the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty opened Wednesday after both sides
linked progress at separate weapons reduction talks to full
compliance with the ABM accord.
   Superpower delegates held two meetings Wednesday, one in the
morning and one in the afternoon, said U.S. spokesman Terry
Shroeder. He said he had no details of what was discussed.
   The first full meeting, or plenary, of both delegations is
scheduled for Thursday at the U.S. diplomatic mission. The U.S.
delegation is headed by Maj. Gen. William Burns, head of the Arms
Control and Disarmament Agency, and the Soviet side by top
disarmament official Viktor Karpov.
   The conference is the third such meeting held since the ABM
treaty went into effect. Under the accord, such meetings must be
held every five years.
   The ABM treaty restricts each side to deploying only one ABM
system, comprising a radar and anti-ballistic missiles. The aim is
to prevent either side from creating a full nationwide protective
network under the theory that neither would launch a nuclear attack
if it feared devastating retaliation.
   The United States maintains that a Soviet radar under
construction in Krasnoyarsk, in Siberia, violates the treaty
because it is not located on the periphery of the country, facing
outward, as the treaty stipulates that missile tracking radars must
be.
   The United States has also voiced concern at Soviet deployment
last year of two other radars in Gomel, near Kiev, saying they also
violate the treaty.
   An information sheet distributed by the U.S. mission says U.S.
officials recently told the Soviets that unless the Krasnoyarsk
radar is dismantled, no agreement is possible at separate
negotiations on reducing strategic, or intercontinental, nuclear
forces. This was apparently the first time the U.S. side made such
a linkage.
   The Soviets have for years linked progress in the strategic
weapons negotiations to limits on the Reagan administration's
space-based missile defense system.
   The Soviets have said that some research on the system,
officially known as the Strategic Defense Initiative and popularly
called ``Star Wars,'' violates the ABM treaty, but their public
statements have not made clear where they draw the line. The U.S.
has rejected the Soviet call for limits on the program.
   U.S. officials in Washington said early this month that the
chief U.S. aim at the review conference would be to get the Soviet
side to ``correct its violations of the ABM treaty.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said that if the Soviet
position on Krasnoyarsk does not change at the review conference,
``the president will consult with the Congress and our allies
concerning next steps.''
   Karpov, the Soviet delegation chief, said upon arrival Saturday
that his side is prepared to discuss the Krasnoyarsk radar. He said
the Soviets were ``ready to demonstrate in practice our consistent
adherence to the ABM treaty.''
   Moscow will insist on ``the preservation of the ABM treaty
intact as it was signed in 1972,'' he said, apparently referring to
the Soviet position that the ``Star Wars'' program threatens the
treaty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
