<1ST_LINE>u a PM-FlagBurning     08-24 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Flag Burning,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Man Guilty In Flag-Burning Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury today convicted a man of burning
an American flag outside an armed forces recruiting station during
a demonstration.
   William C. Cary Jr., a 22-year-old member of the Naval Reserve,
could receive up to a year in prison. No sentencing date was set.
He remained free on $1,000 bond.
   Cary testified Tuesday that he set fire to the flag in
Minneapolis in March to show his discontent with President Reagan's
decision to send troops to Honduras.
   ``I don't necessarily agree with what my government was doing,
but that doesn't make me less of an American or less of a
patriot,'' said Cary, who at the time of his arrest worked in a
used clothing store.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Thor Anderson said the act was a show of
contempt for the flag. ``This case is not about political
beliefs,'' he told the jury.
   ``There are ways one can be legally contemptuous,'' he said.
``One can stand on a podium and shout or sing. But Congress has
said that for certain reasons you can't be contemptuous of the
flag.''
   Cary, dressed in garb made from a U.S. flag, was arrested during
a large protest in which demonstrators used bowling balls and rocks
to break windows at the recruiting office. He was charged with
burning a flag in public.
   Cary testified that a woman he didn't know handed him one end of
a flag she was carrying and asked for his help in burning it. He
said he used his own lighter and he and the woman laid the burned
flag in front of the recruiting office doorway.
   ``It seemed like an appropriate gesture,'' he testified. ``I
knew there were cameras there. I knew I could get people's
attention that way.''
   Anderson said proceedings are under way to expel Cary from the
Naval Reserve, of which he has been a member since age 18.
</TEXT>
