<2ND_LINE>AM-Preaching Kids,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Preaching Children To Be Taught At Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father whose children repeatedly have been
suspended from school for preaching at its gates has not ruled out
legal action against the system, which has agreed the young
evangelists can be taught at home.
   David Strode said in an interview Wednesday his children _
Duffey, 11, Pepper, 7 and Matthew, 6 _ will be removed from
Eastfield Elementary School. But he said he will not sign a
document releasing the system from possible legal action.
   ``McDowell County schools rejected the Bible, so I reject
them,'' he said.
   Strode, himself a street preacher, said he and his children will
continue preaching, although he said he expects the town ``to take
some kind of action'' in response.
   ``They're trying to shut me down,'' he said.
   Under North Carolina law, Strode has 30 days to set up a
home-education plan.
   Strode, 40, an unemployed machinist, had said he didn't want to
run a home school, but he said Wednesday it appeared to be the only
solution.
   ``I'm just glad they (the children) are out of there,'' he said.
   The children are happy with the decision, Strode said.
   ``The problem ain't the kids,'' he said. ``It's the parents and
the teachers. It's hard to fool kids. Parents' hearts are much
harder. An adult's conscience is much harder than a child's.''
   The decision to take the children out of school came after
daylong negotiations between school officials and Caleb Campaign, a
Chicago-based Christian civil rights organization representing the
Strodes.
   ``We pretty much got what everybody wanted,'' said Dan Rodden,
president of Caleb Campaign.
   Rodden said his organization would help with the home education
program and even help Strode find a job.
   The Strode children's first day of school Monday lasted less
than a minute and ended with Duffey being suspended for 10 days. At
the school gate, Duffey and Matthew began to shout Bible verses and
Pepper yelled ``Repent.''
</TEXT>
