<HEAD>Ford Introduces New Thunderbird, Cougar</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to CORRECT that changes are in
wheelbase rather than overall length. PICKS UP 7th graf pvs,
`Analyst Joseph ...'; A version also moved on the financial wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. today introduced a 1989
Thunderbird with a longer wheelbase and wider tread width and a
Cougar that rides an inch closer to the ground.
   In addition, a supercharged, 3.8-liter, V-6 engine is available
on some models of the two cars.
   ``Ford is again going to have the hottest cars,'' said auto
analyst Ronald Glantz of Montgomery Securities Inc. of San
Francisco.
   However, Glantz said Ford's plans to increase capacity may cut
into its sales, which set an industry record at $1.66 billion
during the second quarter of this year.
   Ford said the 1989 Thunderbird, which led the way five years ago
when the company moved toward automotive aerodynamic styling, will
have a 9-inch longer wheelbase and wider tread width than the year
before.
   The Mercury Cougar wheelbase is 9 inches longer, too, but its
overall length is 2 inches shorter.
   Other Ford and Lincoln-Mercury models introduced today in
Cambridge, Mass., by Ford executives showed more subtle changes, if
any.
   Analyst Joseph Phillippi of Shearson Lehman Hutton of New York
said Ford's strong sales and production concerns accounted for the
relatively few changes.
   Ford is the nation's second-leading automaker behind General
Motors Corp.
   The Big Three automakers _ GM, Ford and Chrysler Motors Corp. _
will be introducing new models through September.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
