<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Tampering     08-24 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tampering,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>County Prosecutor Won't Charge Cyanide-Capsule Killer With Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stella Nickell, convicted in federal court of
using cyanide-laced pills to kill her husband and a stranger, will
not face state murder charges, prosecutors said.
   Mrs. Nickell was convicted of product tampering in U.S. District
Court last May, and was sentenced to 90 years in prison.
   Dan Donohoe, spokesman for King County Prosecutor Norm Maleng's
office, said Tuesday that Maleng determined that ``substantial
justice was already done'' in the federal court sentence.
   ``The sentence is probably as much as she would have gotten for
a state murder conviction,'' Donohoe said.
   He also said Maleng thoroughly checked the case and noted a U.S.
Justice Department opinion stated the conviction would withstand
appeal.
   Maleng also said that, if necessary, he could impose a murder
charge at a later date since there is no statute of limitations.
   The charges against Mrs. Nickell, 44, of Auburn, stemmed from
the June 1986 deaths of her husband, Bruce Nickell, 52, and Sue
Katherine Snow, 40, also of Auburn. Both died after taking
cyanide-laced Extra-Strength Excedrin capsules.
   Besides putting tainted pills in a bottle of capsules used by
her husband, Mrs. Nickell was accused of placing poison pills in
capsule containers on store shelves to make her husband's death
appear to be at the hands of a random killer.
   She stood to gain about $100,000 more in life insurance policies
if her husband died by other than natural causes.
   The deaths touched off a nationwide tampering scare and caused
Excedrin manufacturer Bristol-Myer to recall the brand.
</TEXT>
