<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CyprusTalks     08-24 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyprus Talks,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek, Turkish Cyriot Leaders To Meet On Island Reunification</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek and Turkish Cypriot leaders agreed Wednesday
to meet next month for unconditional talks aimed at reunifying
their war-divided island.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar held a working
lunch for Greek Cypriot leader George Vassiliou and Rauf Denktash
of the Turkish Cypriot side in which he said the two men pledged
``a determined and sustained effort'' to resolve issues that have
long divided Cyprus.
   Vassiliou and Denktash said the meeting ``created a new
opportunity for finding a just and lasting solution of the Cyprus
problem,'' the U.N. leader told reporters.
   ``It was a good beginning, we made progress on the procedural
issues,'' said Vassiliou, recently elected president of the
internationally recognized Cyprus government.
   It was Vassiliou's first meeting with Denktash, president of the
breakaway Turkish Cypriot state established in the Turkish-occupied
part of the island, which is only recognized internationally by
Turkey.
   Denktash also seemed satisfied by the meeting, saying Vassiliou
was ``a good talker and negotiator.''
   The Cyprus problem arose first in the wake of intercommunal
clashes in 1963 that led to the dispatch of a United Nations peace
force to the island. It was aggravated in July 1974 when Turkey
invaded and occupied 37 percent of the island in the wake of a coup
by supporters of union with Greece.
   Denktash's unilateral declaration of independence in November
1983 was declared legally invalid by the U.N. Security Council,
which demanded its abrogation.
   Previous negotiations between Denktash and former Cypriot
President Spyros Kyprianou broke down in December 1985.
   Kyprianou had insisted the negotiations follow the
implementation of United Nations resolutions demanding the
withdrawal of the estimated 30,000 Turkish troops from north Cyprus.
   ``I believe we will be able to find ways of settling the various
problems. He is different from Kyprianou,'' Denktash said.
   Denktash, however, indicated the question of troop withdrawal
was likely to be the biggest stumbling block.
   Denktash on Wednesday reiterated his position that there can be
no withdrawal ``before the dissolution of the illegal Cyprus
government,'' and its replacement by a joint Greek-Turkish Cypriot
administration.
   A senior U.N. official close to the negotiations said the
meeting ``went better than we expected and the two leaders got
along very well indeed.''
   ``We are sure they have already laid the foundations of fruitful
future negotiations,'' the official added, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Perez de Cuellar said negotiations between the two Cypriot sides
will start Sept. 15 in Nicosia. The venue will be a hotel in the
UN-patrolled no-man's-land splitting the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
sectors of the city for 25 years.
   He added that the two leaders will meet again Sept. 16 and
``recognized that the success of these talks depended on their
personal and continuous involvement.''
   The two also agreed to meet with Perez de Cuellar in New York
``after the first rounds of meetings in Nicosia to review the
progress achieved during this initial stage,'' he added.
   Greek and Turkish Cypriot sources revealed that the Nicosia
talks would be carried out on an intensive daily basis and that the
New York meeting would be held at the end of October.
   Perez de Cuellar said the two leaders also had reaffirmed their
committment to agreements reached between 1977 and 1984 for the
settlement of the Cyprus problem through the establishment of a
bizonal federation.
   The other major outstanding issues involve the implementation of
a series of U.N. resolutions ignored by Turkey.
   These demand the repatriation of 50,000 mainland settlers from
north Cyprus and the return of 200,000 Greek Cypriot refugees,
one-third of the island population, to their homes there.
   The two sides, however, disagree on constitutional aspects and
the powers of the central government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
