<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Defense     08-24 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Defense,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Chief Resigns After Sub Collision Kills 30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Japan's Defense Agency resigned
Wednesday to take responsibility for a submarine collision that
killed 30 people aboard a sports fishing boat last month.
   Tsutomu Kawara, fighting back tears, urged his successor to take
steps to restore public confidence in the Self-Defense Forces after
a series of accidents.
   ``Many innocent lives were lost in an extremely regrettable
accident ... in which the defense force was one of the parties
involved,'' Kawara told reporters after handing in his resignation
to Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita.
   Kawara, 51, who served as director-general for 10 months, said
his successor, Kichiro Tazawa, should ``take over the
responsibility of ensuring that such an accident never occurs
again.''
   Tazawa, installed as agency head Wednesday night, said in a
televised news conference that pursuing a safer armed forces would
be his major goal.
   The fishing boat, the 154-ton No. 1 Fujimaru, was rammed in the
side by the massive Nadashio naval submarine on July 23. Japanese
were outraged when television reports and witnesses' accounts
revealed crew members standing on the submarine and watching people
drown.
   ``While defense has grown ... increasingly important for our
country, there have been a large number of incidents involving the
Defense Agency,'' Kawara said.
   The submarine crash brings the number of military accidents this
year to 11 and the death toll to 32. Critics say public confidence
in the military is waning in a country where the armed forces have
rarely been popular.
   Kawara becomes the first Defense Agency director-general in 17
years to relinquish his post in a controversy involving to the
armed forces.
   In 1971, Keikichi Matsuhara resigned to take responsibility for
the deaths of 162 people when a military plane collided with a
commercial domestic airliner in northern Japan.
   It is customary for high-ranking business executives or
government officials to assume responsibility for a major incident
and resign as a means of restoring public confidence in the
institution they represent.
   Two other defense agency officials _ Defense Agency deputy head
Seiki Nishihiro and Adm. Shuichiro Higashiyama, chief of staff of
the Maritime Self-Defense Forces _ also indicated they would resign
after the submarine collision, but Kawara reportedly refused to
allow them to step down.
   Takeshita attended a memorial service Wednesday in Tokyo for the
30 victims of the submarine collision and reaffirmed that the
government would take steps to prevent accidents and provide
compensation for the victims' families.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
