<DOCNO> AP880824-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GunClubPollution     08-24 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gun Club Pollution,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dispute Over Pollution Threatens 76-year-Old, Lakefront Gun Club</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gun enthusiasts who have been shooting clay
targets along Chicago's lakefront for generations are under fire
from the parks agency and citizens groups who say the 76-year-old
club is polluting Lake Michigan.
   Patrons of the Lincoln Park Gun Club situated two miles from
downtown argue that it is a unique part of the lakefront's heritage
and one of few places in the city where people from all walks of
life can compete on equal ground.
   But the Park District and others complain of lead shot, clay
targets and plastic wads from shotgun shells.
   A Park District committee takes up the issue tonight, said Nancy
L. Kaszak, an attorney for the agency.
   The skeet and trap shooting club was founded in 1912, when
patrons showed up in straw hats and three-piece suits. Now, they
wear everything from hunting clothes to shorts.
   Membership costs $220 per year, and members can shoot for $3 per
round while non-members must pay $6.
   The club on city-owned land pays upkeep but no rent, said club
manager Ed Bishop. It has 386 members but more than 5,000 people
come to shoot every year.
   ``It's an integral part of the lakefront and an example of the
diversity of this city,'' said John Madonia, a 41-year-old health
care executive who came to the gun club with his father more than
20 years ago.
   ``It doesn't make any difference how much money you make _ if
you don't hit the target, it doesn't break,'' added John Mickey,
club vice president.
   Club officials acknowledge that the plastic wads cause litter
but said the organization is willing to hire people to pick up them
up. They also said the lead shot, wads and clay targets do not
pollute the water.
   ``It's more a litter problem than a pollution problem,'' Bishop
said.
   ``The gun club says it's litter, but we say it's water
pollution,'' argued Theodore Denning, manager of the Chicago field
office of the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency's division
of water pollution.
   Denning said that the clay and shot do not appear to threaten
marine life but that state law requires Illinois waters be free of
debris.
   Opponents of the club also say it is a safety hazard. ``We have
concerns about the operation and usage of guns in such a highly
dense park facility,'' Ms. Kaszak said.
   Bishop said the club's record speaks for itself. ``We've been
here 76 years and we've never have an accident,'' he said. ``You're
safer here than you are in a golf course.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880824-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1523EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Guild-Dukakis     08-24 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guild-Dukakis,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Guild Gives Non-Unanimous Endorsement to Dukakis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Newspaper Guild on Wednesday qualified its
backing of Democrat Michael Dukakis' presidential candidacy,
declaring a 15 percent abstention primarily because of opposition
by wire service employees to any political endorsements.
   Three of the AFL-CIO's 90 other affiliated unions _ the Air Line
Pilots Association, the Teamsters and the Marine Engineers _ voted
to abstain their entire memberships in the labor federation's
formal endorsement of Dukakis.
   The Marine Engineers for three decades have opposed making a
presidential endorsement and the Air Line Pilots said they had not
had a meeting of their executive board on making an endorsement.
   Teamster President William McCarthy, whose union endorsed Ronald
Reagan in 1980 and 1984, said he was abstaining on a presidential
endorsement until after a mail poll of his union's members is
completed in mid-September.
   Newspaper Guild President Charles Dale said his union's
executive board and convention in June ``gave its blessing'' to a
presidential endorsement.
   But primarily because of uproars in the past from its
1,000-member Wire Service Guild local, he told the AFL-CIO's
general board that he was casting only 21,390 votes for a Dukakis
endorsement and voting his union's 4,000 other members as
abstaining.
   ``At least one of our locals _ the Wire Service Guild,
representing employees of Associated Press and United Press
International _ has a policy of dissassociating itself from any
political endorsements by this international,'' he said. ``So I
note that our vote does not carry with it the support of members of
that local.''
   In 1983, The Newspaper Guild had cast all of its members' votes
in favor of the AFL-CIO's early endorsement of Walter Mondale.
   The following week the Wire Service Guild formally dissociated
itself from that endorsement, saying that because it represents
reporters who cover political campaigns, it should refrain from
taking sides in them.
   The local based its action on a membership referendum conducted
in 1973 following the parent union's presidential campaign
endorsement a year earlier of Democrat George McGovern.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880824-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1529EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen     08-24 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Suggests Quayle Too Immature For High Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee
Lloyd Bentsen suggested Wednesday that his Republican counterpart,
Dan Quayle, lacks the maturity required of someone who might have
to lead the country.
   ``I don't think America can risk youthful indiscretion in
someone who could become our president at any moment,'' Bentsen,
67, told the Southern Legislative Conference in Lexington, in his
toughest attack on the 41-year-old Quayle.
   The Texas senator referred to a speech that Quayle made earlier
this week before the Veterans of Foreign Wars in Chicago, where
Quayle blamed ``youthful indiscretion'' for his opposition to
Senate legislation that would establish a Cabinet-level Department
of Veteran Affairs.
   The Indiana senator told the VFW he was reversing that position.
Bentsen said that was an example of how Quayle would behave if he
were in the White House.
   ``A youthful indiscretion? My friends, that vote occurred only
five weeks ago,'' Bentsen said. ``I don't think America can risk
youthful indiscretion in someone who could become our president at
any moment.''
   At a news conference after his speech, Bentsen made a veiled
reference to Quayle's decision to seek entry into the National
Guard in 1969 during the Vietnam War. Bentsen, whose son joined the
Guard one year earlier, has refused to attack Quayle directly on
that issue.
   Asked about Quayle, Bentsen, a former World War II bomber pilot,
said:
   ``I certainly don't think he's too young. But I think that you
have to have some maturity.
   ``And I think that the breadth of experience that I've had, and
the tests that I've undergone, some of the things that happened to
me early on, in combat, make you grow up pretty fast.''
   Quayle's quick switch on the VA bill showed that he didn't have
``the continuity of judgment that you would expect,'' said Bentsen,
who supported the veterans bill which the Senate approved July 12.
   Bentsen said he was ``not stepping up criticisms of his
(Quayle's) personal life,'' and he made no mention of allegations
involving Quayle's association with former lobbyist Paula Parkinson
during a Florida golfing weekend in 1980.
   But Bentsen said he was ``just getting started'' comparing his
record and experience with Quayle's.
   Asked if he thought Quayle would still be on the GOP ticket in
November, Bentsen replied: ``I hope so.''
   Quayle received a warm reception from the Southern legislators,
many of them pro-Reagan Democrats, not long after Bentsen addressed
them. The two candidates met briefly at the Lexington airport,
where Bentsen said he had just ``warmed up the crowd'' for Quayle.
The two shook hands and laughed.
   In his speech, Bentsen criticized Republican nominee George
Bush's assertion that he would create 30 million new jobs in eight
years. Bentsen said there were only 6.5 million people looking for
work.
   ``The only way you'd get 30 million jobs is to take away the
border patrol and move one-third of Mexico here,'' he said. ``Or
raise the working age to 80.''
   Bush's statement was another example of ``voodoo economics,''
Bentsen said.
   ``There is no real alternative to the honest, able leadership of
Mike Dukakis,'' Bentsen said. ``Mike Dukakis is right for the South
_ take it from a Texan.''
   From Lexington, Bentsen flew to Louisville and visited a senior
citizens home. The Senate Finance Committee chairman talked about
his efforts toward enacting a catastrophic health insurance law.
   He told about 300 residents of Dosker Manor that despite their
talk of helping the elderly, the Republicans had tried to cut back
programs for seniors.
   ``Don't just read their lips, see what they do,'' he said,
twisting a phrase that Bush used had used in his acceptance speech
at the GOP National Convention in New Orleans about opposing tax
increases.
</TEXT>
