<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TheGraduate     08-24 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-The Graduate,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Graduate' Author Nearly Destitute</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Woodstock Festival, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AB4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man whose book ``The Graduate''
became the smash-hit movie of an idealistic generation says he is
nearly destitute, living out of a van and trying to make ends meet
on a few thousand dollars a year.
   ``It's hard to make anybody believe the author of `The Graduate'
needs money,'' said Charles Webb, 49, who says his abhorrence of
materialism led him to give away two houses in his salad days.
   Hard times, however, have driven Webb and his ex-wife, an artist
who calls herself Fred, out of the California campground where they
lived for the last decade to the Massachusetts town where Webb went
to college 30 years ago.
   He came East, he said Wednesday, in hopes of finding a publisher
for his latest project, a compilation of writings on prejudice. His
plight, however, has taken him to a welfare office in North Adams,
which rejected him because he has no permanent address.
   ``The things he stands for and believes in are principles he
can't live by any longer,'' said Fred, 48, who still lives with her
ex-husband.
   The novelist, whose hero in ``The Graduate,'' Benjamin Braddock,
struck a chord among young readers with his post-graduate misery at
his parents' suburban home, has lived until now according to what
friends consider impossibly high and even self-destructive
standards.
   ``If he's hard up for dough, it's obviously due to ... his
inclination toward divestiture,'' said Eric Davis, a college
classmate who teaches at the private Commonwealth School in Boston.
   Webb said he gave a Hollywood house to a real estate agent in
the 1960s and another home to the Massachusetts Audubon Society in
1970, because he felt the need for ``getting free of things.''
   Getting free also explains his and Fred's decision eight years
ago to get a divorce although they had no intention of separating.
Fred said the couple felt marriage violated their constitutional
freedoms.
   The couple were married in 1962, the year ``The Graduate'' was
published and a year after his graduation from Williams College.
Webb, son of a California doctor, epoused odd views even back in
college, Davis said.
   ``We always used to wonder whether Chuck was putting us on,''
Davis said. ``He's quite sophisticated, a very intelligent person
with a real heart, but he always said things that sounded
peculiarly simple.''
   Webb says he received only $20,000 for the film rights to ``The
Graduate,'' which made a star of Dustin Hoffman when it came out in
1967. The novel, however, is still in print and continues to earn
him a few thousand dollars in royalties annually.
   ``The Graduate'' was followed by four other novels, including
``The Marriage of A Young Stockbroker,'' which also was made into a
movie. His last work, ``Booze,'' was published in 1978.
   That year, Webb took his two sons, then in the sixth and ninth
grades, out of school and went ``underground'' because of his fear
that schools were harming their minds.
   After a year in France, the Webbs moved to Ventura County in
California, where they remained, living in their van, until they
returned to Massachusetts a few months ago.
   Webb said he stopped writing during that time, reluctantly
accepting support from his mother, to raise his sons and
concentrate on larger issues, such as prejudice.
   ``I came to feel that writing fiction was a more narrow concern
than addressing problems that went beyond my narrow,
career-oriented goals,'' he said.
   Both sons are now in graduate school, one studying Russian and
the other art. ``I hope that's an indication they are going to be a
little more stable than their parents,'' Webb said.
   But he added that he doesn't regret the unusual life that led to
his present situation. ``It's hard to think there would be another
way to do it.''
</TEXT>
