<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     08-24 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tensions Between Moslem Factions High After Zia's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pakistan-Analysis, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces armed with machine
guns prevented sectarian violence Wednesday as thousands of Shiites
marched through Pakistani cities and beat themselves to observe a
major Moslem holy day.
   The marches came one week after the death of President Mohammed
Zia ul-Haq, a Sunni Moslem whose policies drew criticism from
hard-line Shiites. The cause of the plane crash that killed Zia is
not known, but sabotage is suspected.
   Sectarian friction between Shiite Moslems, a small minority, and
the majority Sunni Moslems typically increases on Ashura, which
marks the death almost 1,400 years ago of the prophet Mohammed's
grandson, Imam Hussain.
   About 30 people have died this year in Sunni-Shiite gun battles
in northern Pakistan, according to news reports. Tension rose in
early August after the assassination by unidentified gunmen of
Pakistani Shiite leader Arif Hussain al-Hussaini in the northwest
frontier city of Peshawar.
   New clashes were reported in the region after Zia died Aug. 17
in a plane crash that also killed U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel and
28 others.
   The Shiite procession in Peshawar and other major cities went
off without incident and disbanded before dusk Wednesday.
   During the processions fervent Shiites beat their chests and
flogged their backs with switches of razor-sharp metal to show
devotion to the martyr.
   In the southern port of Karachi, the country's largest city, up
to 40,000 Shiites marched through the main district in observance
of the Ashura holiday, but no violent incidents were reported.
   About 20,000 police, paramilitary units and army regulars
dressed in full battle gear lined Karachi's streets along the
procession. They drove vehicles mounted with machine guns and kept
watch from rooftops on the seven-mile route.
   In Lahore, Pakistan's second-largest city, another procession of
40,000 people peacefully made its way along tightly guarded city
streets.
   Authorities imposed curfew-like conditions along the route, with
residents ordered to stay indoors and not look out their windows, a
witness said.
   Acting President Ghulam Ishaq Khan and other government leaders
had made pleas for sectarian harmony on the eve of Ashura.
   Pakistan officials say they believe Zia's death was a result of
sabotage but have not said who they think is responsible. Some
officials have hinted at agents of neighboring Afghanistan's
pro-Soviet government. An investigation by American and Pakistani
officials is being conducted.
   Zia, a Sunni, instituted Moslem law in Pakistan, but hard-line
Shiites claimed the program did not take into account their form of
jurisprudence. Pakistan's Shiites also disapproved of Zia's close
ties to the United States, which has has long had icy relations
with Shiite-led Iran.
   A flurry of political activity has followed Zia's death as
political leaders prepare for crucial nationwide elections
scheduled for November.
   Opposition leader Benazir Bhutto on Tuesday called on Ishaq Khan
to dismiss the Cabinet and appoint a caretaker government until
elections. Thirteen of the 16 Cabinet ministers were appointed by
Zia.
   Ms. Bhutto leads the country's largest opposition party, the
Pakistan People's Party, and has expressed confidence that if
elections were conducted fairly, her group would win. She has
demanded the government rescind Zia's order that all candidates run
unaffiliated with a party.
   In 1977, a coup led by Zia ousted Ms. Bhutto's father, Prime
Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto. Two years later, Zia had the former
official executed.
</TEXT>
