<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChildrenAttacked     08-24 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children Attacked,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Held In Attack On Son, Suspected In Daughter's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the parents of 12-year-old Sarah
Caldwell buried their strangled daughter, their 10-year-old son was
close to dying from stab wounds.
   The next evening, when the children's often-distraught father
disappeared, the family feared J. Robert Caldwell might harm
himself and police issued an all-points bulletin.
   Then, several days later, the 41-year-old Caldwell was arrested
at the apartment of a co-worker and charged with attempted murder
in the Aug. 16 attack on his son.
   Prosecutors said laboratory results will determine whether the
father may also be charged with the murder of Sarah, who was
strangled and raped.
   Caldwell appeared in court Wednesday and asked for a
court-appointed lawyer. No bail was set.
   The day after Sarah's burial and again Tuesday, police talked to
her younger brother, Ben, about the attacks that occurred after
Mrs. Caldwell left the family's home. She found the children when
she returned home.
   Ben Caldwell, who lost four pints of blood and was found
face-down in a bathtub, wasn't told of his sister's death until a
week after the attacks.
   The boy had been stabbed repeatedly in the back, apparently with
scissors.
   Cobb County District Attorney Tom Charron said the warrants for
Caldwell were based on interviews with the boy and other evidence,
but he would not reveal what the boy told investigators.
   ``There is a lot of evidence and no inconsistencies,'' he said
at a news conference Tuesday night.
   Family members described Caldwell as prone to leaving home.
   ``He was a good father. He just had this problem of skipping
whenever the pressures got tough,'' said Lill Anderton, Caldwell's
mother-in-law.
   ``There's a lot of unanswered questions, ... an awful lot,''
said father-in-law B.L. Anderton. ``And I don't know if I want to
know the answers.''
   Caldwell's mother, Bertha Padgett, said it was common for her
son to vanish for six or seven months at a time.
   Family members said Caldwell left his wife shortly after Ben was
born and didn't return for years. Although the couple had been
divorced, they had lived together since 1986, the family members
said.
   Mrs. Padgett said Caldwell dropped out of high school to join
the Navy, was rebuffed because of his age but joined a year later
and eventually returned to Georgia to marry a woman 10 years his
senior. She died of pneumonia.
   Caldwell served time in jail on abandonment charges after his
first wife swore out a warrant against him, his mother said.
</TEXT>
