<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     08-24 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike at Key Mine in Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 workers went on strike at
a key mine in southern Hungary on Wednesday, demanding restoration
of cuts in bonuses and changes in a new income tax, state radio
said.
   The strike at the Mecsek mine near Pecs marked the first known
worker protest against the stringent economic policies of Karoly
Grosz since he became Communist Party leader in May.
   State radio said agreement was reached to restore the cut
bonuses and that some strikers resumed work. Other strikers, said
to include more than 300 miners and an unspecified number of office
workers, would wait until Thursday, it was reported.
   The radio reported the strikers threatened to stop work again if
parliament does not vote to iron out a quirk in a new tax law that
gives some workers on sick benefit more net income than those
working normally.
   The strike coincided with labor unrest in Poland, but appeared
unconnected.
   Reports of strikes have been extremely rare in communist
Hungary, although there were scattered reports of labor unrest in
1969, 1977 and 1980-81.
   Wednesday's relatively swift reporting of the miners' stoppage
appeared to reflect the greater openness of state-run media under
Grosz.
   The state news agency MTI said the stoppage began Tuesday night,
when 150 miners refused to start the evening shift at the Istvan
pithead in the Mecsek colliery at Komlo, 10 miles north of Pecs
near the Yugoslav border.
   The day shift of 150 miners also refused to go into the pit head
and the stoppage spread to ``several other sections,'' state radio
said.
   The state news agency MTI called the stoppage ``a pure
industrial dispute with no political undertones.''
   Komlo is Hungary's only mine producing high-grade black coking
coal for the Danubian iron works, one of the nation's three main
iron and steel mills.
   MTI said one grievance of the striking miners was computation of
personal income tax introduced Jan. 1 as part of Grosz's efforts to
curb Hungary's $18 billion gross foreign debt and to stimulate the
economy.
   Hungary's official trade unions have criticized the policies,
saying workers, pensioners and the unemployed must be protected
against inflation, already running at 18 percent this year.
   Miners are among the most militant workers in Hungary.
   The official trade union organization SZOT protested Wednesday
against a provision in the new tax system that means workers on
sick leave can end up with more net income than those who work
regularly.
   Government spokesman Gyorgy Marosan said without elaborating
that this was an anomaly the government soon would fix.
   The miners' other main complaint was that the new tax system has
sliced annual bonuses by 30 percent to 50 percent, radio said.
   Gyula Zipper, deputy industry minister, told state radio it
would be up to parliament to decide whether to change the tax law,
but that companies should make up bonuses to last year's levels.
Banks should give credits for this to companies posting a deficit,
Zipper said.
   This appeared to weaken recent government statements that
enterprises would have to turn a profit or face closure as a result
of reduced state subsidies.
</TEXT>
