<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DCSchools     08-24 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DC Schools,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>D.C. Officials Unveil Plan to Upgrade School System.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new effort to improve the capital's
beleaguered public schools will give principals broader power and
eliminate some of their bosses, officials announced Wednesday.
   ``We've been a top-down organization, and we want to put more
authority and responsibility where the action is,'' school
superintendent Andrew Jenkins said. ``We are going to make the
local school principal more responsible.''
   Special and bilingual education programs also will receive more
attention, the superintendent said.
   Jenkins was appointed head of the city's schools in May under a
contract that required him to overhaul the school system. He
pledged Wednesday that the new plan would be put into effect by
February, 1989.
   Various national surveys have ranked the capital's public
schools near the bottom of the list for urban areas. One study, by
Charles Harrison, former director of the Education Writers
Association, gave the district's 88,000-student school system a
grade of 17 out of a possible 100 after comparing attendance rates,
average SAT scores, teacher-student ratios, dropout rates and the
number of college-level courses offered in 52 metropolitan school
systems.
   Only Oakland and Hillsborough County schools near Tampa, Fla.,
rated lower than the capital's school system.
   Jenkins had no cost projections for the new program, but
promised the school system would stay within its $623 million
budget for fiscal year 1989, which begins Oct. 1.
   One major change is that the position of ``regions'' _
adminstrators responsible for overseeing several schools at once _
will be eliminated. Instead, the principals of each school will
report directly to Jenkins or a yet-to-be-appointed vice
superintendent.
   ``After awhile, all bureaucracies become out of sync,'' Jenkins
said. ``They need to be put back together.''
   Although he provided no specific figures, Jenkins said other
less visible administrative positions would be eliminated. Those
employees will be reassigned within the system instead of being
dismissed, Jenkins said.
   ``At the end of the school year, I expect to see tangible
progress'' in standardized achievement scores,'' the superintendent
said.
</TEXT>
