<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Trial,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight Leftist Terrorists Sentenced To Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERZINCAN, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 300 people accused of belonging
to an outlawed Marxist terrorist group were convicted Wednesday by
a military court following a six-year trial, a news agency said.
   Eight of the defendants were sentenced to death, 14 received
life in prison and another 270 received jail terms ranging from one
year to 20 years, according to the independent Huriyet News Agency.
The court acquitted another 434 people.
   All of the defendants were charged with belonging to the violent
and outlawed Marxist group Dev-Yol (Revolutionary Path). The group
was responsible for plotting a coup in the 1970s from the Black Sea
Coastal town of Fatsa, Turkey's first Marxist community.
   Charges against the defendants included 103 political killings,
36 murder attempts, kidnappings, bombings and armed robberies. The
agency gave no breakdown of the convictions.
   The alleged leader of the group, Fikri Sonmez, a tailor and
elected mayor of Fatsa, died of a heart attack in jail two years
ago.
   Violence involving leftist and rightist extremists and security
forces claimed at least 5,000 people from 1978 to 1980.
</TEXT>
