<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-24 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael G. Metkin won a heated competition
this week when a furnace stored in his garage was dubbed the oldest
of its kind in the city.
   The 64-year-old Metkin, a tool and die maker, was one of 200
people who responded to a contest to find the oldest Atlas furnace.
   His round coal-burning furnace was built in 1925 by Atlas
Heating and Ventilating, a San Francisco company that later became
the biggest builder of gas furnaces in the United States, said Bob
Tuck, the company's retired president.
   Atlas, which invented the first gas blower furnance and gas
safety pilot light, was at its height from the mid-1930s to World
War II. It sponsored a contest to find the oldest of its products
as a way of celebrating its 80th anniversary.
   ``That may be junk to others, but it's treasure to me because it
played an important part of life here,'' said city archivist Gladys
Hansen, who hopes to take the door from the furnace and put it on
display in the local history room of the public library.
   Metkin said the furnace was never converted to gas and has sat
unused in his garage. ``Even though I never used it, something told
me to save it,'' Metkin said.
   For winning the contest, Metkin gets a new $3,000 heating system.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long Island's search for a catch phrase
is nearing an end.
   Members of the Long Island Tourism and Convention Board held a
private meeting Tuesday in Riverhead to choose a slogan to promote
tourism.
   The board reviewed a list of 25 slogans culled from more than
7,500 entries. Ideas poured in after an advertising campaign
sponsored by the commission and the Long Island Rail Road.
   The winning slogan is expected to be announced next week. The
author will receive a three-day vacation and services selected from
a list of contest sponsors.
   According to sources close to the contest, three front-runners
have emerged. They are:
   _ Long Island _ Land for all seasons.
   _ Long Island _ Love it by land, love it by sea.
   _ Long Island ... naturally!
</TEXT>
