<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1948EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Firefighters'Test     08-24 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Firefighters' Test,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State: St. Paul Firefighters' Test Discriminates Against Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE LAHAMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The physical abilities test for city
firefighters appears designed to ensure that women won't pass, said
the state Human Rights commissioner.
   ``It is not a test that finds the best possible firefighters,''
the commissioner, Stephen Cooper, said Tuesday. ``It's a test for
just a few qualities. It would be like if I was going to hire you
to be an over-the-road trucker and the only thing that I tested you
for was the ability to eat french fries.''
   Cooper said his investigators looked at firefighters'
examinations in several major U.S. cities. The result was a report
issued Tuesday in which an unidentified fire chief in another city
was quoted as saying, ``If you were going to design a test to
exclude women, you'd end up with the St. Paul test.''
   The report concluded there was probable cause that
discrimination against women took place, Cooper said.
   A complaint was filed after all 17 women who took the test in
May failed to pass. They had all passed a separate written exam.
   A judge temporarily halted the hiring of St. Paul firefighters
pending the investigation by the Human Rights Department.
   Cooper said the next step is to try to resolve the dispute
through an informal conciliation process with city officials. If
that is unsuccessful, he said, litigation is a last resort.
   Assistant City Attorney Terry Sullivan said neither he nor other
city officials would comment immediately. ``We'll respond in the
next several days as to what approach we're going to take,'' he
said.
   Cooper's report said the test was unfair to female applicants
and is discriminatory even in the absence of an intent to
discriminate.
   The city failed to meet its burden of showing that its
methodology is valid and that the extreme effect it has on women is
justified, he said.
   ``There is no evidence that a person's score on the physical
test is predictive of his-her future job performance as a
firefighter,'' Cooper said.
   Cooper said the timed test measured only sprinting ability and
upper body strength, areas in which men excel while ignoring
stamina, an area in which women can perform well. A ladder climb
and blindfold maze race, events in which women can often outrun
men, were not rated for speed but scored on a pass-fail basis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
