<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1950EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     08-24 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0762</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliamentary Deadlock Could Cause New Fighting In Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bitter feud among lawmakers over
Syria's role in Lebanon has prevented the election of a new
Lebanese president and could rekindle the nation's 13-year war
between Moslems and Christians.
   Parliamentary deputies representing the 80 percent of Lebanon
controlled by Syria, the nation's main power broker, and its Moslem
militia allies want a president willing to crush Syria's main foe,
the right-wing Lebanese Forces.
   The Lebanese Forces _ the Christians' main militia which has
links to Israel _ is blocking re-election of former president
Suleiman Franjieh, a Christian branded by political rivals as
``Syria's candidate.''
   ``Should a constitutional vacuum develop, one can kiss Lebanon
goodbye,'' said Christian politician Shaker Abu Sleiman.
``Lebanon's fate is at stake,'' said parliamentary deputy Joseph
Skaff, also a Christian.
   Franjieh, 78, governed from 1970 to 1976. He is the front-runner
in a lackluster field of candidates that includes Dany Chamoun, son
of the late Camille Chamoun, another former president.
   Behind the friction lie old hatreds.
   Franjieh holds the Lebanese Forces leader, Samir Geagea,
responsible for killing his son Tony, Tony's wife and 3-year-old
daughter along with 30 others in a raid on the family's summer
mansion in June 1978.
   Geagea opposes Syria's strategy of seeking political reforms
that would give Moslems equal power with the Christians, who have
dominated the government, judiciary and army since independence
from France in 1943.
   Back then, the Christians were considered the majority.
   Now, Moslems comprise about 55 percent of Lebanon's 4 million
people and Christians make up 45 percent.
   In July, just 38 of the 76 members of Parliament attended a
session to elect a new president, far short of the quorum needed.
   All but two of the deputies who turned up were Moslems. They
accused the Lebanese Forces of physically preventing Christian
deputies from attending. No date for a new session has been set.
   There have been no parliamentary elections in Lebanon since
1972. The 99-seat house has simply renewed its mandate every two
years.
   The Lebanese Forces pledged: ``There will be no quorum so long
as Franjieh is a candidate.'' But the Syrians declared they still
back Franjieh.
   ``Syria's staunch support for Franjieh against local, regional
and international powers is a very risky move that could plunge
Lebanon into all-out violence,'' said a foreign diplomat who
demanded anonymity.
   A Moslem politician, who asked not to be identified, said: ``If
the spirit of challenge persists, we might not have a president by
Sept. 23.''
   That's when the six-year term of the incumbent president,
Maronite Catholic Amin Gemayel, expires. Under constitutional
rules, Gemayel, 46, cannot run again for a consecutive second term.
   The politician noted: ``Franjieh, whether candidate or
president, means war. If elected, he'll launch war on the Lebanese
Forces, and if not elected, he'll launch war on them.''
   After more than a decade of war and the fragmentation of Lebanon
into a cluster of sectarian cantons, Gemayel's authority is limited
to his own stronghold in the Metn mountains.
   The Lebanese Forces control the rest of the shrunken Christian
enclave.
   Syria and its Moslem allies have boycotted Gemayel for 2{ years,
since he torpedoed a Syrian-brokered peace accord under which the
Christians would surrender some of their power.
   Lebanon's acting prime minister, Salim Hoss, a Sunni, went to
Damascus on Wednesday for talks with Syrian leaders on the
presidential deadlock, a senior government official said in Beirut.
``He will certainly discuss with the Syrian command what should be
done if a president is not elected by Sept. 23,'' the offcial
added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Despite their differences, most Lebanese factions believe a
constitutional vacuum will be disastrous.
   Under an unwritten national covenant, dating back to
independence, the president has to be a Maronite, the prime
minister a Sunni Moslem and the House speaker a Shiite Moslem.
   Beirut's independent An-Nahar daily said Gemayel would form an
interim government headed by a Maronite prime minister if a
president is not elected before Sept. 23. The 1943 covenant allows
a Maronite to be named prime minister if the presidential post is
vacant.
   But 10 Syrian-backed leftist and Moslem factions warned they
will prevent such a government from running the country.
   Besides Franjieh, a warlord whose private army controls north
Lebanon, none of the other half-dozen Christian contenders appears
to have much of a chance.
</TEXT>
