<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NewspaperMinorities     08-24 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspaper Minorities,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>16 Percent on Newspaper Payrolls Are Minority Members, Survey Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0683 to restore keyword line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks and other racial minorities constitute
16 percent of the workforce of American newspapers, but only 8
percent of the news and editorial staffs, according to the American
Newspaper Publishers Association.
   The ANPA survey, made public Wednesday, also said that 37
percent of the papers' employees are women.
   In the nation's overall workforce, minorities constitute 21
percent and women 47 percent of the total.
   The study suggested that the newsroom was the place in a
newspaper plant were minorities were least likely to be found. Ten
percent of newsroom employees were members of minorities, and, when
clerical and administrative workers were subtracted, the number
dropped to 8 percent, according to ANPA spokesman Joe Lorfano.
   That finding approximates the results of an annual survey
conducted by the American Society of Newspaper Editors.
   In April, the 1988 ASNE survey found blacks, Hispanics,
Asian-Americans and American Indians constituted 7.02 percent of
newsroom employees, a slight increase from the 6.56 percent level
in 1987 but a sharp increase from the 3.95 percent in the survey's
first year, 1978.
   The ASNE survey was based on responses from 1,092 of the
approximately 1,645 daily newspapers published in the United States.
   In the ANPA study, responses came from 546 of the 1,443 daily
newspapers that were sent questionnaires.
   The study, conducted by Belden Associates of Dallas, was
undertaken to give the association ``a benchmark to measure the
effectiveness of our programs to assist individual newspapers in
their efforts to increase employment and promotion opportunities
for their employees,'' said Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, chairman of the
ANPA and publisher of The New York Times.
   It was the first industrywide attempt to determine the racial
composition of all departments in newspapers.
   The survey said that minorities constitute 22 percent of the
employees in newspapers' general management _ including executive,
professional, technical, clerical and service workers. They were 19
percent of the production workers and 19 percent of circulation
workers; 17 percent of those in accounting, finance and information
services; 13 percent of those in advertising and 11 percent in
marketing, promotion and research.
   The ANPA said its Minority Opportunity Committee, chaired by Jay
Smith, publisher of the Atlanta Journal and Constitution, is
considering establishing a computerized national employment program
to allow newspapers to list minoritiy job opportunities.
</TEXT>
