<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     08-24 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenians Renew Annexation Campaign for Disputed Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Nagorno-Karabakh residents rallied
around their legislative building Wednesday while the deputies
inside discussed grievances in the disputed region.
   The actions ended a month of relative quiet in Nagorno-Karabakh,
an enclave of mostly Christian Armenians located within the Soviet
republic of Azerbaijan, near the border with Turkey and Iran. From
February to July, the residents went on strikes and street protests
to demand that jurisdiction of their region be moved from
predominantly Moslem Azerbaijan to the Soviet republic of Armenia.
   The campaign subsided in late July after the central leadership
rejected the demand.
   Wednesday's report of many thousands of people gathered outside
the Nagorno-Karabakh legislative building in Stepanakert came from
the state-run radio station in Yerevan, the Armenian capital. The
broadcast was monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp. in London.
   The Soviet news agency Tass reported ``an all-city meeting'' at
which the opinions of work collectives were expressed.
   The legislature appealed to Moscow to consider the opinions of
these work collectives and ``the wishes expressed by deputies''
about the administrative subordination of the region, Tass said.
This appeared to be a veiled reference to earlier demands for
Nagorno-Karabakh to be placed under the control of Armenia.
   A resident of Stepanakert said by telephone that people massed
Wednesday to renew the annexation demand. But the telephone
interview was cut off before the resident, a woman, could identify
herself. Other calls to Stepanakert and the Azerbaijani capital,
Baku, did not go through.
   The Nagorno-Karabakh legislature also approved a new plan to
improve the social and economic conditions in Nagorno-Karabakh by
1995, Tass said. So far, the program was being implemented
``unsatisfactorily,'' the legislature declared.
   The lawmakers also approved plans for strengthening the region's
economic ties with business enterprises in Armenia, and called for
closer cooperation with the republic in ``spiritual and cultural
life,'' Tass said.
   Nagorno-Karabakh was made part of Azerbaijan in 1923 although
more than three-quarters of its residents are ethnic Armenians.
They claim economic, cultural and religious discrimination under
Azerbaijani rule.
   The Presidium of the Communist Party's Central Committee in
Moscow on July 18 said Nagorno-Karabakh should remain part of
Azerbaijan, but it set up a commission to consider changes in its
territorial status. The area is now classified as an autonomous
region of Azerbaijan.
   The Presidium sent a representative, Arkady I. Volsky, to
Nagorno-Karabakh to help local authorities improve living
conditions. Tass said without elaborating that he attended
Wednesday's session of the Soviet of People's Deputies.
</TEXT>
