<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle-Guard     08-24 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Guard,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Guardsman Passed Through Enlistment Process Quicker Than
Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indiana National Guard official said
Wednesday that it took less time for an unemployed truck driver to
be sworn into the Guard than it did Dan Quayle, who has been
accused of using family influence to secure a spot with the Guard
and avoid the Vietnam War.
   It took retired Sgt. Stephen W. Morell three days to complete
processing and Quayle, the Indiana senator who is the Republican
vice presidential nominee, 11 days, Guard records show.
   Morell, who says he dropped out of college and walked into a
recruitment office, was offered a clerk-typist's position three
days after undergoing preliminary testing on May 19, 1969.
   Morell served side-by-side with the Quayle, who records show was
placed 11 days after he was tested May 8, 1969.
   ``We entered the Guard the same rank and left the Guard the same
rank. And I was a nobody,'' Morell told The Associated Press.
   Capt. Cathi Kiger said how quickly recruits pass through
preliminary processing, such as aptitude tests, interviews and
physical examinations, often depends on the schedule of the person
undergoing the tests.
   ``Enlisting can take anywhere from a week to a year,'' she said.
``We try to accomodate their schedules.''
   Kiger said 348 non-prior-service recruits and 92 prior-service
recruits wre enlisted during fiscal year 1969. The Guard lost 902
enlisted men during that year, she said.
   Reports that Quayle entered the Guard with the help of his
family's influence have dogged his campaign.
   ``If his family really had all this influence like everyone
says, he would have been sent directly to officer's candidate
school and come out a lieutenant or captain,'' Morell said of
Quayle, whose maternal grandfather, Eugene C. Pulliam, published
several newspapers in Arizona and Indiana.
   ``Dan was an OK guy,'' Morell said. ``He did his job, and I did
mine. We washed dishes and washed jeeps together.''
   Morell said he would not have found it particularly
objectionable had Quayle received preferential treatment.
   ``If someone would have offered me a hand, I would have shaken
it and said thank you,'' he said. ``I don't want to insinuate he
got a hand, but if he was offered help, any fool would say thank
you. And Dan isn't any fool.''
   Morell said he was forced to drop out of college at Indiana
University for financial reasons and, began considering the
National Guard.
   ``If you weren't a full-time student, you were full-time draft.
There was no in-between,'' he said.
   ``I figured I might as well stay at home, do my weekend a month
and get married,'' Morell said.
   Kiger said the service was below its authorized strength when
the then-22-year-old Quayle signed up.
   ``I can find no evidence that he was given special consideration
and there was no need,'' Kiger said. ``Units that were not up to
100 percent strength could continue to recruit.''
   But Maj. Gen. Alfred Ahner said Tuesday that he received a call
at that time regarding Quayle from Wendell Phillippi, managing
editor of The Indianapolis News, a Pulliam newspaper. Phillippi was
a retired Guard major general.
   Ahner said he contacted the Guard's personnel office on Quayle's
behalf.
   ``They said they had a couple of spaces,'' Ahner said Tuesday.
``I said hold one of them, there's a good guy coming over.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
