<DOCNO> AP880824-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola     08-24 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Negotiators Meet With Officials Over Withdrawal Of Cuban
Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S., South African, Cuban and Angolan
officials met Wednesday to negotiate a timetable for withdrawal of
50,000 Cuban troops from Angola.
   No statement was issued after the four parties met for three
hours, but reporters were told they would meet again Thursday. A
Soviet and United Nations' representative were present in the Congo
capital, but did not attend the talks.
   Chester Crocker, U.S. Assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, met separately with South Africa and the Cuban and Angolan
delegations before the four-party talks began.
   In Luanda, Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos said the
possibility of peace in Angola has never been nearer since rebels
took up arms against the Portuguese colonial army for independence
of the southern African nation in 1961.
   ``Never as now, since the historic morning of Feb. 4, 1961, has
peace for our heroic and suffering people been so visible on the
horizon,'' dos Santos told members of the People's Assembly, the
country's representative body, in an Angolan news agency report.
   Cuban troops have supported Angola in fighting U.S. and South
Africa-backed UNITA rebels in a guerrilla war against the
Marxist-oriented Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola
government. The war has continued since Angola gained its
independence from Portugal in 1975.
   Jonas Savimbi's guerrillas of UNITA, which stands for National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, have not been involved
in the talks. The Angolan government refuses to negotiate with
UNITA, calling them bandits and stooges of South Africa.
   UNITA also has refused to adhere to the cease-fire agreement,
which was signed Monday on the Angolan-South-West African frontier
by military representatives from South Africa, Angola and Cuba.
   Savimbi's forces have received support the last year from the
United States. President Reagan's administration has pressed Angola
to negotiate with UNITA, saying that no complete peace could be
reached without such a reconciliation.
   Dos Santos said disagreement exists over the timetable for
withdrawal of Cuban troops _ ``South Africa wants them to be out in
12 months, the United States wants 36 months, and Angola and Cuba
have proposed 48 months.''
   But, dos Santos continued, ``all indications are that an
agreement on a timetable will be possible.''
   In Lisbon, news reports have raised the possibility that
Portuguese troops could participate in an international
peace-keeping force in the region.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar was quoted by the
French newspaper Le Monde as saying he would accept South Africa's
invitation to visit that country if the Brazzaville talks go well.
   South Africa has said it will withdraw its troops from southern
Angola, where they have supported anti-Marxist rebels as well as
pursued black nationalists seeking to drive them from South-West
Africa, by Sept. 1. This was to be the first phase leading to
elections and independence for South-West Africa, also known as
Namibia.
   But South Africa insisted on a Cuban withdrawal within a year,
saying their continued presence in Angola would pose a threat after
South-West Africa is granted independence.
   In Cape Town, South Africa, President P.W. Botha said Wednesday
that the new leadership of Mikhail S. Gorbachev has prompted the
Soviet Union to throw its support behind the peace initiative in
Angola and South-West Africa.
   ``The Gorbachev factor is important,'' Botha told Parliament.
   ``This does not mean that the Russians have relinquished their
plans for world domination and have become the world's friendly
neighbor,'' Botha said. ``What it does mean is that Mr. Gorbachev
has realized that the Russian economy cannot support the extremely
expensive involvement in remote regions of the world.''
   The Soviet Union has provided the weaponry for Angola's Marxist
government.
</TEXT>
