<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Yugoslavia Quakes,0121</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quakes Damage Villages In Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two strong quakes shook central
Yugoslavia in the past two days, cracking the walls of some village
homes, it was reported Wednesday.
   The first tremor, at 2:22 a.m., measured 3.4 on the Richter
scale and was centered near the town of Duvno, about 70 miles west
of Sarajevo, according to the Tanjug news agency.
   On Tuesday, a quake with a reading of 4.6 on the Richter scale
was recorded in the same area, the city's observatory said.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause
slight damage in the immediate area.
