<HEAD>With AM-Angola</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINDHOEK, South-West Africa (AP) _ A black bishop who heads the
Anglican Church in South-West Africa was hit by rubber bullets
Wednesday as territorial police confronted student protesters,
local journalists said.
   Bishop James Kauluma was hit on the leg and back by rubber
bullets, sustaining brusies, after he arrived outside the school,
reporters said.
   The state-run radio said 11 people were arrested during the
incident at a secondary school in Katutura, a black township
adjacent to Windhoek, capital of the South African-ruled territory
commonly known as Namibia. An earlier report said up to 40 students
were arrested.
   The protesters reportedly advocated a boycott of classes in
solidarity with pupils in northern Namibia, where a school boycott
has been under way for several months to press demands that
military bases be moved away from schools.
