<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Reagan-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0636 08-24 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0636,800</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Bush remarks, rally; pick up 6th graf
pvs bgng ``Reagan heaped...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan touted Republican
presidential nominee George Bush today as a man of action for whom
the backup role of vice president ``didn't come easily.''
   ``George Bush is a man of action _ a man accustomed to
command,'' Reagan said at a Reagan-Bush rally at the hotel where
the president is staying during a break from his California ranch
vacation.
   Bush renewed his criticism of Democrat Michael Dukakis' veto of
a Pledge of Allegiance bill, saying that if confronted with such a
measure he would have left it up to the U.S. Supreme Court to
determine whether it was constitutional.
   ``What is it about the Pledge of Allegiance that upsets him so
much?'' Bush asked.
   Dukakis in 1977 vetoed a bill that would have penalized any
school teacher who failed to lead the pledge every morning.
   ``I would have signed the bill,'' Bush said. ``Any
constitutional question that some might raise should be decided by
the Supreme Court of the United States.''
   Before the rally, Reagan and Bush met privately for 15 minutes
with approximately 50 California supporters and GOP leaders.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater and Bush press secretary
Sheila Tate, in a joint statement, said Bush told the group, ``We
will not give away one inch of ground in this state.'' They quoted
Reagan as urging them to ``saddle up and ride hard to exert every
bit as much energy for George as you did for me.''
   Reagan praised Bush at the rally, saying ``The vice presidency
doesn't fit easily on such a man. But George Bush is also a
patriot. And so he made it fit, and he served with a distinction no
one has ever matched.''
   ``I once said he is a great vice president, but I know and I've
seen that it didn't come easily,'' the president said.
   Reagan made no reference to the controversy surrounding the GOP
vice presidential candidate, but he said, ``Dan Quayle stands for
the same principles as George Bush and I do.''
   Reagan heaped scorn on the Democrats in his speech, saying they
had fielded ``a three-headed ticket that doesn't know left from
center'' _ a reference to presidential nominee Michael Dukakis,
running mate Sen. Lloyd Bentsen and runnerup Jesse Jackson.
   ``They talk about reaching for the center, but on issues like
national defense, they've taken positions that only a McGovern
could love,'' he said, reaching back to 1972 when liberal Sen.
George McGovern of South Dakota was the Democratic presidential
nominee.
   On Tuesday, Reagan signed a landmark trade bill on a pier at
Long Beach and spoke at a rally in Irvine for Republican Sen. Pete
Wilson of California.
   As he left the platform in Long Beach, the president replied
with a firm ``No'' when asked whether Bush should drop his running
mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, from the ticket.
   ``He's a fine man and well qualified for the job,'' Reagan said
of Quayle, who is the center of controversy over his military and
academic record.
   California Sen. Alan Cranston, the second-ranking Democrat in
the Senate, was among officials on the platform as Reagan signed
legislation designed to reduce U.S. deficits in world trade.
   The president's signature climaxed three years of skirmishing
between the White House and Capitol Hill, but clearly did not mark
an end to partisan debate over the trade issue.
   ``In 1981, George Bush and I arrived in Washington committed to
getting government out of your way,'' Reagan told an audience of
port officials, dock workers and others.
   Using an old nautical term, Reagan described the U.S. economy as
yare, meaning ``easy to handle, quick to respond, bright, lively.''
   ``This bill will allow us to provide up to a billion dollars a
year for retraining workers to adjust to our turbo-charge economy _
an economy that, with the right leader, will remain yare,'' he said.
   In his fund-raising address for Wilson, who is challenged by
Democratic Lt. Gov. Leo McCarthy, Reagan said, ``America is not
going to trade away our winning team for third-stringers with a
weak defense, a foreign policy of errors, curveball campaign
promises, a set of policies to be named later, and billions of
dollars in higher taxes.''
   The speech is expected to be the first of many on behalf of GOP
Senate candidates as well as the Bush-Quayle ticket.
   The president has two political appearances _ for California
Republicans in Thousand Oaks and for Rep. Robert Lagomarsino in
Santa Barbara _ scheduled Saturday on his way back to his ranch.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president also is expected
to visit eight to 15 cities on behalf of GOP candidates after he
returns to Washington on Sept. 6.
</TEXT>
