<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1658EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burundi     08-24 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burundi,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burundi Army Still Fighting In North Where Thousands Were
Massacred</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burundi's ruling party on Wednesday
threatened to deal a ``death blow'' to instigators of tribal
warfare that left 5,000 people dead and sent about 40,000 fleeing
across the border.
   The refugees pouring into Burundi's northern neighbor, Rwanda,
claim the Burundi army, which along with the government is
dominated by the minority Tutsi tribe, is taking part in a mass
slaughter of the nation's majority Hutu tribe.
   A U.N. official said there was evidence refugees were wounded by
troops. But a senior Western diplomat in Burundi said ``the idea
the army is massacring Hutus, burning huts, etc., is just not what
we're hearing here.''
   ``Non-governmental sources, including missionaries coming down
from the north, say the army is acting with a great deal of
restraint,'' said the diplomat, who spoke on condition his name not
be used.
   But he said the army ``still is engaged in fighting with
dissident Hutus.''
   The ruling Union for National Progress party issued a statement
vowing ``to deal a death blow to outsiders who have been inciting
peaceful Burundians to cause trouble in the country,'' according to
state-run Radio Burundi.
   The statement did not refer directly to refugees' claims of army
involvement in a slaughter, but urged Burundians to desist from
listening to ``foreign propaganda and false reports by foreign
media.''
   The Hutu People Liberation Party, an exiled opposition group,
has charged that Burundi's military massacred thousands of Hutus.
   The government has denied the accusations and claims 5,000
people were killed in a slaughter instigated by exiled Hutus who
infiltrated the tiny central African country to inflame anti-Tutsi
sentiment.
   Despite making up nearly 85 percent of Burundi's 5 million
people, the Hutu are subservient to the Tutsi, who comprise the
remaining 15 percent and dominate the government and army.
   The Hutu and the Tutsi are longtime enemies. Following an
abortive 1972 coup attempt in the former Belgian colony, the Tutsi
massacred more than 100,000 Hutu, including most of the tribe's
intelligentsia, according to human rights groups.
   As of Tuesday, about 38,000 refugees had fled into Rwanda since
the violence began Aug. 14, and an estimated 5,000 peasants
continue to cross the border daily, said Code Cisse, the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees representative in Rwanda.
   ``We saw many people who had been injured by bullets and
bayonets,'' Cisse said in a telephone interview. ``They said they
were fleeing because they didn't want to get shot by the military.''
   Most of those fleeing are members of the Hutu tribe, said Cisse,
who visited border areas over the weekend.
   Rwanda, a densely populated and impoverished nation, has
appealed for international aid to cope with the influx of refugees
which it says are straining its meager resources.
   Burundi, meanwhile, has promised to work with those who fled to
Rwanda and to make possible a speedy return home.
   Details about what sparked the current violence are sketchy.
   Refugees told Cisse the unrest began Aug. 5-6 with local
opposition to an army attempt to arrest some Hutu, although the
mass killing did not start until more than a week later.
   Diplomats in Burundi, however, said they understood Hutu
initially turned on Tutsi.
   The region where most of the killing took place is in Burundi's
north, a remote hilly and marshy region, around the farming
communies of Ntega and Marangara. The army has since sealed off the
region.
   The government has restricted travel between towns, enforced a
dusk-to-dawn curfew nationwide and banned meetings of more than
five people.
   The massacre was the first reported violence since Maj. Pierre
Buyoya seized power in a bloodless coup Sept. 3, 1987, while former
President Jean-Baptiste Bagaza was attending a Francophone summit
in Canada.
   Burundi covers an area about the size of Maryland. About 6
million people live in slightly smaller Rwanda. There, the
Hutu-Tutsi percentages are roughly equal, although the Hutu
dominate the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
