<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle-Manion     08-24 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Manion,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Defended By Controversial Federal Judge and Friend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court judge once
branded by opponents as unfit for the federal bench said Wednesday
the smooth political career of his law school friend, Dan Quayle,
left ill-prepared to handle controversy.
   Daniel A. Manion, a Vietnam veteran and conservative Republican,
dismissed questions about Quayle's Vietnam-era service in the
National Guard and a claim by former Washington lobbyist Paula
Parkinson that Quayle propositioned her during a 1980 Florida
vacation.
   Manion said Quayle should remain on the Republican ticket as
George Bush's running mate. But he said Quayle's political career
might have gone better if Bush had chosen someone else.
   ``He walked into this thing unimpeded,'' Manion said.
   Quayle scored upset victories over incumbent Democrats to win
seats in the House and Senate and easily won re-election to the
Senate in 1986.
   ``From a guy who could walk down the street unrecognized, bang,
he's suddenly put in the spotlight,'' Manion said. ``He was
unprepared, and that's probably not a very good way to put a vice
president in.''
   Manion became a controversial figure when President Reagan
nominated him in 1986 for an appeals court judgeship. Opponents on
the Senate Judiciary Committee attacked him as poorly qualified and
ideologically extreme.
   It was Quayle who telephoned Manion's South Bend law office from
Capitol Hill to tell him of his narrow confirmation victory.
   Manion, a former Army supply officer in Vietnam in 1966, said
questions about Quayle's use of family influence to enter the
National Guard and avoid Vietnam combat in 1969 dealt with
``obscure things'' that should not prevent government service.
   Manion also defended Quayle's emotional response to Ms.
Parkinson's claim that he propositioned her eight years ago.
   ``He's a strong family man,'' Manion said. ``He's not one of
these philanderers who goes looking for lost weekends. He is a
golfer and that's why he went.''
   Manion and Quayle attended the Indiana University School of Law
together. Manion was graduated a year ahead of Quayle in 1973.
``Very personable, nice fellow,'' Manion said. ``He was just kind
of an average guy.''
   Manion said he expects the controversies over Quayle to fade,
and would advise the Republican ticket to ride out the storm.
   ``I say, man, you're on the horse, you ride it,'' he said. ``It
may not be the one you thought had the speed, but you hope it's got
the endurance.''
</TEXT>
