<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Rollins,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actor Pleads Innocent To Cocaine, Drunk Driving Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Howard Rollins Jr., through his
attorney, pleaded innocent Wednesday to charges of possession of
cocaine, driving while intoxicated and speeding.
   State Judge Freddie Pitcher Jr. agreed to waive the presence of
the 37-year-old actor and allowed attorney Jim Boren to enter the
plea.
   The judge didn't set a trial date.
   Rollins was arrested in March while he was in Louisiana filming
the NBC television series, ``In the Heat of the Night.''
   A trooper reported Rollins was driving more than 100 mph on
Interstate 12. Police said they found two bags of a substance which
turned out to be cocaine.
   Rollins, of Baltimore, had leading roles in the films
``Ragtime'' and ``A Soldier's Story.''
