<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Laffer-Bush     08-24 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Laffer-Bush,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservative Economist Questions Bush's Promise of 30 Million Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative economist Arthur B. Laffer on
Wednesday questioned Republican nominee George Bush's goal of
creating 30 million new jobs in eight years as president.
   At a news conference for GOP Senate candidate Joseph Malone,
Laffer said 20 million jobs in eight years might be an attainable
figure.
   Bush's goal is ``a large number'' and an estimate ``that I would
not have made,'' Laffer said.
   ``Whether 30 million is a reasonable or optimistic goal or not,
the point is you want to keep those jobs going, keep that
prosperity going,'' he said.
   The 48-year-old economist is best known for the ``Laffer Curve''
which holds that beyond a certain point, increasing taxes won't
increase government revenues because high taxes slow down the
economy.
   Bush talked about creating 30 million new jobs in his acceptance
speech at the Republican National Convention in New Orleans last
week. He spoke of his goal of creating ``30 in eight _ 30 million
new jobs in the next eight years.''
   On Tuesday, Bush's aides retreated somewhat from the vice
president's declaration. They said Bush used 30 million as a goal
rather than a promise.
   The Labor Department's Bureau of Labor Statistics recently
projected a growth of 18.4 million jobs over the next 12 years.
   ``That 30 million I don't think is a number you should focus
on,'' Laffer said. ``Twenty million would get the point across.''
   Laffer, a Californian and member of President Reagan's Economic
Policy Advisory Board, questioned Democratic nominee Michael
Dukakis' contribution as governor to the economic growth of
Massachusetts.
   Laffer said the Dukakis administration created its own deficit
problems by overestimating tax revenues in the state. But Laffer
agreed with Dukakis that more should be done to collect delinquent
federal taxes.
</TEXT>
