<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--GeneticFlower     08-24 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Genetic Flower,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Genetic Research Produces New Flower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commercial flower growers will have a new,
genetically engineered dwarf version of the long-stemmed lisianthus
by next spring, the Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
   Roger H. Lawson of the department's Agricultural Research
Service said the deep-purple lisianthus may be the first commercial
flower developed through biotechnology research.
   he dwarf lisianthus will be sold as potted plants, rather than
seed, and will be available in April 1989, he said. It will be made
available by the Society of American Florists and USDA.
   Lawson, who heads up a new floral crops program funded jointly
by USDA and the floral society, said the new plant bears several
tulip-sized blooms at once, is a 6- to 10-inch mutation of a
2-foot-tall lisianthus that is popular in many parts of the world
as a cut flower.
   Wild lisianthus grows throughout the American prairie region, he
said.
</TEXT>
