<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2234EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Rains     08-24 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Rains,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rains On Atlantic Coast Leave 25,000 Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains this month flooded about
25,000 people out of their homes on the isolated Caribbean coast
and destroyed thousands of acres of subsistence crops, officials
said Wednesday.
   Reynaldo Antonio Tefel, Minister of Social Welfare, said the
majority of those affected are Indians who live mostly on corn and
whatever else they can grow.
   He said 37 tons of food had been sent to the area and the
government is asking the United Nations and the Red Cross for help.
   Barricada, the newspaper of the ruling Sandinista party, said
Switzerland and Norway plan to donate food and other aid.
   The remote, jungled region is home to about 155,000 people, most
of them Suma, Rama orMiskito Indians. Many of their wooden homes
are built on stilts to avoid damage by floods when rivers rise
during the rainy season.
   A preliminary survey by the National Emergency Commission showed
90 percent of the area's crops were destroyed, Tefel said, and
``this means those 25,000 people will need food for the next six
months.''
   He said the leftist Sandinista government was short of funds
because of economic difficulties created by the 7-year-old war the
U.S. backed rebels.
   Red Cross spokeswoman Salome Valle estimated 80 percent of the
corn, yucca and bean crops were damaged. She said the Red Cross had
provided shelter to about 3,000 people.
</TEXT>
