<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ConventionCoverage     08-24 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention Coverage,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservative Group Accuses TV Networks of Pro-Dukakis Bias</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative media watchdog group accused
the four major television networks Wednesday of displaying
``blatant anti-conservative bias'' in their coverage of the
Democratic and Republican nominating conventions this summer.
   L. Brent Bozell, founder and chairman of the Media Research
Center, said his group analyzed 100 hours of prime-time coverage on
ABC, CBS, NBC and CNN and found ``a seriously flawed double
standard'' among the networks.
   The media ``let Michael Dukakis get away with murder'' at the
Democratic convention in Atlanta by failing to report on issues,
Bozell said.
   At the Republican convention in New Orleans, he said, ``the
media spent too much time looking for scoops'' when they should
have been reporting on issues.
   The Media Research Center rated CNN best of the four networks it
studied, followed by NBC, ABC and CBS.
   Bozell's group looked at the ideological labels network
reporters and commentators used, their choice of who to interview,
the types of questions they asked, which if any controversies they
highlighted and whether the coverage was valuable to the viewer.
   Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, the controversial GOP vice
presidential candidate, was the subject of 432 of the 889 questions
posed by network questioners during prime-time coverage of the New
Orleans convention, Bozell said.
   Of 190 citations of all GOP controversies, he said, there were
140 mentions of Quayle's service in the Indiana National Guard
during the Vietnam War.
   By comparison, he said, there were only four mentions of
controversy during the Democratic convention. He said there were
three comments about the ethics investigation of House Speaker Jim
Wright and one on vice presidential nominee Sen. Lloyd Bentsen's
former fund-raising breakfast club for lobbyists.
   Bozell said said the Quayle issue would not have come up 140
times if questions had been answered better initially. ``If the
Bush people had handled it better, there's no question'' that fewer
questions would have been raised, he said.
   Robert Lichter, co-director of the non-partisan Center for Media
and Public Affairs, said Quayle's selection during the convention
made it inevitable that he would be scrutinized quickly and
intensely by reporters.
   Lichter blamed the focus on Quayle partly on the Republicans.
   ``The Republicans handed the material to the media, who then
proceeded to tailor it,'' he said. ``If Quayle had had the right
answers at the beginning, he could have defused a lot of this
controversy.''
   Lichter has been analyzing ABC, CBS and NBC political coverage
since the start of the primary season. He said network coverage of
the two parties ``pretty well balanced out'' during the primaries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
