<DOCNO> AP880824-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1748EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-AFL-CIO-Dukakis     08-24 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AFL-CIO-Dukakis,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kirkland Says Dukakis Getting Solid Support Within Ranks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO officially endorsed Michael
Dukakis for president on Wednesday, and labor leaders said they can
deliver the Massachusetts Democrat a margin of 2.5 million union
votes in November.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland told Dukakis the endorsement
``represents our commitment to work for you in every state in the
union,'' but a spokesman for Republican George Bush called the
endorsement ``a classic dog bites man story.''
   The presidents of the labor federation's 91 affiliated unions
voted 95.7 percent of their 14.1 million members in favor of a
Dukakis endorsement, with only three unions abstaining entirely.
Not a single union worker was counted in the AFL-CIO tally as
favoring an endorsement of Republican George Bush.
   However, among those unions abstaining was the largest, the 1.6
million-member Teamsters, who in 1980 and 1984 endorsed Ronald
Reagan after making no presidential endorsement in 1976.
   Newly installed Teamster President William McCarthy of Boston,
who sources in the union say personally dislikes Dukakis, said he
is withholding an endorsement until a mail poll of his members is
completed Sept. 16.
   Asked if the Teamsters could endorse Bush, an official in the
union said, ``I just don't see it.''
   ``If the poll comes back strong for Dukakis, we'll probably
endorse him,'' said the Teamster official, speaking on the
condition of anonymity. ``If it's close, we'll probably remain
neutral.''
   The 30,000-member Air Line Pilots Association and the
40,000-member Marine Engineers union also voted to abstain from
making a presidential endorsement. The Newspaper Guild voted 4,000
of its 25,390 members as abstaining primarily because of opposition
to any endorsement by its Wire Service Guild local.
   Kirkland had estimated earlier that the federation's endorsement
of Walter Mondale in 1984 was worth a net 2 million votes despite
exit polls showing that as many as 47 percent of voters from union
households cast their ballots then for Reagan.
   ``Our rule of thumb is that we have to do two-thirds or better
in order to be successful in the election,'' he said. ``We fell
short of that. I'm reasonably confident that the results this time
will be improved.''
   Bush campaign spokesman Mark Goodin, calling the endorsement ``a
classic dog-bites-man story,'' said, ``Every four years the AFL-CIO
trots out what has become an obligatory endorsement of a Democratic
presidential candidate and 1988 is obviously no exception.''
   Communications Workers President Morton Bahr said four polls of
his union's members in the past year show that those who voted for
Reagan in 1984 _ a slight majority, according to political
operatives in the union _ ``are coming home to the Democratic
party.''
   United Auto Workers President Owen Bieber said a poll of his
union's members in July and August at 28 sites showed 96.9 percent
favoring a Dukakis endorsement.
   ``Obviously we had a lot of people in 1980 and 1984 who made a
mistake,'' Bieber said, citing the loss of hundreds of thousands of
jobs in the past seven years, including a 52 percent decline in
farm and heavy equipment factories alone. ``The attitude of our
members has changed.''
   The 1.3 million-member United Food and Commercial Workers, which
has a higher concentration of Republicans than most unions, said
its latest telephone poll showed a two-to-one edge for Dukakis
among those members who had made up their minds.
   ``For the first time in four years, a majority of our members
classify themselves as Democrats with fewer than 24 percent calling
themselves Republicans,'' said UFCW President William Wynn, who
noted that his union's members split even on Mondale and Reagan
four years ago.
</TEXT>
