<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Navy-Cannibalism     08-24 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy-Cannibalism,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Skipper Believes He Acted Properly, Attorney Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy skipper believes he acted properly in
declining to take aboard a boatload of Vietnamese refugees who
later reportedly turned to cannibalism to survive, the officer's
attorney said Wednesday.
   ``The captain is confident that what he did was correct given
the facts and circumstances,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Ron Petronio, the
attorney for Capt. Alexander G. Balian, who provided supplies to
the refugees.
   Balian, 48, of Los Angeles faces a possible court-martial for
alleged dereliction of duty.
   Balian informed the Navy Tuesday that he would exercise his
right not to attend an ``admiral's mast'' disciplinary hearing that
had been scheduled for Wednesday before Vice Adm. George Davis,
head of the Pacific Fleet's surface forces.
   Under military law, Davis now must decide whether to drop the
matter or order an Article 32 hearing. Such a hearing, similar to a
civilian grand jury proceeding, is the first step in a full
military court-martial.
   ``It's not that he would not get a fair hearing, because he
would have. But the nature of the (admiral's mast) proceedings are
such that they're not public'' and Balian's side of the story would
not have come out, Petronio said.
   Balian, who was skipper of the amphibious landing ship USS
Dubuque, is charged with failing to render appropriate assistance
to the refugees and violating a standing order to aid and rescue
refugees found at sea in life-threatening situations. He was
temporarily relieved of command Aug. 13.
   The charges were prepared for Balian's administrative hearing
and could be changed if a court-martial is ordered.
   According to Navy officials, the Dubuque encountered the refugee
boat June 9 in the South China Sea while en route to the Persian
Gulf.
   Balian gave the refugees several hundred pounds of supplies,
including food, water and navigational aids, but didn't take the
estimated 110 people aboard because he judged their vessel
seaworthy, according to the Navy.
   The refugees, who left Ben Tre in southern Vietnam on May 22,
were at sea 37 days before fishermen from the Philippines rescued
them on June 28. Only 52 survived.
   Some of the survivors have been quoted as saying they killed and
ate some of their fellow passengers to stay alive after they
encountered the Dubuque on June 9. Two of the victims reportedly
died of starvation, but three others allegedly were murdered
through drowning and then eaten.
   The Navy and the United Nations High Commission on Refugees are
investigating the reports.
   Petronio said Balian would have no comment until the Navy
decides whether or not to proceed with a court-martial.
   ``He's a very loyal Navy officer who's not going to buck the
system,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
