<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1759EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AIDSDrug Bjt   08-24 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Drug, Bjt,0769</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Grant For AIDS Drug To Expire Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal payments for the drug AZT are running out for about
6,000 AIDS patients nationwide, and many may be forced into poverty
to qualify for the life-prolonging drug under Medicaid, officials
said Wednesday.
   A one-time, emergency appropriation of $30 million was enacted
by Congress last summer to help those AIDS patients who couldn't
afford the $8,000-a-year treatment, had inadequate health insurance
and made too much money to qualify for Medicaid.
   About a fifth of all AIDS patients in the country are receiving
AZT under the grant, according to Richard Schulman of the Federal
Health Resources and Services Administration.
   AZT, or azidothymidine, has been shown to prolong the lives of
some AIDS patients but has severe side effects.
   Because few states have taken action to continue funding, many
of those patients may be forced to ``spend down until they reach
Medicaid level,'' Schulman said.
   ``You use your own resources until you're out of money and you
qualify for Medicaid, which can be pretty devastating,'' he said.
``That's what's going to happen, I have no doubt about it.''
   AIDS activists have criticized the states for not continuing the
program. The federal program technically expires Sept. 30 when the
government's fiscal year ends, but states with surpluses at that
time will be allowed to continue supporting their AIDS patients
until their AZT money runs out, officials said.
   In Florida, the money has already run out, despite extra funds
voted by the Legislature.
   ``Congress made it very clear to the states that they needed to
pick up the slack once this (federal) program expired,'' said Jeff
Levi, executive director of the National Gay and Lesbian Task
Force. ``It is unfortunate that the states have waited until the
last minute to react.''
   Levi suggested that Congress enact ``some type of matching
program'' during the transition to state funding.
   ``It doesn't make a lot of economic sense to have people who are
working to stop working ... and go on Social Security so they can
get Medicaid to get a very expensive drug that may not work,'' said
Larry Kessler, director of Boston's AIDS Action Committee.
   So far, only the District of Columbia has actually appropriated
money to continue the program after the grant expires, Schulman
said.
   The fiscal 1989 budget includes $250,000 for emergency drug
assistance, says Jane Silver, who administers the district's AIDS
office. However, the district's budget still must be approved by
Congress.
   While no state has acted to continue AZT funding for all those
receiving it under the grant, six states _ Arkansas, Florida,
Kansas, Louisiana, Missouri, and Texas _ have changed their
Medicaid rules to cover the drug for the poorest patients.
   Only in Alabama and Colorado is AZT not paid for by Medicaid.
   The $30 million AZT grant was disbursed proportionately among
the states based on the number of AIDS patients as of July 1987.
Money from some states that had overestimated their need was later
transferred to other states.
   New York, which has more AIDS cases than any other state, got
the most, about $8.5 million, and has helped about 900 patients so
far.
   According to Barbara McTague, director of New York's AIDS Drug
Assistance Program, the money is expected to last a year beyond the
grant expiration. As a result, there is as yet no legislative push
to come up with state money to continue to program, she said.
   Schulman said most states with surpluses will be allowed to keep
the money provided it is spent on AZT. Normally, unspent grant
money must be returned to the Treasury at the end of the fiscal
year, Sept. 30.
   California was next with $7.6 million for 1,500 patients. It was
followed by Texas, which got $2.1 million to treat 520 patients,
according to Donna Marler, the AZT coordinator for the Texas
Department of Health. She said the Texas Legislature, which
convenes in January, will be asked to provide state money for AIDS
treatment.
   Florida got the fourth largest grant of $1.7 million, and later
received an additional $329,000 from states where the money was not
needed. When the state still overspent the grants in treating about
630 patients over the year, the Legislature appropriated an extra
$278,000.
   Still, Schulman said, Florida was forced to discontinue the
grant program about five weeks ago. The deficit stemmed primarily
from the fact that until July 1, Medicaid in Florida did not pay
for AZT.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
