<2ND_LINE>AM-Rigged Contests,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Promotional Contests Rigged, Federal Indictment Alleges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two executives of a New Jersey marketing firm
and three other people have been indicted on charges of rigging
California promotional contests and awarding prizes to friends and
relatives.
   Prizes involved in the alleged scheme included a $14,000
Mustang, a $28,500 Corvette and $25,000 in cash, according to
Tuesday's 13-count indictment.
   The games were sold by C & K Marketing to the Alpha Beta
supermarket chain and the Taco Bell fast-food chain, but neither
Alpha Beta nor Taco Bell took part in the fraud, said Assistant
U.S. Attorney David Katz.
   Named in the indictment were C & K's president, John Edward
Curtin III, 37, of Sea Girt, N.J; vice president Kevin Joseph
Kissane, 35, of Brielle, N.J.; Curtin's brother, Kim John Curtin,
35, of South Laguna, Calif.; auto dealer Jerome S. Baratta, 56, of
Port Au Peck, N.J.; and James Frederick Lee, 50, of San Diego.
   The defendants were scheduled to be arraigned in federal court
here Sept. 6.
   The indictment alleges mail fraud, wire fraud, aiding and
abetting and use of misleading conduct.
   The Alpha Beta game was called ``California Dreamin''' and Taco
Bell's game was dubbed ``Wheels, Reels and Meals.''
   The indictment said Kim Curtin gave his friend James Lee the
winning ticket for the Mustang in the Alpha Beta contest in 1985
and John Curtin and Kissane rigged the Taco Bell game the following
year to make Lee the winner of the Corvette.
   In the Taco Bell game, Lee elected to take $28,500 in cash
instead of the car, but his victory was on paper only and the
marketing company kept the money, the indictment alleged.
   Lee acknowledged winning the Mustang and selling it for $12,000,
but he declined to say if Kim Curtin had given him the winning
ticket. He declined to comment further.
   Baratta, a relative of Kissane, was the arranged winner of a
$25,000 second prize in the Taco Bell game and the money actually
went back to the company, according to the indictment.
   Baratta said he was unaware the contest was a setup. The Curtins
and Kissane declined comment.
</TEXT>
