<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Reagan-Bush Bjt   08-24 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Bush, Bjt,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Blasts Dukakis at Reagan-Bush Pep Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush renewed his
criticism of rival Michael Dukakis' stand on the Pledge of
Allegiance on Wednesday, accusing the Democrat of ``looking for a
reason'' to avoid signing a bill requiring teachers and students to
say the pledge.
   ``What is it about the Pledge of Allegiance that upsets him so
much?'' Bush queried at a high-voltage pep rally, where he was
joined by President Reagan in their first post-GOP convention
campaign appearance.
   ``I would have signed that bill,'' Bush said. ``Let's face it _
my opponent was looking for a reason not to sign that bill _ I
would have looked for a reason to sign it.''
   Battered by questions over the military record of his running
mate Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., during their first week of
campaigning, Bush appeared intent on focusing the attention
elsewhere.
   Bush's renewed emphasis on the issue came one day after Dukakis
questioned Bush's ``dedication to the Constitution and the rule of
law'' on the matter. Dukakis said Bush had ``no business'' running
for the White House if he was willing to sign a bill that he knew
to be unconstitutional.
   The vice president used the pledge to wrap up his acceptance
speech to the Republican convention. And twice recently, Bush
faulted Dukakis at campaign appearances because the governor vetoed
a bill in 1977 that would have penalized any school teacher who
failed to lead students in the pledge every morning.
   Dukakis says he rejected the bill because the Massachusetts
Supreme Court declared the law unconstitutional.
   Bush used his appearance with Reagan to argue the matter should
be decided by the Supreme Court of the United States.
   ``I find it hard to believe that the Founding Fathers would have
objected to teachers leading students in the Pledge of
Allegiance,'' Bush said.
   The vice president also faulted his Democratic rival with being
weak on defense and crime as well as eager to raise taxes.
   ``We can't take another gamble'' by putting a Democratic
governor like Jimmy Carter in the White House, Bush contended.
   ``We must have tough, experienced leadership ... which someone
who's been there and someone you can trust _ I am that man,'' Bush
said.
   Reagan has appeared several times in his home state to press the
cause of his vice president. California, with its rich deployment
of 47 electoral votes, is seen by both campaigns as essential for
winning the White House.
   In his remarks to the crowd of several thousand at the Century
Plaza Hotel, Reagan contended Bush will shift gears smoothly from
being a loyal No. 2 to being a strong president because he is ``a
man of action _ a man accustomed to command.''
   The president argued that being a loyal No. 2 isn't always a
simple job.
   ``The vice presidency doesn't fit easily on such a man. But
George Bush is also a patriot. And so he made it fit and he served
with a distinction no one has ever matched,'' Reagan said.
   ``I once said that he is a great vice president, but I know and
I've seen that it didn't come easily. George Bush is a man of
action _ a man accustomed to command,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan said he was comfortable with the idea of passing on the
mantle of chief executive to Bush.
   ``I have seen him keep a cool head in hot crises. I have seen
his leadership and vision. I have given him some of the most
sensitive and difficult tasks we've had, and he has never let me or
the country down,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan lambasted the Democratic ticket as ``a three-headed
ticket that doesn't know left from center,'' an apparent reference
to Dukakis, his running mate Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, and Democratic
runner-up Jesse Jackson.
   Reagan also tried to offer a boost to Quayle's troubled
campaign, dogged by questions over his entry into the National
Guard and his relationship with a female lobbyist on a Florida
golfing trip.
   ``I'd say America has a great candidate ... and I must confess I
like his running mate, too,'' Reagan said in comments that were not
included in his prepared remarks.
   ``Dan Quayle stands for the same principles as George Bush and I
do,'' the president said.
   Reagan and Bush appeared together at the noisy pep rally after
conferring privately for about 15 minutes.
   Besides California Gov. George Deukmejian and Sen. Pete Wilson,
R-Calif., attending the rally were actor Charlton Heston, actress
Cheryl Ladd, singer Pat Boone and comedian Bob Hope, who quipped
that Quayle can ``not only be our vice president, he can be our
national bird.''
</TEXT>
