<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0645 08-24 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0645,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Wins AFL-CIO Backing; Promises `Era Of Economic
Patriotism'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with new material.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis tucked away the
endorsement of the AFL-CIO on Wednesday and promised strong
business-labor relations backed by a president who is ``an economic
leader, not a cheerleader.''
   Dukakis, in speeches to the labor group in Washington and a
college audience in Michigan, said that more Americans are working
now than ever before. But he said the new jobs created during the
Reagan administration have been low paying and average family
income stands where it was 20 years ago.
   ``That's the price our workers and their familes are paying for
voodoo economics,'' the Democratic presidential nominee said,
resurrecting a line George Bush used against Ronald Reagan in 1980.
   ``I have met too many young people who have accepted jobs over
the last eight years that pay less than their old jobs,'' Dukakis
said in a speech at Grand Valley State University. ``I have met too
many couples who are working harder at two jobs just to stay in
place.''
   The Democratic presidential nominee criticized Bush's promise to
create 30 million new jobs if elected to two terms as president, a
pledge senior Bush ecomonic advisers have conceded may be overly
optimistic.
   ``This election is not about whether Mr. Bush's own economists
believe his speeches,'' Dukakis said. ``It is about making every
American a full shareholder in the American dream. It's about
creating jobs with a future, jobs you can count on, jobs you can
raise a family on.''
   It was the second consecutive day Dukakis has directly
criticized Bush. On Tuesday, Dukakis noted that Bush has no
experience as a chief executive and also said the vice president
was unfit for the presidency if he would sign a law mandating
recitation of the Pledge of Allegiance in schools even if advised
that it was unconstitutional.
   In Washington, Dukakis chastised the vice president for not
mentioning the trade and budget deficits in his speech to the
Republican convention.
   ``And to add insult to injury, he wants to cut taxes for the
wealthy again,'' Dukakis said. ``My friends, if this were a movie,
we'd call it `son of voodoo.'''
   Dukakis also said Bush had failed when sent to Japan by Reagan
in 1983 to improve trade relations. He also criticized both Reagan
and Bush for suddenly supporting the trade bill signed by the
president Tuesday.
   ``Trade is an issue which requires presidential leadership each
day _ not just 77 days before a presidential election,'' Dukakis
said. ``In 1983, Mr. Bush was put in charge of managing our trade
problems with Japan, when the trade deficit with Japan was $22
billion. After visiting Japan and meeting with Japanese government
officials, he came home, declaring U.S.-Japanese trade relations
were `superb.' Since then, our trade deficit with Japan has
tripled.''
   He also touched on several fronts important to labor, promising
to help foster improved management-labor relations and to
strengthen the National Labor Relations Board, the Federal Trade
Commission and the Occupational Safety and Health Administration.
   ``We want to be able to say that there's a new spirit of
determination in America, a new economic patriotism that brings us
together as one people, one nation, helping us to compete _ and win
_ in the world market,'' Dukakis said.
   ``My friends, the next president of the Unites States must be an
economic leader, not a cheerleader,'' he said. ``He must do more
than talk about creating more jobs, he must be a president who
knows how to build a strong economy _ and has done it. A president
who knows how to create and save jobs _ and has done it. A
president who has the strength and the vision and the values to
build a strong economy and a vibrant future for America.''
</TEXT>
