<1ST_LINE>u p AM-BushBounce 1stLd-Writethru a0668 08-24 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush Bounce, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0668,780</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: to UPDATE with NBC-Journal and Harris polls, INSERT one graf
after 2nd pvs, Bush rebounded...it began; ADDS final graf to give
margin of error, other data.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pollsters: Quayle Controversy May Limit Bush's Bounce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's boost from the Republican National
Convention shows signs of decaying as quickly as it arose, a victim
of the controversy surrounding running mate Dan Quayle, pollsters
said Wednesday.
   Bush rebounded to at best a narrow lead in public opinion polls
this week after badly trailing the Democratic nominee, Michael
Dukakis, last month. But new polls indicate that Bush's bounce may
have peaked virtually as soon as it began.
   Two polls Wednesday put Bush ahead by leads so slim they were
within the margins of error _ 44-39 in an NBC News-Wall Street
Journal poll done Saturday through Monday and 49-47 in a Harris
poll done Friday to Monday.
   ``I think he's been hurt in the long run for the race,'' said
Michael Traugott, a Gallup Organization pollster. ``As this
reporting takes hold, there has to be some negative consequence for
the Bush-Quayle ticket.''
   News reports since the GOP convention last week have been
dominated by questions about Quayle's entry into the National Guard
during the Vietnam war and about a former female lobbyist's claim
he propositioned her in 1980.
   Those issues arose at a critical time in the campaign, when Bush
needed to capitalize on the positive response to his acceptance
speech by keeping attention focused on his themes, pollsters said.
   ``If you hit a high note you've got to keep hitting it, because
the public isn't paying attention and it needs to have that
constantly reinforced,'' said Keating Holland, a CBS News pollster.
``The good news that Bush is trying to continue to pump out is
getting lost in this Quayle thing.''
   The result: In a Gallup poll conducted Thursday and Friday, Bush
led Dukakis by nine percentage points. But in a Gallup poll done
Friday through Sunday, he led by just four points, a dead heat
because of the margin of error.
   Similarly, Bush led by six points, also within the error margin,
in a CBS News poll conducted Friday through Sunday. Holland noted
that Bush's support was strongest Friday and seemed to wane as the
weekend progressed.
   It was expected that Bush would receive a boost in popularity as
a result of television coverage of the Republican convention, just
as Dukakis won a bounce from the Democratic convention in mid-July.
The partisan speechmaking and careful choreography of modern
conventions reliably lift their nominees in the polls, albeit
temporarily.
   But Quayle questions arose even before the convention closed.
Traugott likened the effect to the 1976 debate in which President
Ford contended that Eastern Europe is not under Soviet domination;
initial polls found no effect, but Ford soon suffered as news
reports stressed the gaffe.
   ``This will turn out to be one of those events, like the 1976
debate, that will be cited as a major explanatory factor for either
a narrow (Bush) loss or a victory which could have been bigger,
given the boost that he should have received from the Reagan
performance of the past eight years,'' Traugott said. ``It will
become part of the folklore of the 1988 election.''
   While Ford's misstatement reflected on himself, pollsters
doubted that concerns about Quayle personally were harming the GOP
ticket, because voters tend to decide exclusively on the
presidential nominees.
   ``People repeatedly say the vice presidential choice doesn't
matter,'' said Jeff Alderman, pollster for ABC News. ``If the vice
presidential candidate can't help very much, then it's equally
difficult for him to hurt very much.''
   Instead, others said, the apparent damage stems from a lack of
positive publicity for the Bush campaign coming out of the
convention. With voters somewhat unfamiliar with the nominees and
not strongly committed to either one, negative developments _ such
as the Quayle questions _ can strongly influence the electorate, at
least briefly, they said.
   That is not to say polls now can predict the election's outcome.
Measures of underlying public attitudes for months have indicated a
close contest, even as Dukakis rose to an 18-point lead on the tide
of publicity from his convention. Dukakis' bounce was greater and
lasted longer than Bush's, but some polls put the race back at a
tie even before the Republicans met.
   ``Bounce is not momentum. Momentum implies you're going to
continue on indefinitely,'' Holland said. ``Bounce means you're
going to rise, you're going to fall. And the fall can be as quick
as the rise is.''
   The NBC-Journal poll was conducted Saturday through Monday among
1,762 registered voters, the Harris poll Friday through Monday
among 1,310 likely voters. Both had error margins of plus or minus
three points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
