<1ST_LINE>r i AM-American-Terrorism     08-24 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American-Terrorism,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Woman Cleared of Terrorism Lands in Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American woman cleared of terrorism
charges after being imprisoned in Peru dodged reporters upon her
arrival in Ireland Wednesday after saying she wanted to go
sightseeing and visit family here.
   Cynthia McNamara, 40, a native of Philadelphia, was the only
passenger to leave a Soviet Aeroflot flight from Lima, Peru, at
Shannon airport 128 miles west of Dublin, airline officials said.
Immigration officials said she was allowed to enter the Irish
Republic on her American passport.
   She eluded waiting reporters at Shannon by mingling with about
200 passengers from another flight and slipping out a side door.
   Ms. McNamara earlier said she would move on from Ireland to
London to meet friends and eventually hoped to find a job teaching
English somewhere in Europe.
   She was imprisoned for nearly five months in Peru on charges of
taking part in an August 1987 rebel attack in Vilcashuaman,
Ayacucho state, by the Maoist Shining Path movement. Two government
workers were killed.
   She said she was a tourist, had no ties with the rebels and had
nothing to do with the attack. Her lawyers, the U.S. Embassy in
Lima and survivors of the attack and other witnesses backed her up.
   A Lima court cleared her April 26, but she was rearrested on the
same charges Aug. 2 when she went to a police station for
permission to leave the country. She was held in jail until Monday
night, but was finally freed after an Ayacucho court ruled she
could not be tried twice for the same crime, her lawyer said.
   ``My name is cleared. I feel relieved,'' Ms. McNamara told
reporters before leaving Lima Tuesday.
   Peruvian police first arrested her on Dec. 5.
</TEXT>
