<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Parkinson-Press     08-24 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Parkinson-Press,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0716 to correct category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Eyes of Texas Media Are Upon Paula</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MESQUITE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The press has taken a nearby hill,
christened it ``Fort Mesquite'' and settled in for a long wait _
but a friend staying with Paula Parkinson at an apartment here says
the media siege won't work.
   ``She is still here, but she doesn't want to talk to anybody,''
said a woman who identified herself only as Cori and as a niece of
Ms. Parkinson's roommate, John Gideon, who was arrested Friday
after a domestic disturbance.
   ``She's not going to say anything for a long time.''
   But Dallas area reporters and photographers and network TV crews
are keeping an unblinking eye on the second-story apartment of the
ex-lobbyist, who has become a thorn in the side of the vice
presidential nominee, Dan Quayle.
   Neighbors say the press began circling, cameras in hand, outside
Ms. Parkinson's apartment late last week, even before the Daily
News of Los Angeles reported that two former attorneys for Ms.
Parkinson quoted her as telling the FBI in 1981 that Quayle had
propositioned her on a Florida golfing holiday.
   Then Playboy magazine announced Tuesday that an article in its
November edition will include a statement about the incident from
Ms. Parkinson, who says she rebuffed Quayle's advance because she
was with another congressman, then-Rep. Tom Evans, R-Del.
   ``We flirted a lot and danced extremely close and
suggestively,'' Ms. Parkinson was quoted by Playboy. ``He said he
wanted to make love.''
   Quayle, who has denied any relationship with Mrs. Parkinson,
said Tuesday he is tiring of questions about her and his National
Guard service. ``This is getting a little bit outrageous and I'm
getting a little bit indignant about just one bum rap after
another,'' he said.
   Ms. Parkinson, who was interviewed by the FBI as part of an
investigation into whether sexual favors were being traded for
votes against legislation opposed by her employer, has refused to
come to her apartment door. She did accept a list of prepared
questions from one reporter only to send them back outside without
answering them.
   ``The residents here feel like it's an invasion of their
privacy, too,'' said an apartment manager, who refused to be
identified. ``They aren't real thrilled about having all these
cameras around.''
   Mesquite police said Gideon was arrested after a disturbance at
the apartment complex. He was being held Wednesday at the Lew
Sterrett Justice Center in Dallas in lieu of $2,000 bail on charges
of driving without a license, possession of marijuana and driving
while intoxicated. He also was being held for state prison
authorities for investigation of a possible parole violation.
   Ms. Parkinson, who changed her name back to her maiden name
Paula Laham following a 1984 divorce from Hank Parkinson, has held
a number of short-term jobs since the original Washington sex
scandal and an ensuing appearance in Playboy.
   She also has had legal problems, The Dallas Morning News
reported in its Tuesday editions. She was arrested for public
intoxication twice in 1985, with one case being dismissed and the
other probated for 90 days. Then last December, she pleaded guilty
to a charge of driving under the influence and was placed on
probation for two years, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
