<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Bolivia-Rescue     08-24 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia-Rescue,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mountain Climbers Rescued After Reports of Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers found a mountain-climbing party
of five Frenchmen, one Canadian and two Bolivians on Wednesday, the
day after their guide reported what he described as a guerrilla
attack.
   Eduardo Perez Beltran, acting interior minister, told The
Associated Press the climbers were expected in La Paz on Thursday
and police were continuing to investigate.
   Jorge Alderete, interior undersecretary, said earlier: ``We do
not yet have a clear picture of the situation but the first
information indicates it is a group linked to the Peruvian Shining
Path guerillas.''
   Berfardo Guarachi, the Bolivian guide, said 16 heavily armed men
surrounded the climbing party's base camp Monday at about 15,000
feet in the Andes, 50 miles north of La Paz. Guarachi said he heard
shots before escaping down a glacier.
   Guarachi said Tuesday that the men communicated with
walkie-talkies and five wore khaki uniforms.
   After the climbers were found, Perez Beltran said a preliminary
investigation indicated they were surrounded by armed Indians who
may have been hunting and there was no evidence of guerrilla
involvement.
   He said military aircraft flew over the site and helicopter
pilots found the camp abandoned Tuesday, raising concern among
officials.
   Paititi, the travel agency that handled the expedition, said the
foreign climbers were experienced and the two Bolivians worked for
the agency. Guarachi is a veteran mountaineer who was the first to
reach an airliner that crashed on Illimani mountain in 1984.
   The Shining Path, a Maoist group, began fighting in the Peruvian
Andes eight years ago and the guerrilla war has cost more than
15,000 lives. No guerrilla operations have been reported in the
Bolivian Andes and no people live near the base camp.
</TEXT>
