<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Rebels     08-24 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Rebels,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Two Newspaper Officials Linked to Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested two officials of a leftist
newspaper the government has linked to Shining Path, the 8-year-old
Maoist guerrilla group, a lawyer and several Lima dailies said
Wednesday.
   Lawyer Alfredo Crespo said Luis Arce and Danilo Blanco, editor
and administrator respectively of El Diario, were arrested Tuesday
while seeking the release of five people detained during a raid on
a printing plant the newspaper uses. Government and police
officials refused comment.
   Arce accused police of ransacking the Imprenta Pedro Leon
printing company Friday, arresting five workers and confiscating
100,000 copies of a special El Diario edition carrying what was
presented as an interview with Shining Path leader Abimael Guzman.
   Police confirmed a raid at the time but have refused comment
since.
   Crespo, president of the Association of Democratic Lawyers, said
anti-insurgency police were holding Arce and Blanco. The government
considers Crespo's group a Shining Path front.
   Officials say El Diario is the voice of Shining Path, whose
guerrilla war has taken more than 15,000 lives and caused damage
estimated at $10 billion. Arce denies links to the guerrillas.
   His newspaper, which prints about 5,000 copies, is among the
targets of a law proposed by President Alan Garcia that would make
it illegal for organizations or media to apologize for terrorism.
</TEXT>
