<DOCNO> AP880824-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1935EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PrimariesRdp     08-24 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primaries Rdp,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anchorage Voters OK Financial Backing for Olympics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of bringing the 1994 Winter Olympics to Alaska's largest
city said Wednesday that voters boosted their effort, while
Oklahoma Democrats rallied behind a first-time candidate who won a
crowded race to oppose a first-term Republican congressman.
   In Anchorage, Alaska, voters agreed by a 2-to-1 margin Tuesday
to assume financial responsibility for the Games. Alaska voters
also narrowed the field for Alaska's sole seat in the U.S. House,
and all five Oklahoma congressmen who faced challengers in
Tuesday's primary won renomination.
   The Anchorage vote gives the city a good lobbying position when
it goes before the International Olympic Committee next month in
Seoul, said Rick Nerland, executive vice president of the Anchorage
Organizing Committee.
   ``I think the numbers that we're seeing now are impressive
numbers to the IOC,'' Nerland said.
   The ballot question asked whether the municipality should cover
any unanticipated debts incurred by staging the Games.
   With 79 of 91 precincts reported Wednesday, the vote was 26,365
in favor and 13,878 against, or 66 percent to 34 percent.
   The Anchorage organizers had said they needed a clear majority
to impress the IOC, though they are not sure how much weight the
vote will carry in the international competition.
   The nine-member IOC is to choose in September between Anchorage;
Lillehammer, Norway; Ostersund-Are, Sweden; and Sofia, Bulgaria.
   In Alaska's House primary, eight-term Republican Don Young and
Democrat Peter Gruenstein, making his first try for a statewide
office, advance to the general election.
   Young handily defeated Republican challenger George Johnston, an
Arco Alaska employee from Anchorage. With 94 percent of the votes
counted Wednesday, Young had 50,958 votes, or 55.2 percent, to
Johnston's 4,977 votes, 5.3 percent.
   Gruenstein drew 32,375 votes, or 35 percent, to pull ahead of
two Democratic contenders. Eugene Vick of Juneau got 2,474 votes,
2.6 percent. Ryal White of Anchorage had 1,503 votes, 1.6 percent
of the total.
   In Oklahoma, freshman Rep. Jim Inhofe faced no Republican
challengers Tuesday, but this fall faces Kurt Glassco, a Tulsa
lawyer making his first run for political office. Glassco, a
one-time aide to former Gov. George Nigh, won the Democratic
nomination Tuesday with 60 percent of the vote despite a crowded
field that included four other candidates.
   ``Jim Inhofe is going to have his hands full'' with Glassco,
predicted Barry Moore, an aide at the Democrat's state headquarters
in Oklahoma City.
   Democrats say Inhofe, a first-term congressman, has been
ineffective in representing his district, but Republicans expressed
confidence Inhofe would prevail.
   ``It may be close, it may be a blowout,'' said Larry Stein, a
spokesman for the Republican Party in Oklahoma City, adding that
``Jim Inhofe has built a very conservative record up there.''
   Republicans also are touting Mike Brown, a lawyer making his
first run for political office, in the fall race against Democratic
Rep. Glenn English, who got 84 percent of the vote Tuesday over one
rival. Stein said Brown would campaign on economic issues such as
jobs.
   Rep. Mike Synar surprised some observers by winning 69 percent
of the vote in the Democratic primary against state Sen. Frank
Shurden, who had labeled him too liberal. Synar will face political
newcomer Ira Phillips, a former economic development specialist for
the Cherokee Nation who garnered 55 percent of the vote in the GOP
primary.
   Republican Rep. Mickey Edwards easily won renomination, and
faces Democratic political newcomer Terry Montgomery. Rep. David
McCurdy has no Republican opposition in November and Rep. Wes
Watkins faced no opposition in either the Democratic primary or the
general election.
</TEXT>
