<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Mayor 1stLd-Writethru a0679 08-24 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Mayor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0679,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Visits Relatives Of Arson Attack Victim</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 3 grafs SUB for 7th graf pvs, The attack ... UPDATING with
report of Israelis arrested in second attack. Picks up 8th graf
pvs, Several Or ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QARARA, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of an Israeli town
where arsonists killed three Palestinians apologized to a victim's
family Wednesday in an attempt to patch up strained Arab-Jewish
relations.
   ``What happened really shocked me,'' Yitzhak Bukovza, mayor of
Or Yehuda near Tel Aviv, told relatives of Mustafa Khalil Abadlah
during a visit to their home in this central Gaza Strip town.
   ``It's a (religious) commandment to bring the spirit of peace
and express our will to live together,'' Bukovza said.
   Abadlah's three brothers listened with tears in their eyes and
accepted the mayor's apology. But they also demanded harsh
punishment for the arsonists and better protection for Arab workers
in Israel.
   Three Palestinians laborers sleeping in a construction site
shack in Or Yehuda were killed when assailants set the hut on fire
Aug. 8. Three Or Yehuda residents are being held in the attack.
   Police said the assailants were not out to attack Arabs, but to
take revenge on a Jewish contractor who refused to give them work.
   Earlier this week, police detained four Arabs suspected of
hurling smoke bombs and firebombs at an Or Yehuda home to avenge
the arson.
   However, Israel television reported Wednesday that police
detained two Or Yehuda residents, ages 20 and 30, on suspicion of
carrying out the attack for which the four Arabs were held. The
report said one of the suspects lives in the apartment building
where the bombs were thrown.
   Their aim was to provoke neighbors to expel Palestinians from
the town, the television said.
   Several Or Yehuda residents welcomed the arson attack. ``So what
if an Arab burned to death?'' Shuki Calif, 16, told the Hadashot
newspaper. ``What's an Arab anyway. He isn't human.''
   In his visit to Qarara, Bukovza defended city residents, saying:
``Those who are under suspicion are Or Yehuda residents, but we can
say with a clear conscience that our boys were not involved in
this.'' He did not elaborate.
   Bukovza was accompanied by a dozen city residents during the
trip. The delegation's bus was guarded by two army jeeps and
followed by about two dozen journalists.
   When the group arrived at the four-story home of the Abadlah
family, mayhem broke loose as camera crews and photographers pushed
for positions, leaving the relatives bewildered and intimidated.
   The meeting was awkward at first. The victim's three brothers
were seated in chairs, and Bukovza delivered his statement standing
in front of them, until a village leader pointed out that it would
be more appropriate for him to be seated as well.
   One of the brothers, Abdel Razik Abadlah, said after the
meeting: ``I'm very thankful that this important man came to see
us. I'm very happy that he apologized to us.''
   However, Abadlah said he would no longer work in Israel because
``if I go, I will get killed.'' He said he has worked as a
construction worker in the Tel Aviv area for 10 years.
   The family demanded a thorough investigation, better protection
for Arab workers and compensation from Or Yehuda.
   Bukovza, speaking in Hebrew and halting Arabic, invited the
family to Or Yehuda at the end of the 40-day period of mourning and
promised compensation.
   When asked for immediate assistance, Bukovza said he and others
would pay ``a symbolic sum'' until a deal was worked out.
   Initially the mayor, whose parents were born in Libya, also
planned to pay condolences to the families of the other two
victims. It was not clear why they did not attend the meeting.
   The Or Yehuda arson was one in a recent series of violent
confrontations between Arabs and Jews inside Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
