<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-24 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Front Triggers Thunderstorms Across South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A wide band of showers and strong thunderstorms with locally
heavy rain stretched from central Texas to southwest South Carolina
Wednesday, and cool showers also doused much of the Northeast.
   A cold front curving south from the Great Lakes through
southwest Virginia, northern Louisiana and central Texas mixed with
warm, moist air and generated storms through much of the South.
   Some of the heaviest rain hit Louisiana, with Alexandria getting
over 1} inches and Shreveport up to 1{ inches.
   In the six hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT, New Bern, N.C., received
1.90 inches of rain.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered across New England
and western sections of New York State and Pennsylvania, and
thunderstorms were moving off the North Carolina coast.
   A few showers and thunderstorms formed over the Mojave Desert of
California and the southern Sierra Nevada Mountains. Heavier rain
was predicted for the afternoon and evening and a flash flood watch
was posted for the mountains and deserts of southern California.
   Widely scattered showers also developed over the mountains of
New Mexico and Colorado, and over southwest Washington.
   Hot, humid air continued its grip on much of Texas. Galveston
set a record high for the date of 95 degrees, surpassing a
94-degree mark set in 1935. Austin and Corpus Christi tied records
with readings of 102 and 98, respectively.
   Smoke from several forest fires in northwest Wyoming was
spreading southeastward across that state and into western Nebraska
and was expected to cause very red sunsets and sunrises over parts
of Wyoming and the central Plains for the next day or two.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 55 degrees at Concord,
Keene Laconia and Lebanon, N.H., to 104 degrees at Beeville, Tex.
The overnight low was 31 degrees at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   Thursday's forecast called for scattered showers from Michigan
to New York and New England, with the heaviest rain in northern
Michigan and northern New England. Showers and thunderstorms also
were expected along the Gulf Coast and Florida and much of the
southern Plateau.
   Highs were expected to remain cool in the 60s in northern
Michigan and northern New England; in the 70s from North Dakota
through the Great Lakes to southern New England; and between 100
and 105 degrees over the desert Southwest and the central valleys
of California. Highs elsewhere were forecast to be in the 80s and
90s.
</TEXT>
