<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-PCBFire     08-24 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-PCB Fire,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3,000 Residents Evacuated After Fire In PCB Depot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three thousand people driven from their homes by
a fire at a PCB depot in suburban Montreal waited with friends and
relatives late Wednesday while scientists conducted water and soil
tests for contamination.
   Many evacuated residents complained they were being kept in the
dark about the possible dangers of inhaling PCBs, a liquid chemical
suspected of causing cancer.
   ``I'm not afraid for me but for my baby,'' said Chantal Labarre,
24, eight months pregnant. ``We all have questions and wonder what
the danger is.''
   Another resident, Jean-Pierre Reinesch, said: ``The firemen were
told to burn their clothes. What about us?''
   Environment Minister Tom MacMillan promised a thorough
investigation into the cause of the six-hour inferno in St.
Basile-le-Grand, 15 miles east of Montreal. The blaze sent flames
more than 150 feet into the night sky on Tuesday and covered the
area with a thick black cloud.
   More than 50 residents were treated for skin and lung irritation
at local hospitals, Alain Lavoie, an official of the Quebec
Environment Ministry, told The Associated Press.
   Police sealed off the area as federal and provincial scientists
conducted soil and water tests. Doctors checked residents of a
5{-square-mile area.
   Production of PCBs (polychlorinated biphenyls) now is banned,
but it was formerly used as a coolant in hydroelectric
transformers. PCBs inhibit electrical flow and won't burn at
temperatures under 1,832 degrees.
   The depot stored drums containing thousands of gallons of
discarded oil with PCBs.
   Environment official Antonio Flammand said some test results may
not be available for weeks. Until then, it is impossible to predict
the long-term effects of inhaling the fumes.
   ``There's a possibility that animals (near the scene) and
firemen who were exposed may suffer long-term effects,'' said
Flammand.
   Residents in St. Basile and neighboring sections of East
Montreal were advised not to eat fruit or vegetables from their
gardens, or drink tap water. In nearby Ste-Julie, people were
warned to keep windows closed, and keep children and pets inside.
   The privately owned warehouse, roughly the size of a hockey rink
with steel outer walls and a cement floor, has been a topic of
controversy, with residents pressing for better safety. The Quebec
government found seven safety violations two years ago but
improvements reportedly remained to be carried out.
   ``It's a scandal that it's still there,'' said resident Renee
Archambault. ``It takes a disaster like this before people wake
up.''
   The only plant in Canada capable of destroying PCBs is in Swan
Hills, Alberta, but does not accept PCB waste from other provinces.
St. Basile is one of 50 storage sites in Quebec alone.
   ``It was a bomb waiting to go off,'' said resident Kane Fleming.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
