<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DeadSeals     08-24 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dead Seals,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seal Deaths An Early Warning For Humans, Scientists Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of more than 7,000 seals in the heavily
polluted North Sea indicates major problems in all the world's
oceans and is a warning to humans living around them, British
scientists said Wednesday.
   No link has been established between pollution and the virus
leading to the severe pneumonia that is killing the seals, but
dumped chemicals may be destroying their immune system so they
cannot fight disease, said scientists of the British government's
Natural Environment Research Council.
   ``Whatever is causing the problem in the North Sea could spread
to affect all the world's oceans,'' said Dr. Brian McCartney,
director of the Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory monitoring the
North Sea.
   ``Pollution is higher in the North Sea than in the Atlantic
Ocean, but the two seas are connected and the state of the North
Sea is an early indicator of the state of all the oceans,'' he told
a news conference.
   ``Seals are prone to infection, but we have seen nothing like
this before,'' said Dr. John Harwood, head of the government-funded
Sea Mammal Research Unit at Cambridge.
   ``We feel powerless as there is almost nothing we can do to stop
the seals dying,'' he said.
   The British government announced it would fund new research to
discover how and where seals pick up harmful pollutants in the sea.
   Junior Environment Minister Virginia Bottomley said the
government was concerned about the death of seals because disease
could reach Britain from the eastern North Sea and the Baltic Sea.
   The research involves taking samples of blood and tissue from
seals and fitting some of the animals with radio transmitters so
ships can track their feeding movements. A report should be ready
within six months, Mrs. Bottomley said.
   The scientists said a group of highly toxic compounds called
PCBs _ polychlorinated biphenols _ used in electrical equipment
like transformers are among the prime suspect chemicals.
   ``Seals represent the highest mammals in the North Sea and are
the closest to man physiologically, so when they die in thousands
it is a warning to man,'' McCartney said in an interview.
   Harwood said half the population of common seals in northwest
Europe has died from the virus on the coasts of Denmark, West
Germany, the Netherlands, Norway, Sweden and Britain.
   He said Britain's 200,000 gray seals might be threatened. These
seals account for half the world population of gray seals and still
are not known to be affected by the virus.
   Only 500 to 1,000 monk seals survive in the eastern Aegean Sea
of the Mediterranean and the west African coast of Mauritania.
These seals ``could be in terrible danger if the disease spreads,''
and the disease could also spread to dolphins and porpoises, he
said.
   Harwood said Dutch scientists isolated two viruses in dead
seals, one a type of herpes and the other a type of picorna, which
causes polio and hoof and mouth disease in livestock.
   Dr. Minnie Courtney, an independent marine biologist of London
University, said: ``We know nothing of immunity in seals or fish,
only in man. We are in a very weak position when something like
this happens. It's as if you had to start studying medicine for
human beings all over again.''
   Sir Richard Body, a Conservative lawmaker, called for urgent
government action to stop North Sea pollution because Britain was
``pouring more filth'' into it than any other nation.
   Opposition Labor Party lawmaker David Blunkett said, ``It is
time for Britain to act, to prevent the North Sea becoming the Dead
Sea and to work with the Dutch and the Scandinavians in saving what
seals we can.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880824-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Norway-Refugees     08-24 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Norway-Refugees,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conference Adopts Plan of Action For African Refugee Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conference sponsored by the United Nations
and the Organization of African Unity adopted a plan Wednesday to
help ease the plight of 5.4 million refugees in southern Africa. It
asked for intensified world aid.
   The Oslo Declaration and Plan of Action said relief efforts
should concentrate on rebuilding agriculture, finding jobs for
displaced people and providing them access to credit and marketing
structures.
   The three-day conference attracted more than 400 delegates from
80 countries, specialized U.N. agencies and African ``liberation
movements.''
   The plan suggested a general outline for helping refugees in
nine states bordering or near South Africa: Angola, Botswana,
Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and
Zimbabwe.
   It said greater efforts should be made to forecast and prepare
for emergencies; to assess relief needs and plan deliveries; to
help affected areas recover and develop, and to step up the
mobilization of resources.
   ``The conference recognizes that the conditions of refugees,
returnees and displaced persons is a global responsibility,'' the
declaration said, stressing the need for international
burden-sharing.
   Documents distributed at the conference estimated some of the
annual recovery costs for southern Africa as: $150 million for
agriculture, $100 million for health and education, $50 million for
housing, $50 million for roads, $40 million for emergency food
stocks, $25 million for water supplies, $20 million to deal with
soil erosion and $15 million for sanitation.
   The conference recommended more coordination among existing
organizations, particularly the High Commissioner for Refugees, the
World Food Program, the U.N. Children's Fund, the U.N. Development
Program and the World Health Organization.
   The document blamed South Africa's racial policy for many of the
problems in the area, although millions of the refugees also were
displaced inside their own countries by domestic conflicts.
   ``The root causes of the tragic humanitarian crisis unfolding in
the region is South Africa's apartheid policy, its illegal
occupation of Namibia, the policies it pursues in the region of
direct and indirect acts of aggression, intimidation and
destabilization,'' the declaration said.
   ``The fundamental and lasting solutions to the region's refugee
problem lie in the adoption of political and other actions aimed at
bringing about total abolition of apartheid, racial equality,
national independence and improved economic and social conditions.''
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar attended the
conference opening on Monday before leaving for Iran-Iraq peace
talks in Geneva.
   Also attending were OAU chairman and Mali President Moussa
Traore; President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe; Prime Minister Gro
Harlem Brundtland of Norway and Jean-Pierre Hocke, the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees.
   The conference asked that its declaration be submitted to the
next OAU and U.N. sessions for appraisal and follow-up.
   By law and custom, apartheid in South Africa establishes a
racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no
vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy
and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880824-0212 </DOCNO>
