<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Robertson-Jews     08-24 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson-Jews,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Leader `Disappointed' On Robertson Response To `Temptation'
Letter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent Jewish leader said
Wednesday he's ``disappointed and saddened'' at the response of Pat
Robertson to his request for a statement condemning anti-Semitic
remarks made about the film ``The Last Temptation of Christ.''
   Abraham H. Foxman, national director of the New York-based
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, chastised the former
Republican presidential hopeful for failing to quickly condemn
statements made by some critics of the Martin Scorsese film, The
New York Times reported Wednesday.
   Foxman, in a telephone interview with The Associated Press, said
he was sad the personal correspondence between him and Robertson
had become public in the newspaper and that he considered Robertson
to be a friend.
   But he repeated his contention that Robertson's initial response
to his letter asking the television evangelist for a condemnation
of anti-Semitism had been inadequate.
   ``I appreciated his advice,'' Foxman told the AP. ``And I
respect his judgment.
   ``But I am still disappointed and saddened. This is something
that needs no great strategy or counsel. We should be able to stand
up and say, `Anti-Semitism is wrong.'''
   Some conservative Christians, unhappy with the Universal
Pictures film, claimed it is a Jewish attack on Christianity. Lew
Wasserman, the head of MCA, Universal's parent company, is Jewish.
   Robertson criticized the film but did not join in the attacks on
Wasserman.In a statement Wednesday, he said he did eventually
condemn the anti-Jewish comments about the film on his television
show, ``The 700 Club.''
   In his first letter to Robertson, Foxman asked the evangelist to
condemn anti-Semitic rhetoric.
   In his response, Robertson said he would condemn any
anti-Semitism ``that might occur,'' and suggested the ADL join him
in criticizing the picture.
   Robertson, founder and chief executive officer of the Christian
Broadcasting Network, issued a statement Wednesday saying he too
was upset that private correspondence had been made public, and
expressed disappointment that the ADL leader had not taken his
advice to condemn the film.
   ``I was advising a dear, personal friend of what I felt was the
most effective strategy in this particular situation _ to stop
anti-Semitic rhetoric and sentiment about this film before it ever
began,'' Robertson said.
   ``Had they done what I suggested, it would have been a great
move to solidify the rapport between Christians and Jews in America
and further prompt unity between us.''
   Foxman said he believed that whether the ADL took a stand on the
film or not, Robertson should speak out on the anti-Semitism.
   ``I have seen the film, and I can understand why Christians are
upset. I think that the discussion of the portrayal of Jesus in the
film is certainly proper within the Christian community.
   ``But at the same time, the anti-Semitism is something we have
been fighting for 2,000 years. If we let these things stand
unchallenged, they become the accepted truth. It is time that those
in the middle stand up and be heard, rather than only those on both
extremes,'' Foxman said.
   In his statement, Robertson said: ``I will always stand against
anti-Semitism. I have already spoken out on `The 700 Club' on this
matter as I promised.''
   CBN spokeswoman Frankie Abourjilie said she had no details on
what Robertson had said or when he said it.
</TEXT>
