<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EmmyAwards     08-24 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Emmy Awards,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>HBO Wins First Ever Emmy for Cable Television in Early Awards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In its first year of eligibility, cable
television's Home Box Office has become an Emmy award winner, it
was announced Wednesday.
   HBO collected two Emmy trophies _ both for ``Dear America:
Letters Home From Vietnam'' _ in the early ``area'' Emmy awards
announced by Doug Duitsman, president of the Academy of Television
Arts and Sciences.
   Area awards are presented in categories where they may be one
winner, more than one winner or no winner. To avoid the opening of
an empty envelope during the Emmy telecast Sunday night, the area
awards were handed out ahead of time. It marked the first time the
awards have been handed out early.
   Cable programs have never before been eligible for Emmy Awards.
   HBO's ``Dear America'' was given an Emmy for best informational
special, and shared a trophy for best individual achievement in an
informational special with PBS' ``Buster Keaton: A Hard Act to
Follow.''
   Other winners were PBS' ``Nature'' and ``Buster Keaton'' for
best informational series; PBS' ``The Metropolitan Opera Presents:
Turandot'' for best individual achievement in classical music-dance
programming; ABC's ``The 15th Annual American Music Awards'' for
best indivdual achievement in special events programming; ABC's
``The 60th Annual Academy Awards'' for best variety-music events
programming; PBS' ``Strong Poison'' for best achievement in graphic
design and title sequences; and ABC's ``Moonlighting'' for best
achievement in special visual effects.
   Additional Emmys will be presented Saturday afternoon during a
non-televised ceremony. The major Emmys will be handed out Sunday
night during the 40th annual awards show, to be broadcast live on
the East Coast at 8 p.m. EDT by the Fox Broadcasting Co.
</TEXT>
