<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0760 08-24 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0760,0842</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Spurns U.S. on Deportation Issue; Troops Wound 15</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 19th pvs `U.S. Ambassador ...' to UPDATE
with report that Shamir and Rabin told Pickering deportain policy
would continue; Cabinet endorses policy. PICKS up 20th bgng,
`Washington's criticism... DELETES two bottom grafs pvs to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and
wounded up to 15 Palestinians on Wednesday and their government
rejected U.S. criticism of its policy of deporting activists from
the occupied territories.
   The United States told Israel, in the first such warning, that
relations would be damaged if the Israelis continued deporting
Palestinians from the occupied lands. Deputy Secretary of State
John Whitehead delivered the warning Monday at a meeting in
Washington with an Israeli diplomat.
   In Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, troops fired on
Palestinians who hurled stones and burned tires in the alleys of
the central market, the army said.
   As soldiers and Palestinians skirmished, scores of kites flown
by children on rooftops darted in the sky. One box kite sailing
near the casbah, or old city, wore the red, white, black and green
colors of the outlawed Palestinian flag.
   A spokesman said two Palestinians were wounded by gunfire, two
by rubber bullets and two by plastic bullets. Arab hospital
officials put the number hit by gunfire at 11, including a
17-year-old girl seriously wounded in the chest.
   Four Palestinians were wounded at the Shati refugee camp in Gaza
City, the army spokesman said. Arab hospital officials said an
8-year-old boy was shot in the back.
   Israel radio said a 10-year-old Israeli boy on his way to the
Jewish settlement of Kiryat Arba was struck in the head by a rock
as his bus passed the El Arrub refugee camp near Bethlehem.
   Palestinians began a two-day general strike Wednesday in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip to protest the deaths of four
Arabs held in Israeli prisons.
   The mayor of an Israeli town where arsonists killed three
Palestinians drove to the Gaza Strip to apologize to the family of
one victim.
   At least 252 Arabs have been killed in the uprising that began
Dec. 8 among the 1.5 million Palestinians who live in the occupied
lands, most of them shot by Israeli soldiers. Four Israelis also
have been slain.
   Soldiers with bulldozers demolished three homes before dawn
Wednesday in Jelazoun refugee camp. The houses belonged to members
of outlawed local committees who were suspected in the beating
death of a Palestinian youth who allegedly collaborated with
Israel, the army said.
   An Associated Press reporter in Nablus counted more than 20
instances of soldiers opening fire _ most often into the air as
warnings or with rubber or plastic bullets, which are lethal only
at close range.
   At least twice while the reporter was present, soldiers radioed
commanding officers for permission to fire live ammunition.
   Maj. Elkana, whose full name cannot be disclosed because of army
regulations, turned down a soldier who asked permission to fire a
.22 caliber rifle at the legs of protesters blocking a main road.
   Mayor Yitzhak Bukovza of Or Yehuda, near Tel Aviv, told
relatives of arson victim Mustafa Khalil Abadlah: ``What happened
really shocked me. It's a commandment to bring the spirit of peace,
and express our will to live together.''
   Abadlah was sleeping a construction site shack in Or Yehuda when
he was burned to death.
   His three brothers listened with tears in their eyes and
accepted Bukovza's apology, but demanded harsh punishment for the
arsonists and better protection for Palestinian workers in Israel.
   The Foreign Ministry, in a reply to the U.S. criticism, said
Wednesday: ``Israel does not accept the American interpretation of
international law regarding deportations. The legality ... was
checked recently by Israel's Supreme Court, which ruled that
deportations are legal, according to both Israeli and international
law.''
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering spent 90 minutes with Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir discussing the issue.
   Israel television later reported that both Shamir and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin told Pickering the deportation policy would
continue. Israel's inner Cabinet of 10 senior ministers met
Wednesday and endorsed the policy, the television said.
   Washington's criticism ``has created a small crisis, certainly
tension in the relationship,'' said Eytan Gilboa, a specialist on
the United States at Jerusalem's Hebrew University. ``The language
was exceptionally strong.''
   Israel has deported 33 Palestinians since the rebellion began,
contending they are leaders of resistance to Israeli rule, and has
ordered the expulsions of 25 more.
   The United States considers expulsions a violation of human
rights and an obstacle to peace in the Middle East. State
Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Wednesday the United
States was ``shocked'' by the decision to deport another 25
Palestinians.
   Washington has long-standing differences with Israel on
deportation, detention without trial and other punitive measures
against Palestinians, but never had indicated they threatened
relations.
</TEXT>
