<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile 1stLd-Writethru a0753 08-24 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0753,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All States of Emergency Ordered Lifted For First Time Since 1973
Coup</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with more details of emergency
powers, reax from opposition and church figures. PICKUP 6th graf
pvs `Since Sept. ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The right-wing government on Wednesday
decreed an end to all state of emergency measures for the first
time since President Augusto Pinochet took power in a 1973 coup,
the interior minister announced.
   The action was taken less than a week before Chile's military
commanders meet to nominate a candidate, expected to be Pinochet
himself, for a presidential referendum planned for October.
   Interior Minister Sergio Fernandez, in a news conference at the
government palace, told reporters that presidential decrees
removing the emergency measures ``have been issued today and will
take effect upon publication in the official bulletin,'' within the
next few days.
   The two measures now in effect are a state of emergency and a
state of disturbance to internal peace.
   Under the state of emergency, the government is authorized to
suspend publication and broadcasts by news media and restrict
public gatherings.
   The state of disturbance measure permits Pinochet to order the
arrest and detention of opponents for up to 20 days; send into
exile citizens deemed dangerous to internal security; order
internal exile for up to three months, and restrict freedom of
information and public gatherings.
   Opposition figures reacted with cautious approval.
   ``Better late than never,'' said Alejandro Hales, head of the
national lawyers' association and a prominent critic of Pinochet.
   ``I now hope the government will not resort to any legal
loopholes to prevent Chileans from exercising rights of which they
have been deprived for 15 years,'' Hales told reporters.
   Manuel Bustos, leader of the main labor conferation, called the
government's action positive ``because it creates better conditions
for a clean referendum.''
   The president of the country's Episcopal Conference, Monsignor
Carlos Gonzalez, lauded the government action.
   ``It makes me profoundly happy,'' Gonzalez said in remarks
broadcast by Radio Cooperativo of Santiago. ``I think this will
contribute to the peace of everyone, it gives tranquility, it gives
confidence.''
   Since Sept. 11, 1973, when Pinochet led a coup that toppled the
government of elected Marxist President Salvador Allende, Chile
always has been under a state of siege, of emergency or of
disturbance of internal peace. Each has been lifted at one time or
another, but never before have all been lifted and often more than
one has been in effect at the same time.
   According to Fernandez, the new decrees were issued because
authorities had established order within the country.
   ``The efforts of the competent (government) agencies to
guarantee public calm and order have born fruit,'' he said.
``Neither the cunning aggression of extremists nor the violence
that certain groups persistently utilize has managed to compromise
the general atmosphere of order, peace and progress.''
   The Roman Catholic Church, several foreign governments including
the United States, the political opposition and even many
government supporters had called for lifting the states of
emergency before the referendum. They said the ballot would lack
credibility if civil liberties were restricted during the political
campaign.
   Pinochet, navy commander Jose Merino, air force chief Fernando
Matthei and national police director Rodolfo Stange meet Aug. 30 to
pick the presidential nominee and announce a date for the
referendum. Pinochet is virtually assured of the nomination.
   Although the precise date of the ballot has not been announced,
Pinochet has said it will take place in early October. If the
candidate wins a majority in the vote, he will begin an eight-year
term in March. If a majority rejects him, open elections will be
held in 1990, with Pinochet remaining in place until then.
   According to lawyer Gustavo Villalobos of the local Catholic
church's human rights agency, the lifting of the states of
emergency could allow most of Chile's 504 political exiles to
return. The law allows for some exiles to remain barred from
returning, he told The Associated Press in an telephone interview.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
