<DOCNO> AP880824-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0728 08-24 0895</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0728,0924</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Reported Converging After More Polish Workers Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to UPDATE with police reported converging
on southern mines and port of Szczecin. PICKS up graf 17 pvs `An
army helicopter ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WAR53</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police converged on strikebound coal mines
and a port, activists said Thursday, after more workers joined
stoppages and Solidarity denounced official repression of the
protests.
   The government and workers are struggling for the initiative in
the biggest labor upheaval since Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski imposed
martial law in December 1981 to crush and then outlaw Solidarity,
the first independent labor union in the Soviet bloc.
   Strikers demand higher pay, better working conditions and that
Solidarity be made legal again.
   ``We condemn and strongly protest these acts,'' Tadeusz
Mazowiecki, a senior Solidarity adviser, said Wednesday of police
strike-breaking actions.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban was asked by telephone whether
the government was getting the upper hand and replied: ``There is
more and more news about strikes ended, but on the other hand there
are new centers of workers' conflicts still appearing.''
   Solidarity founder Lech Walesa declared to young strikers: ``It
is you, the young people, who will renew Solidarity and renew the
country.''
   Strikes began Aug. 16 and have spread to more than 20 sites.
   A Soviet spokesman said Wednesday his government was watching
the Polish strike situation with concern, but the Kremlin has not
made an official statement.
   In Hungary, where the Soviet army crushed an uprising in 1956,
more than 300 miners struck Wednesday against bonus cuts and a new
income tax. It was the first known worker protest of stringent
economic policies introduced by Karoly Grosz, who became Communist
Party chief in May.
   In northwest Poland, helicopters circled over the strikebound
Szczecin port early Thursday, and police massed outside its
barricaded gate, said Solidarity spokesman Piotr Niemczyk.
   Police invaded a bus depot in Szczecin early Wednesday, and 150
strikers who had been holed up there for a week yielded quietly. A
strike at the Mieszko coal mine in Walbrzych ended Tuesday night in
similar fashion when police broke down the barricaded gate.
   Adam Michnik, another senior Solidarity adviser, said: ``The
situation in Silesia has become extremely serious.''
   He said workers at other coal mines in southwestern Poland may
follow the example of those at the 30 Years of Poland mine, who
have barricaded themselves in more than 1,500 feet below the
surface.
   ``Other miners are preparing to evacuate (to) underground if
there are signs of intervention,'' Michnik said.
   Polish strikers occupy their job sites instead of walking out,
as do workers in the United States and other countries.
   The official news agency PAP said strikes ended peacefully at
the Lenin, Victoria, Marcel and Borynia mines, all in the Silesia
region of southern Poland, but Niemczyk said the ``voluntary''
evacuation at Borynia occurred only after riot police threatened a
raid.
   Late Wednesday, large convoys of police vehicles headed toward
strikebound coal mines in southern Poland, said an activist in
Jastrezebie, Lycyna Wujec.
   Up to 60 vehicles were seen going toward the July Manifesto mine
in Jastrezebie, where the strikes began last week, Ms. Wujec said.
The convoy consisted of police vans, armored personnel carriers,
water cannons and ambulances, said Ms. Wujec. She said about 12
other police vans headed to the Morcinek mine.
   Witnesses said earlier about 30 police vehicles had moved in
around the July Manifesto mine.
   An army helicopter hovered and a convoy of 103 police vehicles,
including water cannon, jeeps, trucks and an armored personnel
carrier, moved through the town, according to reporters at the
scene.
   Foreign journalists were barred from the mine area for the first
time since Aug. 16.
   About 1,000 employees quit working Wednesday in two departments
at the Nowa Huta steel mill, where a strike attempt fizzled after a
few hours Monday, said Maciej Mach, a worker leader who spoke from
the plant by telephone.
   Nowa Huta, which has 30,000 employees, was the scene of a major
strike during the last labor unrest in May, but a police raid ended
it.
   Solidarity activists said strikes spread on Wednesday to the
Knurow mine in Silesia and the Dzialoszyn cement works in central
Poland, but the government did not confirm the reports. PAP said
eight mines remained on strike and Solidarity spokesmen reported 10.
   The latest Gdansk strike brought all major dock and shipyard
industries to a halt in the Baltic port.
   Employees of the Lenin shipyard, where Walesa works as an
electrician, went on strike Monday in support of the miners and of
port and transport workers in Szczecin.
   Workers at the other port and shipyard facilities in Gdansk
quickly followed, paralyzing the nation's vital export industries.
Tons of high-grade export coal remain in rail cars at the
bulk-loading terminal, which has also been idle since Monday.
   Riot troops have sealed off all strikebound operations in Gdansk.
   Walesa led rallies at three shipyards Wednesday. Some of his
comments were on a tape provided to reporters.
   Hundreds of workers, including some on the deck of a Soviet ship
undergoing repair, listened as he blamed government leaders for
bringing Poland to economic ruin.
   In an effort to quell public unrest, the government has said a
special session of a parliament commission will review economic
policy later this month.
</TEXT>
