<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-CocaineWar     08-24 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Cocaine War,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medellin Mayor Says Cocaine Gangs' War Out Of Control</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A war between two Colombian gangs to
control New York City's cocaine market is out of control, the mayor
of Medellin said in a report published Wednesday.
   The commander of the national police in Medellin, Col. Antonio
Sanchez, asked the federal government on Wednesday to use state of
emergency and state of siege measures to combat the violence.
   On Tuesday, Mayor Juan Gomez Martinez told a news conference,
``The only thing we can do is increase the size of the police
force.''
   Gomez said it is impossible for Medellin to control the mob war
_ ``National or international help is needed.''
   Colombian newspapers reported the news conference in Wednesday's
editions.
   One gang has headquarters in Medellin, Colombia's second largest
city, and the other in Cali, the third largest city. The two
cartels have been at war for six months for supremacy of the New
York City cocaine market, estimated by Colombian authorities to be
worth $35 billion a year.
   Eighty gang members have been killed, 62 of them belonging to
the Cali mob.
   The entire nation has been under a state of siege for all but a
few months of the last 35 years. A state of siege was imposed anew
four years ago when drug traffickers assassinated Justice Minister
Rodrigo Lara Bonilla in the capital city of Bogota, Colombia's
largest city with 6 million people.
   President Virgilio Barco could use the state of siege to give
search and seizure authority to the army and other government
security forces without requiring them to act on a judge's orders.
   Barco also could impose curfews and restrict the right of public
assembly.
   Last year he issued a decree allowing the army to arrest and try
civilians in an effort to combat drug trafficking, but the Supreme
Court struck the decree down as unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
