<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DicksonToDixon 1stLd-Writethru a0686 08-24 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dickson To Dixon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0686,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warm Welcome Awaiting Soviet Delegation In Small-Town Illinois</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Soviets' arrival in
Chicago, Soviet journalist chiding U.S. bureaucracy, makes pvs
first reference to Mayor Dixon conform. Picks up 7th graf pvs `The
visitors...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DIXON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of President Reagan's boyhood
hometown say a friendly welcome is all the pomp and circumstance
they'll need for a weeklong ``Dickson to Dixon'' goodwill visit by
a delegation from Dickson, Siberia.
   ``It will be a very laid back and relaxed visit,'' Dixon City
Clerk Barbara Graff said Wednesday. ``They're coming here in the
spirit of harmony as a sister city. They will see how we live and
exist here. We will show them the American side of life.''
   The Soviet delegation _ Dickson Mayor Nikolai T. Kardamyshev,
journalist Boris S. Ivanov and interpreter Nikolai S. Vishnewvsky
of Moscow _ arrived in Chicago for the first leg of their American
journey. They planned to continue on about 100 miles west to Dixon
later Wednesday night.
   Mayor Kardamyshev and Dixon Mayor James E. Dixon shook hands
warmly after the visitors got off the plane.
   Ivanov noted that the delegation had to wait in line for two
hours in New York before getting their passports and visas checked,
and missed an earlier flight to Chicago.
   ``It's beautiful here, but your bureaucracy is much worse than
ours,'' Ivanov said.
   But he said he was looking forward to the visit because, ``I
want to learn more about the interesting people and places here.''
   In Dixon the group will be greeted by storefront signs
proclaiming ``Peace on Earth'' in English and Russian, and flags of
the United States and the Soviet Union.
   Rather than glitz, Dixon officials hope to impress the Soviets
with a scenic Rock River setting, seven miles of petunia-lined
streets, and friendly, hard-working, peace-loving residents.
   ``I want them to feel they are experiencing Midwestern American
hospitality,'' said Mayor Dixon. ``I want them to see our people at
work. To see what we produce. Hopefully, they will get a feel for
life in small-town America.''
   The visitors will view this town of 15,700 from a boat excursion
on the Rock River, in tours of factories and farms and in meals at
the local restaurants.
   ``We're going to take them to Pizza Hut and places like Arthur's
Garden Deli for sandwiches, stuffed baked potatos and frozen
yogurt,'' Dixon said.
   But mainly, they will get a heavy dose of Reagan history.
   The first thing on their agenda Thursday is a private tour of
Reagan's boyhood home, a two-story frame house on the city's south
side. Ronald ``Dutch'' Reagan, son of a shoe salesman and a dress
maker, lived there from 1920 until he left for college in 1928.
   Born in nearby Tampico, Ill., Reagan moved to Dixon with his
family when he was 9; it was here he began to show an interest in
drama, politics and athletics.
   In Dixon, Reagan appeared in his first school play and was
elected student council president. He served as a lifeguard on the
river, where proud Dixon residents brag, he saved 77 lives in seven
years.
   ``We want to show them what kind of community impacted on
(Reagan's) personality and ultimately on his presidency,'' Dixon
said. ``I want them to see that we are good people, friendly
people, and that we want peace.''
   The Soviets will be told of the city's history _ its founding as
a Rock River ferry-boat crossing in 1830 by Dixon's
great-great-great-grandfather John Dixon.
   They'll hear how Abraham Lincoln was stationed at Fort Dixon in
1832 at age 23 and fought Indians during the Black Hawk War, and
how Lincoln first met his Confederate adversary Jefferson Davis
when the two were stationed at the fort.
   The two cities established a sister-city relationship in early
1987 when Kardamyshev initiated greetings to the like-named town in
north-central Illinois.
   It's still not certain whether an Illinois delegation will be
able to visit Dickson, a town of 5,000 located in extreme northern
Siberia, above the Arctic Circle. The city, which was a staging
area for early Arctic explorers, is named for Oskar Dickson, a
19th-century Swedish merchant who provided supplies for the
expeditions.
   ``It's a remote, frontier village established as a weather and
oceanography facility,'' Dixon said. ``It is off-limits and a visit
may be difficult to work out. But I'd like to visit them. I think
it's important.''
</TEXT>
