<HEAD>Maria DeSillers Tries to Prevent Contempt Sentence</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `The contempt...,' to UPDATE with hearing to
continue Thursday; picks up 9th graf, `When curator...' INSERTS 5
grafs after 12th graf, `To this...' to UPDATE with later testimony;
picks up 13th graf pvs, `Ronnie, 7...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By A.J. DICKERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maria DeSillers went to court Wednesday to fight a
possible jail sentence for failing to turn over financial records
and luxury items allegedly purchased with donations for her late
son's liver transplants.
   At the opening of an often-acrimonious contempt hearing, the
attorney for the court-appointed curator of Ronnie DeSillers'
estate said Ms. DeSillers' fate was in her own hands.
   ``We are here with a sincere sense of regret,'' said Michael
Dribin. ``The curator-trustee has no desire to see Ms. DeSillers
punished ... the key to the jailhouse cell is held by Ms.
DeSillers.''
   As Dribin spoke, Ms. DeSillers muttered ``What a joke.''
   Ms. DeSillers' attorney, Roy Black, said he would show his
client had already complied with the court's demands.
   Dade Circuit Judge Francis Christie has repeatedly ordered Ms.
DeSillers to surrender a BMW car, jewelry, clothes and other items
believed bought with about $200,000 of the almost $700,000 donated
to pay for operations on Ronnie.
   So far, however, Ms. DeSillers has turned in only the car. Her
attorneys have complained that the order is unclear and includes
items she bought with with her own money.
   The contempt hearing was scheduled to continue Thursday. The
judge could rule immediately on whether to jail or fine Ms.
DeSillers, or take the decision under advisement.
   When curator Karen Gievers took the witness stand, Black
repeatedly attacked her testimony.
   Christie admonished Black several times to stop interrupting Ms.
Gievers, who testified she had never received documents that would
enable her to determine whether some of Ms. DeSillers' expenditures
were legitimate.
   Black grilled Ms. Gievers on whether she knew the intentions of
all the donors _ who include President Reagan _ and on whether the
money was given in Ronnie's name or his mother's.
   ``To this day I haven't gotten any of the information,'' Ms.
Gievers responded. ``I was trying to find out what the assets
were.''
   Black also criticized the curator for hiring expensive attorneys
without negotiating a fee first, but she said she would not have
had to pay anything if Ms. DeSillers had obeyed the court orders.
   Ms. Gievers also brushed aside Black's contention that by
turning over the financial records, Ms. DeSillers was being forced
to testify against herself.
   ``Ms. DeSillers cannot hide behind the Fifth Amendment and flout
the courts,'' said the curator.
   Black then called to the stand Christine Penrod, whose son was a
classmate of Ronnie DeSillers. Mrs. Penrod said Ms. DeSillers threw
herself into building a foundation for other transplant children
after her son died.
   ``It was disorganized, perhaps misguided _ I think it was her
way of handling grief,'' said Mrs. Penrod. ``Something needs to be
done for these children but it's not Maria DeSillers.'' She said
the effort was sincere, however.
   Ronnie, 7, died at Pittsburgh Children's Hospital in April 1987
after undergoing three unsuccessful liver transplants. Ms.
DeSillers has refused to pay $262,000 to the hospital, claiming
that her son received improper care.
   His case was widely publicized after more than $4,000 gathered
for him by schoolmates was stolen from a classroom closet, and
donations began pouring in from around the world.
</TEXT>
