<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Sudan-Floods 1stLd-Writethru a0738 08-24 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Floods, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0738,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Flood Damage Slowing Relief Effort</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with officials saying supplies slowed by
disrupted transportation and that Western countries not sending
enough aid. Official defends press censorship. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials on Wednesday said
flood-damaged roads and railways were slowing relief to the north
and complained that the United States and Europe were providing
little help, news media reported.
   The governor of Sudan's northern region, Abdul-Aziz al-Amin,
said the situation after flooding in his area was ``disastrous.''
He said ``relief and food supplies are non-existent.''
   In statements made to the daily al-Siyassa, he blamed the
shortage on disrupted transportation and said rail tracks had been
damaged by the floods.
   The state-run Sudan News Agency also said about one million
people in the northern provinces were in urgent need of relief
supplies.
   Torrential rains Aug. 4-5 in the northern provinces and around
the capital Khartoum left 1.5 million people homeless. The
government declared five disaster areas at the start of the floods,
including Dongola, 300 miles north of Khartoum, and el-Damer, 160
miles north east of the capital.
   On Tuesday, the waters of the Blue Nile overflowed in Khartoum
and Omdurman across the Nile from the capital, Egypt's state-run
Middle East News Agency reported.
   The confluence of the Blue and White Niles in Khartoum form the
Nile river that runs on through Egypt to enter the Mediterranean
Sea at Alexandria.
   International relief supplies were flown in, but Sudanese
officials repeatedly have said they only met 10 percent of the
actual needs.
   At a tea reception for foreign reporters Wednesday, Sayed
Abdallah Mohammed Ahmed, minister for Culture and Information,
attacked the United States and Europe for ``not supplying Sudan
with anyhing worth mentioning.'' He said 90 percent of relief
material received so far came from Arab countries, or 4,390 tons of
the total 4,775 tons.
   In statements carried by the news agency MENA, Ahmed said 13
Arab states had come to Sudan's rescue.
   ``What we need now is not food or blankets, but medicine and
agricultural material,'' he said. ``It is not important now to send
food, but to help us produce it.''
   Earlier Wednesday, Sudanese authorities said there was no
epidemic outbreak of diseases so far, quelling fears of fatal
diseases resulting from a scarcity of clean drinking water
following recent floods.
   Health officials said 19 cases of suspected cholera in and
around the capital proved to be only a mild form of diarrhea.
   Cholera and acute diarrhea kills the young and the weak. A lack
of fresh water supplies makes even basic treatment difficult.
   Officials said cases of malaria, another gastro-intestinal
infection, are on the rise, as are respiratory tract infections and
eye diseases.
   The reports were carried by the daily al-Ayam newspaper, quoting
unidentified health officials.
   Wednesday's reports seemed to contradict earlier statements from
the Sudanese Red Crescent, a relief organization, which last week
said more than 5,000 people were suffering from severe diarrhea,
most of them children. Officials reportedly had identified some
cases as malaria, cholera and typhoid.
   Following the floods, health officials predicted deadly
epidemics of water-borne diseases as people cut off from drinking
warter supplies are forced to drink from contaminated pools left
behind by the rainstorms and floods.
   In his meeting with foreign reporters, Ahmed defended the
government's decision to impose press censorship, saying these were
``ordinary measures used in democratic countries in Europe and the
United States ... to preserve the security and reputation of the
country.''
   On Tuesday, Ahmed ordered foreign journalists and photographers
to conduct interviews and take pictures only in the presence of an
information ministry representative. He said news stories and films
must be cleared before being allowed out of Sudan.
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi a day earlier criticized foreign
media for allegedly exaggerating the disastrous effects of flooding
in the capital and elsewhere, which has been called the worst in
Sudan's history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
