<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle 2nd-Writethru a0766 08-24 0919</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 2nd-Writethru, a0766,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle, On First Solo Trip, Tries to Keep Controversy at Arm's
Length</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with speech delivered; ADDS poll results;
EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle
told a National Guard assembly Wednesday, ``Dan Quayle doesn't run
away from a fight,'' as he sought during his first solo campaign
trip to set aside questions about his military record during the
Vietnam era.
   In an impassioned defense of his National Guard duty during the
war, the Indiana senator told a cheering audience of 1,000 present
and former Guard members that ``I'm not looking for any medals''
but ``I served loyally.''
   ``Nearly 20 years ago, I had no reason to be ashamed of my
service. And you know what, I'm sure as hell not ashamed of it
now!'' Quayle said. Quayle noted that Missourian Harry Truman also
served in the Guard, and said, ``Harry Truman never ran away from a
fight, and the National Guard never runs away either, and by the
way, Dan Quayle doesn't run away from a fight.''
   Quayle said he ``wasn't looking for favors'' when he entered the
Guard in 1969 and reiterated that ``no rules were broken'' and no
effort had been made to ``influence the process'' of his admission
during the height of the Vietnam War.
   ``I'm not looking for any medals. And I'm not asking for a pat
on the back. But let me say this: I served. I served loyally, and I
served to the best of my ability,'' Quayle said.
   The Indiana senator began this campaign swing seeking to shift
attention from the controversy and focus instead on his message of
peace, freedom and jobs.
   Almost at the very start, he had a good-natured airport
encounter with his Democratic counterpart, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas, who had just warned Southern state legislators not to ``risk
youthful indiscretion'' in someone like Quayle who might someday
ascend to the presidency.
   In the speech, he criticized Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis for an ``anti-defense attitude.''
   ``One of the worst false impressions Michael Dukakis has put
forward is the idea that he stands for a strong national defense,''
Quayle said. ``Maybe he sincerely believes that. But he stands for
the opposite, and that position has been clouded over by the
distractions of the last few days.''
   ``I suppose Michael Dukakis is enjoying this firestorm because
it's helping distract people from the issues of this campaign,'' he
said.
   An NBC-Wall Street Journal poll released Wednesday yielded some
encouraging results for Quayle. Sixty-four percent of the
respondents said Quayle's military record should not be an issue in
the campaign, while 27 percent said it should. Also, 42 percent of
registered voters approved of Quayle as the GOP vice presidential
nominee; 27 percent disapproved and 30 percent were not sure.
   The poll was conducted Saturday through Monday among 1,762
registered voters and had a margin of error of plus or minus three
points.
   During the day, Quayle kept out of range of reporters and sought
to concentrate on campaign issues and the prospective virtues of a
George Bush presidency. An aide said Quayle wanted to focus on
``things we want to talk about.''
   Quayle ignored reporters' shouted questions seeking a response
to Bentsen's remarks. Bentsen had tried to exploit Quayle's earlier
comment that his ``youthful indiscretion'' was to blame for his
vote against elevating the Veterans Administration to a
Cabinet-level department.
   Quayle's press secretary, David A. Prosperi, told reporters
later that if Dukakis, the Democratic candidate, were elected
president, the country would be plunged into a ``midlife crisis
because he knows very little about defense issues.''
   In appearances before Midwestern state legislators in Cincinnati
and a Southern legislative conference in Lexington, Ky., Quayle
avoided any discussion of his military record or allegations about
his past association with former lobbyist Paula Parkinson.
   Quayle, 41, the scion of a wealthy Indiana publishing family,
has denied that strings were pulled to get him into the Guard
during the Vietnam War or to gain his admission to Indiana
University Law School after a mediocre performance in college.
   Quayle's father, James C. Quayle, was quoted Wednesday in an
interview with the New York Daily News as saying his son had
majored in ``booze and broads.'' Quayle's spokesman refused comment.
   Quayle has also denied having a sexual affair with Paula
Parkinson, who shared a Florida vacation house with Quayle and
several other House members in 1980. Quayle termed ``outrageous'' a
Parkinson assertion that he had propositioned her.
   In his speeches before state lawmakers Wednesday, Quayle said he
was proud of a jobs training bill he had co-sponsored in the Senate
in the early 1980s. He said the legislation had resulted in
training 3.4 million economically disadvantaged people, ``and there
will be millions more.''
   ``These aren't make-work, makeshift type of jobs. These are real
jobs,'' Quayle said.
   He said he supported reforms of the federal budget process,
which is now carried out annually through budget resolutions and
appropriations and authorization bills.
   ``Congress has a three-layer cake out there, and one of them is
going to have to go,'' Quayle said.
   He said the budget should be drafted every two years, instead of
one, and that the president should be authority to veto individual
budget items rather than entire bills.
   ``I believe that the Congress could stand a little bit of
perestroika, to coin a phrase,'' Quayle said, referring to Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of economic restructuring.
</TEXT>
