<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HumphreyPlane     08-24 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Humphrey Plane,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Candidate Hubert Humphrey's Plane Makes Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane carrying Attorney General
Hubert H. Humphrey III made an emergency landing Wednesday in a
northwestern Minnesota field, a spokeswoman for Humphrey's U.S.
Senate campaign said.
   The six-seat Beechcraft Bonanza landed about 4:30 p.m. after
apparently developing engine difficulty about 10 minutes earlier,
said Karen Chandler, press secretary for the Humphrey campaign. She
said the four people aboard suffered no injuries.
   The campaign aide said the private plane was en route from St.
Paul to Moorhead, where Humphrey was to attend two fund-raisers and
a meeting Wednesday evening of the attorney general's task force on
prevention of violence against women.
   Other passengers were state Solicitor General Norman Coleman and
Lisa Hertzberg, a press aide.
   Chandler said Coleman told her the plane was in the Battle Lake
vicinity when it began sputtering. An air traffic controller
suggested that pilot Jim Thigpen land in Fergus Falls, about 20
miles away, but the pilot decided he couldn't make it that far, the
spokeswoman said.
   He put the plane down in a grassy field where the group was met
by a Northwest Airlines pilot who had seen the plane in trouble and
drove up to offer assistance, Chandler said.
   The Northwest pilot drove the group to Battle Lake, and the
county sheriff drove them about 75 miles to Moorhead, she said.
</TEXT>
