<HEAD>Jessica Hahn Signs Radio Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A radio station manager said Wednesday
that his station's hiring of Jessica Hahn as an on-air personality
was more than a publicity stunt.
   Hahn, whose sexual encounter with Jim Bakker led to the PTL
evangelist's downfall, has signed a 30-day contract starting Monday
with station KOY-FM.
   ``We feel that Jessica has the potential to develop into a
strong radio personality,'' said Jay Stevens, the station's
operations manager. ``That, coupled with her desire ... convinced
us.''
   He and Miss Hahn, who appeared in a white leather miniskirt, KOY
shirt and high heels, spent most of a 30-minute news conference
trying to convince reporters that the station was serious about
developing her into a fifth member of its morning show.
   The 29-year-old former church secretary did a test run on KOY's
``Y-Morning Zoo'' show Aug. 18, and listener reaction was
``overwhelmingly positive,'' Stevens said.
   Miss Hahn was modest about her qualifications, though.
   ``I'm not a professional. I know I need to learn a lot and
polish up,'' she acknowledged. Nevertheless, she said she had been
interested in being on radio for years and felt at home with KOY.
   Stevens said Miss Hahn's contract includes promotional
appearances but insisted the station, which has played elaborate
pranks in its search for publicity, was not trying to raise its
ratings. A public-relations firm distributed sheets from the
Tapscan Rating Analysis System showing KOY-FM sixth of 20 Phoenix
stations in listenership.
   The contract has a renewal option and Stevens said, ``We both
hope to make this a long-term agreement.'' But neither he nor Miss
Hahn would say definitely that she planned to be with the station
by October.
   Nude photographs of Miss Hahn following breast-enlargement and
other cosmetic surgery appear in Playboy magazine's latest issue.
   Stevens refused to discuss salary details, but Playboy spokesman
Bill Farley of Los Angeles said the contract included housing and
``very adequate'' compensation.
   Glenn Beck, another personality on the show, described Miss Hahn
as ``the Vanna White of the morning show. She's going to be our
prize-and-weather bunny.''
