<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0772 08-24 1093</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0772,1100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Nation Can't Risk `Youthful Indiscretion'; Reagan
Bolsters Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP two grafs new to UPDATE with Quayle speech; SUB 15th
graf, In an...Vietnam War, to edit, picking up 16th graf pvs, ``I'm
not...Quayle said.
^By DAVID ESPO</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd Bentsen criticized
Republican rival Dan Quayle's voting record on Wednesday and said
the nation can't risk ``youthful indiscretion'' so close to the
Oval Office. Quayle touted his work on jobs legislation and
defended his military record before a cheering National Guard
audience.
   ``Dan Quayle doesn't run away from a fight,'' the Indiana
senator told a group of 1,000 former and present Guard members in
St. Louis.
   George Bush campaigned in California with President Reagan, who
said Quayle ``stands for the same principles'' as he and the vice
president.
   Democrat Michael Dukakis received an endorsement from the
AFL-CIO in Washington, and charged that the legacy of the Reagan
administration was more jobs but lower family income.
   Meanwhile, two fresh polls indicated that the surge Bush
received during last week's Republican National Convention already
was dissipating. An NBC-Wall Street Journal survey put the vice
president's margin as 44-39, while a Harris survey pegged it at
49-47. Both leads were within the margin of error, indicating the
race is a dead heat.
   The two campaigns also sparred over the timing of campaign
debates for the fall. Dukakis aide Paul Brountas said it was
``inexcusable'' for Bush to decline dates of Sept. 8 and 14
established by organizations interested in staging the
confrontations. Bush campaign chief James Baker said, ``It is
unlikely that a debate can occur prior to Sept. 20.''
   But the political spotlight was uncharacteristically fixed on
campaign understudies, particularly on the 41-year-old Quayle and
the controversy about his Vietnam era stint in the National Guard.
   Democrat Bentsen told Southern legislators meeting in Lexington,
Ky., that Quayle had said earlier in the week that ``youthful
indiscretion'' initially led him to vote against Senate legislation
granting Cabinet-level status to the Veterans Administration.
   Bentsen also noted Quayle told the Veterans of Foreign Wars
convention that he had changed his mind on the subject and now
favored the bill. ``A youthful indiscretion? My friends, that vote
occurred only five weeks ago,'' Bentsen said. `I don't think
America can risk youthful indiscretion in someone who could become
our president at any moment.''
   At a news conference following his speech, Bentsen noted
Quayle's reversal on the VA bill and said, ``You've got to stand up
to that kind of heat.''
   He also referred indirectly to Quayle's Vietnam era stint in the
National Guard.
   ``I certainly don't think he's too young,'' Bentsen said of his
Senate colleague. ``But I think you have to have some maturity.''
   He added, ``And I think the breadth of experience that I've had
and the tests that I've undergone, some of the things that happened
to me early on, in combat, make you grow up pretty fast.''
   Quayle, in his debut as a campaign soloist, said he had helped
draft the Job Training and Partnership Act in the early 1980s,
which he claimed had provided jobs for millions of workers,
including women and poor people.
   ``This program is working. We have trained 3.4 million
economically disadvantaged people in America so far, and there will
be millions more,'' he said before flying on to Kentucky.
   In his St. Louis speech, Quayle said he ``wasn't looking for
favors'' when he entered the Guard in 1969. He said ``no rules were
broken'' and no effort had been made to ``influence the process''
of his admission during the height of the Vietnam War.
   ``I'm not looking for any medals. And I'm not asking for a pat
on the back. But let me say this: I served. I served loyally, and I
served to the best of my ability,'' Quayle said.
   The NBC-Journal poll yielded some encouraging results for
Quayle. Sixty-four percent said Quayle's military record should not
be an issue in the campaign, while 27 percent said it should. Also,
42 percent of registered voters approved of Quayle as the GOP vice
presidential nominee; 27 percent disapproved and 30 percent were
not sure.
   Dukakis made no mention of Quayle as he traveled to Washington
to receive his endorsement from the AFL-CIO. In a speech to union
members, he promised ``new economic patriotism'' based on strong
business-labor relations.
   The Massachusetts governor conceded that more Americans hold
jobs than ever before, but said low-paying positions have been the
legacy of the Reagan administration and that average family income
is no greater than it was 20 years ago.
   ``That's the price our workers and their families are paying for
voodoo economics,'' he said in a speech in a hotel a few blocks
from the White House.
   Bush campaigned with Reagan for the first time since winning the
Republican nomination next week. He sought to deflect attention
away from the controversy over his running mate, accusing Dukakis
of ``looking for a reason'' to veto Massachusetts legislation
requiring teachers to lead their students in recitation of the
Pledge of Allegiance.
   ``What is it about the Pledge of Allegiance that upsets him so
much?'' Bush asked. Dukakis has said he vetoed the bill after
receiving an advisory opinion from the state Supreme Court that the
measure was unconstitutional.
   Reagan heaped praise on his vice president.
   ``George Bush is a man of action _ a man accustomed to
command,'' Reagan told a rally at the hotel where the president is
staying during a break from his California ranch vacation.
   ``The vice presidency doesn't fit easily on such a man,'' he
said. ``But George Bush is also a patriot. And so he made it fit,
and he served with a distinction no one has ever matched.''
   Dukakis aide Brountas said the Massachusetts governor intends to
go ahead with plans to be in Annapolis on Sept. 14, the date
selected by a bipartisan presidential commission for a debate on
national security issues. He said Bush's decision not to debate
before Sept. 20 ``threatens the full schedule of debates
anticipated for the fall.''
   But Baker said it was ``unlikely'' that Bush could debate before
Sept. 20 because the Republican National Convention concluded only
last week.
   Aides to the two candidates are expected to open face to face
negotiations on debates next week in Washington.
   The NBC-Journal poll was conducted Saturday through Monday among
1,762 registered voters, the Harris poll Friday through Monday
among 1,310 likely voters. Both had error margins of plus or minus
three points.
</TEXT>
