<1ST_LINE>u a AM-VesselsCollide 1stLd-Writethru a0672 08-24 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vessels Collide, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0672,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Fishing Vessel Collides With Freighter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to to UPDATE with status of vessels,
CORRECT name of Soviet ship to Irtyshsk sted Bamityhsk, CLARIFY
that Brodeur was referring to Panamanian ship; picks up 6th graf
pvs, `The Canadian...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet fishing vessel collided with a
Panamanian freighter in the fog Wednesday off the Canadian coast,
the Coast Guard said.
   There were no injuries, said Coast Guard Chief Roy Compton.
   Coast Guard Petty Officer Michael Cobb said the freighter, Ocean
Fame, took on water from a gash in its bow and proceeded under its
own power to Barkley Sound on Vancouver Island's southwest coast.
Canadian Coast Guard officials examined the freighter.
   Cobb said the Soviet vessel, Irtyshsk, remained in the vicinity
of the collision and was unloading some of its diesel fuel to
another Soviet fishing boat.
   The collision occurred about 6:30 a.m. about 35 miles north of
Cape Flattery, Wash., and the Coast Guard cutter Clover was at the
scene, the Coast Guard said.
   The Soviet vessel carried a crew of 120; the 500-foot Panamanian
freighter, which left Vancouver on Tuesday loaded with grain for
Japan, had a crew of 18.
   Micheline Brodeur of Transport Canada said she did not have
details of the Panamanian ship's damage, but added, ``Apparently
there was some concern for a while that it would sink.''
   The Canadian naval support vessel Glendyne was to check any
damage on the Soviet boat, she said. The Canadian Marine Casualty
Investigation branch would investigate the accident, Ms. Brodeur
said.
   A Navy spokesman in Seattle, Senior Chief James Jones, declined
to speculate on whether the Soviet vessel was gathering
intelligence on Trident submarines based at the Navy's base at
Bangor.
   In the past, Soviet vessels have parked outside the Strait of
Juan de Fuca to gather information about the nuclear submarines,
which must use the strait between coastal Canada from Washington's
Olympic Peninsula to reach the Pacific Ocean.
   Jones said the intelligence-gathering ships usually are not
disguised as fishing vessels and plainly display their radar towers
and other monitoring devices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
