<1ST_LINE>a a PM-Subirrigation ADV29   08-24 0861</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Subirrigation, ADV 29,0888</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, Aug. 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Drought Puts Spotlight on Underground Irrigation System</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAD AXE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the country's worst drought in half a
century hit this summer, desperate Michigan farmers kept co-op
extension agent Jim LeCureaux's phone ringing.
   Many wanted to know about his tests of a low-cost irrigation
system that also controls flooding and sharply boosts crop yields.
   Hard times have given LeCureaux a ready audience for his pitch
about the wonders of subirrigation.
   ``It's not a new concept. It's just being refined,'' he said
from the office of the Huron County Cooperative Extension Service,
which serves farmers in the tip of Michigan's fertile Thumb region,
a wide peninsula jutting into Lake Huron.
   In controlled studies last year, subirrigated corn fields
produced up to 60 more bushels an acre than non-irrigated fields,
LeCureaux said.
   This year, sugar beets were added to the studies.
   ``It sure helps in dry seasons,'' said LeRoy Kretzschmer, who
uses subirrigation on about 200 acres of the 1,800-acre farm he and
his brothers operate near Caseville. It is one of two county sites
where pilot studies are being conducted this year.
   ``We're kind of going little-by-little now, but eventually, if
this works out, we'll irrigate more,'' he said.
   Kretzschmer and LeCureaux are part of a network of researchers,
agricultural agents and farmers who are fine-tuning an irrigation
technique first used in 19th century Europe.
   Subirrigation is a two-phased water control system that uses
underground pipes, drainage ditches and pumps to keep just the
right amount of moisture in the field.
   ``The idea is very old,'' said Jim Fouss, a researcher at the
U.S. Department of Agriculture's lab in Baton Rouge, La. A form of
subirrigation was employed in New York's Central Park in 1858, he
said.
   ``If the drainage system that you use during wet season can be
used to put water back on, then you essentially get it for free,''
Fouss said.
   Ironically, subirrigation is a system for putting water into
fields that once were considered too wet to farm.
   About 100 million acres of U.S. farmland need some kind of
drainage in order to grow crops effectively, according to Fouss,
who is working to design computer rain forecasts to help run
subirrigation systems.
   Typically, the land is low and flat, with a layer of bedrock or
clay within a few feet of the surface, creating a high water table.
   The soil remains saturated from the spring rains and snowmelt,
often forcing farmers to put off planting until late in the growing
season. The same problem often occurs in the fall, making it
difficult or impossible to harvest the crops.
   These soil conditions are common along the Atlantic seaboard, in
the Ohio, Mississippi and Missouri river basins and in portions of
the Great Lakes region, including Michigan's Thumb.
   But as quickly as farmers installed underground drainage on
their land, they began encountering another problem _ drought.
   Farmers in Georgia and the Carolinas ran into this problem when
large-scale drainage projects went in 40 to 50 years ago, said
Claude Phene, a U.S. Department of Agriculture scientist in Fresno,
Calif., who did early subirrigation research while working at a
USDA lab in Florence, S.C.
   Farmers who installed underground drain pipes to remove enough
water in order to plant in the spring often would find their crops
parched for water by summer. But by damming up some of the runoff
in the drainage ditches, they found they could put water back into
their fields through the same pipes.
   By hit or miss, farmers discovered that by conserving a certain
amount of water in drainage ditches, they could maintain proper
moisture in the plants' root zones during drier summer weather as
water flowed back into the fields.
   In prolonged dry weather, however, drainage ditches couldn't
hold enough water to keep the soil moist, so some farmers began
pumping water into the ditches from streams or wells.
   Because of the expense of installing miles of heavy tile pipes,
subirrigation made sense only for high-value crops such as
vegetables. Now, with the development of lighter plastic piping and
laser-guided installation equipment, the system has became feasible
for use on field crops as well, Fouss said.
   ``It's not a major irrigation practice yet, but it's grown quite
a bit in the last 10 years,'' Phene said. The appeal of
subirrigation, he said, isn't so much that it raises yields but
rather that it smooths the ups and downs.
   ``We want consistent production, a sustainable yield. We're not
trying for the maximum yield,'' said George Merva of Michigan State
University, who is conducting research on the most effective water
levels for subirrigating corn and soy beans.
   He and other researchers say it isn't yet clear how widely
subirrigation can profitably be applied.
   Although this year's drought has had disastrous consequences for
many farmers, it might also prod some into seeking greater
independence from natural rainfall, LeCureaux said.
   This year, farmers are willing to listen.
   ``If you're looking for a teachable moment,'' he said, ``you've
got her.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, Aug. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
