<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-Emmys ADV26-28   08-24 1048</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Emmys, ADV 26-28,1076</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug. 26-28</NOTE>
<HEAD>Emmy Celebrates Its 40th Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Emmys-List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like other 40-year-olds, Sunday night's
Emmy Awards is fighting to stay youthful.
   While liposuction has yet to be contemplated, the ``40th Annual
Prime Time Emmy Awards'' are being produced this year by someone
who has built a career out of spoofing the very medium the Emmys
are intended to celebrate.
   Lorne Michaels, as the creator and original producer of NBC's
``Saturday Night Live,'' has excelled at trashing television from
top to bottom, from biting game-show and newscast parodies to
scathing ``Highway Patrol'' and ``Ozzie and Harriet'' send-ups.
   But can Michaels satirize the Emmys themselves?
   ``Well, this show won't take itself too seriously,'' Michaels
said.
   If the Emmy telecast, carried live by the Fox Broadcasting Co.
at 8 p.m. EDT, has suffered in the past, it has sprung from its
unerring aptitude for boredom _ last year's ceremony, at four
hours, was just 20 seconds shy of qualifying for a miniseries.
   Michaels said ``too many awards'' are handed out at the Emmys.
That he can't change. ``So, in trying to make the show
entertaining, what I've tried to do is strip it down to its core _
the awards _ and make that go as quickly as possible, and then try
to weave the entertainment parts through it.''
   Michaels promised there would not be any production numbers
``per se,'' whatever that means, and he said he would ``try to
squeeze some comedy'' into the usually dull Governors Award, given
this year to animators William Hanna and Joseph Barbera.
   Michaels, a six-time Emmy winner, will be joined in the control
booth at the Pasadena Civic Auditorium by Dave Wilson, the longtime
``Saturday Night Live'' director. And he plans to use several
celebrities, including Mary Tyler Moore, Dick Van Dyke, Danny
DeVito and Michael J. Fox, as hosts rather than depend on an
individual.
   It's hard to say if another new Emmy twist is serious or not. In
one of the stranger moves in Emmy lore, this year's Emmy statuette,
normally cast in gold, pewter and iron, is being played by a person.
   The human Emmy is Norwegian actress Benedikte Handal.
   ``We talked to over a hundred women before we found Benedikte
Handal,'' said Lewis Goldstein, a vice president of off-air
promotion for Fox Broadcasting. ``She had the ethereal quality we
were looking for.''
   Handal is being used in national television advertisements for
the awards broadcast, and her ``ethereal qualities'' will also be
displayed in posters and newspaper spots plugging the show.
   Handal will not, however, be handed out to award winners.
   The closer Emmy races this year revolve around NBC's hot drama
series ``L.A. Law'' and CBS newcomer ``Beauty and the Beast.''
   For the second year in a row, ``L.A. Law'' gathered more
nominations, 19, than any other television program. The series will
be competing for best drama series, best actor in a drama series
for Michael Tucker and Corbin Bernsen and best actress in a drama
series for Jill Eikenberry and Susan Dey.
   ``Beauty and the Beast,'' an improbable hit about a love affair
between an attorney and a hulking, hairy denizen of Manhattan's
underground, and NBC's geriatric comedy ``The Golden Girls'' tied
for the second-most nominations with 12 apiece.
   The nominees for best drama series, in addition to ``L.A. Law''
and ``Beauty and the Beast,'' are ABC's ``thirtysomething'' and
NBC's recently canceled ``St. Elsewhere.'' Joining ``The Golden
Girls'' in the race for best comedy series are ABC's ``The Wonder
Years,'' NBC's ``Cheers'' and ``Night Court'' and CBS' ``Frank's
Place,'' which has yet to be placed on the network's fall schedule.
   The nominees for best miniseries are ABC's ``Baby M'' and NBC's
``Billionaire Boys Club,'' ``Gore Vidal's Lincoln'' and ``The
Murder of Mary Phagan.''
   Up for best actor in a drama series are ``L.A. Law's'' Tucker
and Bernsen, Ron Perlman from ``Beauty and the Beast,'' Edward
Woodward of CBS' ``The Equalizer'' and Richard Kiley, star of NBC's
``A Year in the Life.''
   Competing for best actor in a comedy series are Ted Danson of
NBC's ``Cheers,'' Fox from NBC's ``Family Ties,'' Tim Reid from
``Frank's Place,'' John Ritter, star of ABC's ``Hooperman'' and
Dabney Coleman, the lead in ABC's canceled ``The `Slap' Maxwell
Story.''
   On the women's side, the nominees for best actress in a drama
series, joining ``L.A. Law's'' Eikenberry and Dey, are Angela
Lansbury from CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote'' and Sharon Gless and Tyne
Daly, co-stars of CBS' ``Cagney & Lacey.'' The finalists for best
actress in a comedy series are Kirstie Alley from NBC's ``Cheers,''
Blair Brown from NBC's canceled ``The Days and Nights of Molly
Dodd,'' and three actresses _ Rue McClanahan, Beatrice Arthur and
Betty White _ from ``The Golden Girls.''
   Television's most popular program, NBC's ``The Cosby Show,''
collected just one nomination, for a guest performance by Eileen
Heckart; its spinoff, ``A Different World,'' the second most
popular show, had none.
   For the first time in Emmy history, cable television programs
are eligible for trophies, although chances are slim that any cable
show will emerge with that strong a showing.
   The cable shows drew 15 of the 337 nominations their first time
out _ Home Box Office and Showtime each collected six nominations,
the Disney Channel drew two and Turner Broadcasting System had one.
   Among the cable companies' best chances for an Emmy are best
writing in a comedy series (Showtime's ``It's Garry Shandling's
Show'' is nominated twice) and best informational special (HBO's
acclaimed ``Dear America: Letters Home From Vietnam'').
   NBC leads the three networks with 114 nominations, followed by
CBS with 87 and ABC with 75. The Public Broadcasting Service
gathered 27 nominations and Fox, struggling to become television's
``fourth network,'' drew six.
   In addition to the United States, the awards show will be
broadcast to 21 foreign countries, representing a potential
audience of 1 million viewers.
   Countries planning to broadcast the Emmy program live include
Australia, Canada, the Bahamas, Bermuda, New Zealand and Venezuela.
   Airing the program on a delayed basis will be Bangladesh, the
Dominican Republic, El Salvador, Ecuador, Guatemala, Honduras, Hong
Kong, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, South Korea
and Taiwan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug. 26-28</NOTE>
