<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grocery prices jumped 1.4 percent in July, the
biggest monthly increase since early 1984, as the drought's effects
reached supermarket checkout counters, the government has reported.
   However, there was little evidence of accelerating retail price
inflation elsewhere in the U.S. economy, the Labor Department
report indicated Tuesday. Excluding food, overall retail prices
rose just 0.3 percent for the month, slower than the pace of the
first half of 1987, the department said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods, hurt
by a drop in demand in the volatile transportation sector, fell a
sharp 7 percent in July, the biggest setback in four years, the
government says.
   The Commerce Department reported Tuesday that orders for durable
goods, items expected to last at least three years, fell $8.8
billion to a seasonally adjusted $116.6 billion last month as
demand dropped off for ships and tanks, autos and aircraft.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald P. Kelly, a near-legendary dealmaker, has
resigned as chairman of Beatrice Co. as the company moves away from
megabuck corporate spinoffs to focus on its main food operations.
   Kelly, 66, still will play a role as a director and major
investor in Beatrice, the food giant he has pruned relentlessly
over the past two years, a spokeswoman said Tuesday.
   Frederick B. Rentschler, Beatrice's president and chief
executive officer, will continue to run privately-held Beatrice on
a daily basis.
