<DOCNO> AP880824-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Polaroid     08-24 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polaroid,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Date Set In Shamrock Challenge To Stock Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. says it discussed
increasing an employee stock ownership plan ``long before there was
any whisper'' of a takeover bid from Roy E. Disney's Shamrock
Holdings Inc.
   Shamrock, a California investment firm owned by the Disney
family, claimed in a lawsuit filed in July that Polaroid improperly
increased an employee stock ownership plan from 5 percent to 14
percent to help thwart an unwanted acquisition.
   Carolyn Berger, a vice chancellor of Delaware's Court of
Chancery, scheduled hearings for Oct. 19-25 on Shamrock's suit to
halt the expansion, a court clerk said Tuesday.
   Cambridge-based Polaroid is a Delaware-chartered corporation.
Delaware's takeover law prohibits acquirers who obtain 15 percent
of a company's stock from completing a takeover for three years,
unless they have approval from the target's board of directors or
acquire at least 85 percent of the target's stock.
   Richard F. DeLima, Polaroid's vice president and secretary, said
Tuesday the company's board of directors had considered increasing
the size of the ESOP after it first was approved in March.
   ``By the time of the July (board) meeting, we were aware of
Shamrock's interest in the company and were thoughtful about
whether our plans for the ESOP might be interfered with,'' he said.
   DeLima said that in the period between the ESOP's approval and
its increase, Polaroid's board determined it could increase the
size of the stock issue to 10 million shares with ``relatively
modest'' reductions in pay and benefits.
   On Aug. 16, Polaroid rejected a sweetened takeover proposal from
Shamrock of $40 per share and 40 percent of any settlement in
Polaroid's $5.7 billion patent infringement case against Eastman
Kodak Co.
   Shamrock, which owns 6.9 percent of Polaroid, contends Polaroid
increased the number of shares in the stock issue after getting
wind of its bid.
   The increased ESOP was announced July 12 as part of a
reorganization that included the $300 million stock purchase plan,
up to 800 layoffs and entry into the conventional film market.
Polaroid last week announced it was targeting 1,500 early
retirements in a streamlining effort aimed at fighting the takeover.
   One Wall Street securities analyst said that because employees
who own the stock can decide whether to sell their shares, a
hostile takeover of Polaroid technically is not impossible despite
the 14 percent employee control.
   ``As a practical matter, it really does make it harder,'' said
the analyst, who asked not to be named. ``The legal fiction is that
each employee is an individual stockholder. ... They can play the
arbitrage business too.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880824-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WindfallProfits-Reax     08-24 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Windfall Profits-Reax,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texans Applaud Windfall Profits Tax Repeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas oil producers and politicians say the repeal
of the federal windfall profits tax is only the first step needed
to help revive the oil and gas industry.
   Financial incentives for exploration and to keep marginally
producing wells in operation also are needed, oilmen say.
   The landmark trade bill President Reagan signed into law Tuesday
in California included the repeal of the eight-year-old windfall
profits tax on oil companies.
   John E. Watson, president of the Texas Independent Producers and
Royalty Owners Association, said the trade group had fought for
repeal since the tax was signed into law in 1980.
   The windfall profits tax was enacted in exchange for the
phase-out of price controls on domestic oil. Congress was
attempting to recapture some of the money oil companies were
expected to make when prices increased after full decontrol began
in 1981.
   About $77.3 billion in taxes have been collected since it was
imposed.
   Although low oil prices have kept oil companies from paying much
windfall profits tax during the past 2{ years, oil producers still
have had to certify their production and report it to the Internal
Revenue Service, Watson said.
   The base crude oil price upon which the tax is levied is between
$19 and $20 a barrel for independent producers, Watson said. Crude
oil sold for about $15 a barrel Tuesday.
   ``Of course, when you're not paying any tax, and it gets
repealed, it's not going to have a whole lot of immediate monetary
effect on you,'' Watson said. ``Some accounting work will be taken
off our back, hopefully.''
   Both U.S. senators from Texas, Democratic vice presidential
nominee Lloyd Bentsen and Republican Phil Gramm, played prominent
roles in the effort to repeal the tax.
   ``It is in fact the first positive step Congress has taken on
oil in a decade,'' Gramm said in a telephone interview Tuesday.
``They (oil companies) won't have to figure in this confiscatory
tax in figuring their benefits.''
   But Watson said that to further help the beleaguered oil and gas
industry, federal financial incentives are needed for marginal and
stripper wells.
   Stripper wells generally produce less than 10 barrels of oil a
day. Wells are considered marginal if production is low in
comparison to the amount of revnue obtained, Watson said.
   He also tax credits are needed for exploratory wells.
   Major oil companies fared well in the last quarter, said Watson,
whose organization includes about 4,000 independent producers and
royalty owners.
   ``Independents, on the other hand are still struggling. They're
still falling by the wayside,'' he said.
   Gramm said the oil industry has continued to pay an estimated
$100 million in complying with the tax rules during each of the
past two years, even though oil companies have paid only small
amounts of the actual tax.
   The federal government has spent about $15 million each of the
past two years for paperwork overseeing the tax, he said.
   Gramm said other measures, including tax incentives to spur
drilling and deregulation of gas prices, are still needed to boost
the industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880824-0250 </DOCNO>
