<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-24 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower Against Most Currencies, Gold Falls Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against most major foreign
currencies in early European trading today following remarks by
Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita.
   Gold prices also fell slightly in extremely quiet trading.
   The dollar slid after Sumita said the West German mark's decline
was ``inexplicable'' and termed a further drop in the yen as
undesirable.
   Selling pressure on the dollar then intensified when dealers
reported that the Deutsche Bundesbank, West Germany's central bank,
was selling dollars on the open market.
   ``No matter how well-bid the dollar still is, after the massive
interventions of the past few days, a pause is needed,'' said one
senior trader in Rome.
   But he stressed that market sentiment remains favorable toward
the dollar and that the currency could still rebound.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.37 yen to a closing 134.30 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 134.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.8957 West German marks, down from 1.9060; 1.5990
Swiss francs, down from 1.6055; 6.4415 French francs, down from
6.4635; 2.1395 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1440; 1,406.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,407.50; and 1.2305 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2303.
   In London, the British pound was unchanged from late Tuesday at
$1.6795.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $432 a troy ounce and at
midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $432.10. Both were down from Tuesday's late
bid of $432.75.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $432.10, down from $433 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 59 cents to close at a bid $434.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.73 a troy
ounce, down from Tuesday's $6.74.
</TEXT>
