<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0745EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FarmScene     08-24 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Cattle Prices Up Sharply in August</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices of fed cattle are topping $70 per
hundredweight in late August, up sharply from $66 in July, says the
Agriculture Department.
   ``The recent price strength reflects tighter supplies of
finished (fattened) cattle, stronger export demand and continued
brisk movement at retail,'' the department's Economic Research
Service said Tuesday.
   In all, cattle slaughter in August may rise only 8 percent from
July, although there are two additional working days this month,
which would suggest as much as a 10 percent increase from July, the
agency reported.
   ``Cow slaughter has begun picking up,'' the report said.
``However, this appears to be a seasonal movement of beef cows off
grass (pasture) rather than a forced drought movement.''
   There had been an increase in cow slaughter earlier this summer
as some producers in the drought-stricken Northern Plains and in
the lakes states were forced to send beef and dairy cows to market
because of feed shortages.
   In many cases, however, quality breeding animals have been
purchased by producers in other areas where feed is available, thus
forestalling massive sell-offs of herds.
   According to federal inspection reports, the slaughter of beef
cows this year through the first week in August totaled about 1.89
million head, down 9 percent from the same period in 1987. airy cow
slaughter, at 1.66 million head, dropped 3 percent.
   Prices of fed cattle in the southern Great Plains are selling
for more than $70 per 100 pounds of live weight in late August, up
from $66 in July, the report said.
   Beef from cows goes mainly into hamburger and processing, while
grain-fed steers and heifers provide the higher-grade cuts found in
supermarkets.
   Looking at pork, the report said weekly slaughter is expected to
increase sharply in September, pushing prices down.
   Meanwhile, hot weather has disrupted marketings and slowed
weight gains of hogs. That has lent some support to ``an otherwise
weak market'' this summer, the report said.
   Wholesale prices of dressed broiler chickens in early August
remained around 70 cents a pound, well above the 53 cents of a year
earlier. Prices should average around 61 to 65 cents a pound during
the third quarter, the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says farmers have
developed conservation plans for protecting 54 million acres of
highly erodible cropland, about 38 percent of the 143 million acres
targeted for protection by the 1985 farm law.
   Wilson Scaling, chief of the Soil Conservation Service, said
Tuesday that plans have been put into effect on 17 million acres,
or about 12 percent of the affected land.
   Under the 1985 law, farmers who raise crops on highly erodible
land must have a conservation plan approved by Dec. 31, 1989, and
implement it fully by Dec. 31, 1994, to remain eligible for USDA
program benefits.
   ``We are on target for meeting the 1989 deadline,'' Scaling
said. ``We hope to have 65 percent of the plans completed by the
end of 1988 and the remaining 35 percent completed by the end of
1989.''
   However, Scaling cautioned farmers not to wait until the last
minute to request technical assistance from SCS because they might
have a long wait.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exports of U.S. horticultural products such as
fruit and nuts totaled $246 million in June, a 20 percent increase
from a year earlier, says the Agriculture Department.
   The shipments, not counting those to Canada, included a strong
showing by all products within the horticultural category.
   ``Sales of fresh fruit and tree nuts accounted for 49 percent of
export value in June,'' the department's Foreign Agricultural
Service reported Tuesday. ``Inshell almond exports reached $21.7
million, with most shipments going to the European Community and
Japan.''
   Japan also accounted for 86 percent of the $21.6 million worth
of lemons and grapefruit exported in June, the report said.
</TEXT>
