<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FiggieMove     08-24 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Figgie Move,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Figgie International To Move Corporate Headquarters Back To
Cleveland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Figgie International, which moved its
corporate headquarters to suburban Richmond in 1982, is returning
to Cleveland, a newspaper reported today.
   Cleveland Councilman John E. Barnes told The Richmond
Times-Dispatch that the company will build a new headquarters on
600 acres of city-owned land just outside Cleveland in Warrensville
Township. Figgie will buy the land from city, Barnes said.
   ``There are several reasons'' for Figgie's decision to leave
Richmond, Barnes told the newspaper. ``Cleveland is within 500
miles of nearly 60 percent of the nation's population. It is a
strategic location and it is hot for development now.''
   The move will add at least 1,500 jobs to the Cleveland area and
possibly as many as 15,000 when operations are at full steam,
Barnes said.
   Officials in Henrico County, where Figgie bought 1,500 acres in
1982, said they had done everything they could to persuade the
company to stay.
   ``I'm sorry to see them leave,'' said Supervisor Richard W.
Glover. ``Certainly we'd like to have them here. I think they're
quite an asset to Henrico County, but the land stays here. I'm sure
that there will be others to come and I'm sure that there will be
others to go.''
   Figgie officials could not be reached for comment Tuesday night.
   A news conference was scheduled for 3 p.m. today in Cleveland to
make a formal announcement of the move, Barnes said.
   Harry E. Figgie Jr., chairman and chief executive officer, had
said in April that the company moved to Richmond from its former
headquarters in Willoughby, Ohio, because of the Virginia city's
stable labor climate, good general business conditions and access
to transportation systems. He said there would have to be an
economic reason to move back to Ohio.
   Revenues in 1987 for the diversified company, which makes a
range of products from baseballs to fire trucks, were a record
$1.02 billion, up 11 percent from 1986. Its 1987 profits were $49.3
million, up from $42.4 million in 1986. Sales in the first quarter
of this year increased 12 percent over the same period last year.
   The paper reported that sources said tax advantages lured the
company to move to Cleveland.
   ``I would think it's more than some tax abatement,'' said Paul
Ellsworth, president of the Metropolitan Richmond Chamber of
Commerce, citing the expense of moving. ``There have to be a lot of
issues.''
   Henrico supervisors said they had not known of the impending
move until last night and did not know if the company intends to
sell its Virginia property.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
