<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ExplosivesStrike     08-24 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Explosives Strike,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Union Back To Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300 longshoremen protesting the
use of non-union labor to load explosives onto a military ship have
been ordered to return to work by a federal judge.
   A temporary restraining order was issued Tuesday by U.S.
District Judge Howell W. Melton against members of International
Longshoreman's Association Local 1408, who had refused to return to
work at Blount Island until the ship left port.
   Charles Spencer, president of the ILA local, said the workers
would immediately comply with the judge's order.
   The court order was requested by the Jacksonville Maritime
Association, which represented the owners of four ships filled with
Hondas, Mazdas, Isuzus and Subarus waiting to be unloaded by the
ILA.
   The union had refused to unload the ships to protest the use of
non-union labor by Florida Transportation Services Inc. of Fort
Lauderdale to load explosives on a military ship.
   A similar work stoppage occurred on June 20 when the union
refused to work when the same company unloaded explosives from
another military ship.
   The union claimed the use of non-union labor to handle the
explosives was unsafe because the workers were inexperienced in
handling the devices.
   The judge's injunction will remain in effect until Sept. 2 when
the union and the Maritime Association will meet in his courtroom.
The judge asked the two parties to try and work out their
differences by that time.
   The next scheduled work by Florida Transportation is Sept. 8
when it will unload explosives from a ship.
</TEXT>
