<2ND_LINE>PM-Ashland Suit,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ashland, Former Executives Settle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland Oil Inc. has agreed to pay two
former executives who claimed they were illegally fired for
refusing to offer bribes to foreign officials a total of $25
million, ending a bitter four-year legal battle.
   In announcing the agreement Tuesday, U.S. District Judge William
O. Bertelsman said the settlement was ``fair and reasonable.''
   Ashland Chairman John R. Hall, Senior Vice President Richard
Spears and the company also were assessed a total of $3 million in
punitive damages for their treatment of the two men.
   Former vice presidents Bill McKay and Harry Williams had claimed
they were illegally fired for refusing to offer bribes to foreign
officials or to cover up such bribes.
   A court earlier had found that Ashland had violated the
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act by engaging in a
pattern of illegal interstate activity to obtain oil in the late
1970s and early 1980s that led to the men's dismissal.
   A spokesman for Ashland Oil and an attorney for McKay declined
to comment on the settlement except to confirm it. Attorneys for
Williams could not be reached for comment.
   Bertelsman said McKay and Williams would decide how they would
split the $25 million.
   A hearing on a request by the company for a new trial or for a
different judgment that had been scheduled for Thursday was
canceled.
</TEXT>
