<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Metalworkers-GM     08-24 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Metalworkers-GM,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unions Concerned Over Heavier Work Schedule At GM Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unions representing 120,000 General Motors Corp.
workers in Europe criticized the automaker Wednesday for moving
toward longer shifts as well as weekend and night work.
   The new policy will mean increased stress, fatigue and
disruption of family life, the International Metalworkers'
Federation said.
   Auto industry union officials from West Germany, Britain, Spain,
Belgium, France, Austria and Portugal met under the federation's
auspices Wednesday in Geneva to coordinate strategy.
   A federation statement also said GM management has sought to
increase plant running time since moving its European headquarters
to Zurich in 1986 in a bid to reduce social regulation by the
European Economic Community to a minimum.
   At its Antwerp plant, GM has begun 10-hour shifts and regular
Saturday work under the threat of plant closures and layoffs, the
federation's general secretary Herman Rebhan said.
   GM Spain has introduced night shifts and hired many temporary
contract workers with little job security, he said.
   West German unions have resisted similar moves but have been
threatened with 9,000 layoffs by 1992, Rebhan added.
   ``These new shift systems will worsen future conditions for
workers,'' he said. ``The price is being paid for by workers'
families.''
   The federation groups unions in heavy industry around the world.
</TEXT>
