<HEAD>Smith Elected Bell Atlantic CEO To Succeed Bolger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bell Atlantic president and chief operating
officer Raymond W. Smith has been elected president and chief
executive officer to take over when Thomas E. Bolger resigns on
Dec. 31.
   The company announced Tuesday that Bolger will remain chairman
of the board for a transition period into 1989.
   ``The time is right for an orderly transition of leadership, and
Ray Smith is the right person to lead Bell Atlantic to a successful
future,'' Bolger said.
   Philip A. Campbell will continue as vice chairman and chief
financial officer, reporting to Smith. Also reporting to Smith will
be Robert A. Levetown, executive vice president and general counsel.
   Bolger was elected chairman and chief executive officer of Bell
Atlantic in October 1983, when the company was still part of the
Bell System.
   ``Tom Bolger has led Bell Atlantic through the uncertain
currents of divestiture to a position of prominence in the
telecommunications industry,'' Smith said. ``Our challenge now is
to build on the solid foundation he has created.''
   Smith has served as Bell Atlantic's president and chief
operating officer since November 1987.
   Previously, he served as vice chairman and chief financial
officer with responsibilities for Bell Atlantic's financial plans,
external affairs, human resources, strategic direction and
diversification.
   Bell Atlantic serves customers in Pennsylvania, New Jersey,
Delaware, Maryland, West Virginia and Washington, D.C.
