<1ST_LINE>u f PM-CaliforniaS&Ls     08-24 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-California S&Ls,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DP Holdings Gets Approval to Buy Two California Thrifts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   DP Holdings Inc. received federal
regulatory approval Tuesday to acquire two California savings and
loan institutions, including one that is insolvent.
   DP Holdings, based in San Francisco, is an investment group
headed by former Treasury Secretary William Simon and Preston
Martin, the former chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board.
   DP Holdings plans to raise as much as $207.5 million in new
capital to finance the acquisition _ then merger _ of insolvent
Bell Savings and Loan Association of San Mateo, and Western Federal
Savings and Loan Association of Marina del Rey.
   The acquisition will be aided by a federal assistance package
totaling an estimated $565 million. It was the 77th resolution of
an insolvent thrift by the Federal Home Loan Bank Board so far this
year.
   Bell Savings had been in the Bank Board's management consignment
program for three years.
   The Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. will contribute to
the acquisition with an estimated $500 million note and by
purchasing $15 million of preferred stock of DP Holdings.
   The FSLIC also will receive 25 percent of the common stock of DP
Holdings, although its shares will be non-voting.
   The FSLIC will share on an 80 percent-20 percent basis any
losses on certain assets until DP Holdings absorbs $35 million.
Thereafter, the FSLIC will provide 100 percent coverage on those
assets. It also will receive 80 percent of certain gains from the
sale of covered assets.
   With the acquisition, DP Holdings will boost its assets to
nearly $8 billion from the current $3.5 billion.
   Other thrifts owned by DP Holdings include Westcoast Savings and
Loan of Pacific Palisades, Calif.; Honolulu Federal Savings and
Loan; and Southern California Savings and Loan.
</TEXT>
