<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Cigna-HoraceMann     08-24 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cigna-Horace Mann,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cigna To Sell Horace Mann Subsidiary For $500 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees of the Springfield, Ill.-based
Horace Mann Cos. should not have to worry about moving after Cigna
Corp. announced it would sell the insurance subsidiary to a new
corporation for $500 million, officials said.
   The investment banking firm Gibbons, Green, van Amerongen, a
management buyout specialist, arranged and will finance the cash
purchase announced Tuesday.
   Investors in the new corporation will include Paul Kardos,
president and chief executive officer of Horace Mann, as well as
other Horace Mann senior managers and Gibbons, Green, van Amerongen.
   Kardos said the new arrangement would ensure Horace Mann's
remaining a major business in Springfield. Cigna had announced Aug.
3, 1987, that it would sell Horace Mann.
   ``When it was announced that we were on the block ... there was
a lot of speculation and there were a lot of questions being
asked,'' Horace Mann spokesman John O'Shea said.
   Mann employs more than 2,600 people nationwide, about 1,400 of
them in the Springfield area, and speculation centered on whether a
new buyer would move or cut back.
   ``No one could say that would or wouldn't happen'' until
Tuesday's announcement, O'Shea said of such questions. ``There's no
plans for that.''
   The agreement, the 26th management buyout in the 19-year history
of Gibbons, Green, van Amerongen, is subject to regulatory approval
and completion of undisclosed financial arrangements.
   ``The sale of Horace Mann is a further step in an effort to
better focus our strategic emphasis on commercially oriented
insurance and investment products,'' Cigna chairman Robert D.
Kilpatrick said.
   Kardos said Horace Mann has had ``a constructive relationship
with Cigna,'' but said all parties in the deal would benefit.
   ``Horace Mann will have the independence to control its own
destiny and maintain the management philosophy and employee
relations upon which the company has been built,'' Kardos said.
   Horace Mann sells personal life, auto and homeowners insurance,
as well as group and annuity products primarily to the educational
market.
   The company had 1987 revenues of $720 million with assets of
almost $2 billion. Its book value as of June 30 was about $340
million.
</TEXT>
