<DOCNO> AP880824-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1000EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-USTradeBill     08-24 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-US Trade Bill,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC To Defend Itself Against U.S. Trade Bill If Necessary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community
Wednesday reiterated it will defend its international trade rights
if these are damaged by the U.S. trade bill President Ronald Reagan
has signed into law.
   EEC External Relations Commissioner Willy De Clercq said in a
statement the bill confirmed a U.S. tendency ``to interpret
international trading rules unilaterally.''
   ``The Community stands ready to defend its legitimate interests
each time these are threatened by unilateral measures ... by U.S.
authorities on the basis of the trade bill,'' he said.
   De Clercq said he would seek an ``adequate'' EEC response to the
bill when the EEC Foreign Ministers meet here Sept. 26.
   De Clercq said the EEC had trade rights in the General Agreement
on Tariffs and Trade, the international trade organization, and
that it will ``defend them if necessary.''
   President Reagan signed the trade bill into law on Tuesday.
   Among others things, it gives U.S. negotiators more bargaining
room at international trade talks, boosts U.S. ability to fight
restrictive trade policies of other nations and allows the
president to block foreign investments if these are seen to impair
U.S. national security.
   The EEC objects to portions of the bill including a section
raising retaliatory powers in trade and to the extension for two
years of the Export Enhancement Program. The program pays surplus
farm commodities from government bins to exporters to boost
overseas sales. The program has a price tag of $2.5 billion.
   A Commission spokesman said the EEC ``will check, on a
case-by-case basis, to see how the bill is implemented but we first
want a reaction from the member states.''
   He noted that the bill's contents clashed with President
Reagan's strong views on free trade guarantees.
   The president signed the bill and, in a speech, acknowledged
``it could lead to an import fee that would be illegal according to
international law and inconsistent with our goal of moving toward a
free world trade.''
   In his statement, De Clercq said the United States had declared
at the Toronto summit of industrialized nations in June that
``nations must continue to resist protectionism and the temptation
to adopt unilateral measures.''
   The EEC also was party to the declaration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
