<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ThemeParkLayoffs     08-24 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Theme Park Layoffs,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harcourt Brace to Lay Off 750 Theme Park Workers</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The dismissal of 750 workers in six Harcourt
Brace Jovanovich Inc. theme parks around the country is part of a
``belt-tightening'' program by the parent of Sea World and other
facilities, executives said.
   The layoffs announced Tuesday affect about 10 percent of the
park system's 7,500 full-time employees, said Robert Evanson, a
senior vice president and chairman of Harcourt Brace's parks
operation. They include nearly 350 layoffs in Central Florida.
   ``Employee cuts are a routine part of any corporate
belt-tightening. We will be a more efficient company,'' said Dan
LeBlanc, a spokesman for San Diego Sea World in California, which
will lose about 150 employees.
   Orlando-based Harcourt Brace, a major publishing company,
reported a net loss of $62.9 million on revenue of $446.6 million
in the second quarter. The company repelled an unwelcome takeover
bid last year from British publishing magnate Robert Maxwell by
adopting a $3 billion recapitalization plan and plunging into debt
before selling off several assets.
   A total of 334 workers have received layoff notices at company
facilities in Central Florida, including 113 at Sea World, 161 at
Boardwalk and Baseball near Haines City and 60 at Cypress Gardens
in Winter Haven. An additional nine park support workers will be
laid off from corporate headquarters.
   About 215 employees were fired Tuesday at Sea World of Texas in
San Antonio. Harcourt Brace operates another Sea World in
Cleveland, but there was no word on job cuts there.
   The fired workers, ranging in experience from several months to
more than 15 years, will leave no later than Sept. 6.
   Departments involving care of the parks' animals and direct
services to park visitors were largely spared.
   ``The lines aren't going to be any longer at the food stands or
anything like that,'' said LeBlanc. ``Animals will continue to
receive the world-class care that they're used to. Those areas
barely have been touched.''
   Evanson, 51, was appointed to the park system chairmanship
Monday, replacing Jack O. Snyder, who resigned last month amid a
management reorganization.
   Evanson has been with Harcourt Brace since 1985 and previously
served as deputy for publishing. Without being specific, he said
the newer parks in Florida and Texas had the largest cutbacks.
   The company's theme parks employ about 7,500 full-time employees
and bring in seasonal help during the peak summer months to push
the system's work force to 11,000 or 12,000.
   Most of the temporary workers are laid off soon after Labor Day.
All of Tuesday's layoffs involved the permanent work force.
   Despite the layoffs, LeBlanc said Sea World's shows and other
attractions will remain unchanged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
