<2ND_LINE>PM-Detroit Newspapers,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Papers Ask for Union Support in JOA Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Detroit's two major daily newspapers are asking
their six unions to support an attempt to overturn a 30-day stay
blocking implementation of the joint operating agreement.
   The Detroit Free Press and The Detroit News on Tuesday asked the
unions, which originally opposed the partial merger, to sign briefs
asking U.S. District Judge George Revercomb in Washington D.C., to
overturn the decision.
   Revercomb is to hold a hearing Sept. 8.
   The unions represent 80 percent of the 4,200 employees at both
papers. Union officials were mixed on whether they would comply
with the papers' request.
   ``I imagine we're probably going to sign it, unless there's
something in there we really can't agree with,'' said Joel Wilson,
president of Mailers Union Local 2040.
   ``I'm against it, the way that thing is worded,'' said Donald
Kummer, administrative officer of The Newspaper Guild of Detroit.
   Robert Hall, Free Press general manager, said the three-page
brief says the papers are convinced ``that the Free Press is in
probable danger of financial failure.''
   Former U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese III approved a joint
operating agreement between the two newspapers Aug. 8.
   On Aug. 17, U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green issued an order
blocking the partial merger, saying there was a strong likelihood
JOA opponents could have Meese's decision overturned.
   Knight-Ridder Inc., which owns the Free Press, has said it would
close the paper if the JOA is denied. Under the plan, the Free
Press and News would combine some business functions but maintain
separate editorial staffs.
</TEXT>
