<2ND_LINE>BC-Irish Distillers Bid,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Met Buys 4.5 Percent Stake In Irish Distillers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC said Wednesday it purchased
a 4.5 percent stake in Irish Distillers Group PLC as part of a
hostile attempt to acquire Ireland's largest distiller.
   Working through the subsidiary GC&C Brands Ltd., Grand Met
offered 253 million Irish punts, or about $354 million for Irish
Distillers late last week, but Irish Distillers' board rejected the
offer on Monday.
   The new bid, made following GC&C's restructuring last week as a
wholly owned subsidiary of Grand Met, replaces a $278 million offer
made by GC&C in May. GC&C originally was controlled by a
three-party consortium, which also included Guinness PLC and
Allied-Lyons PLC.
   The original offer attracted only 20.34 percent of Irish
Distillers' shares before protests by the European Commission
forced the consortium to disband.
   EC officials said the consortium had decided in advance to split
up Irish Distillers' markets and brands, which would violate the
Community's competition law.
   Irish Distillers makes Jameson's and other whiskeys.
</TEXT>
