<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in a technical reversal of
Tuesday's mostly lower pattern, analysts said.
   Soybeans led the advance after two days of sharp declines that
saw the contract for September delivery of soybeans plunge a total
of 64 cents to $8.07 a bushel, a 12-week low.
   ``There's a little bargain hunting down here,'' said Joel
Karlin, a research analyst for Chicago-based Research Department
Inc. ``A lot of people are saying the 64-cent fall was overdone.''
   The weather outlook also was supportive for the soybean market,
with some meterologists taking showers out of their weekend
forecasts for the drought-striken Midwest, Karlin said.
   News of corn sales to Taiwan and South Korea gave the corn
market an additional boost, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 2{ cents lower to 3 cents higher
with the contract for delivery in September at $3.87 a bushel; corn
was 2\ cents to 4{ cents higher with September at $2.77{ a bushel;
oats were 3 cents to 6{ cents higher with September at $2.53{ a
bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 6{ cents higher with September at
$8.11{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent lower with October at
70.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .23 cent
higher with August at 81.65 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower
to .12 cent higher with October at 40.32 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .55 cent lower to 1.20 cents higher with August at
37.40 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
