<HEAD>Pan Am Says Pension Payment Could Drain Resources</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $73 million pension payment due next month from
Pan Am Corp. could leave the ailing airline with limited financial
resources to offset the slow fall and winter travel seasons,
according to government documents.
   Pan Am outlined the problem in documents filed recently with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, The Miami Herald reported in
Wednesday's editions.
   New York-based Pan Am is seeking an Internal Revenue Service
extension for its annual pension contribution due Sept. 15. The
airline also owes an additional $46.1 million from last year's
pension debt.
   Pan Am spokesman Jeffrey Kriendler told the Herald that the
airline may be forced to sell some assets or obtain wage reduction
agreements from some of its unions in order to offset the payment.
   Members of the largest union at Pan Am, the Transport Workers,
recently rejected a wage freeze agreement that would have saved the
company an estimated $81 million over three years.
   Pan Am had a net loss of $265.3 million last year. Its chairman,
Thomas Plaskett, recently said the airline might sell its Latin
American routes if labor concessions aren't made.
