<2ND_LINE>PM-Tootsie Roll-Charms,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Sweet Deal For Tootsie Roll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tootsie Roll Industries Inc., bidding for a
bigger chunk of the nation's sweet tooth, has announced it is
acquiring one of its competitors, Charms Co. for $65 million in
cash.
   Charms, based in Colts Neck, N.J., manufactures Charms
square-shaped roll candy, Charms hard-candy lolipops and Blo-Pops
candy pops with bubble-gum centers. The company had 1987 sales of
$38 million and pre-tax income of about $3 million, Tootsie Roll
said in a statement.
   ``In the last five or six years, their business has doubled,''
Melvin Gordon, Tootsie Roll's chief executive, said Tuesday. ``The
Blo-Pop is a good, growing segment.''
   The acquisition reflects a ``major commitment'' by Tootsie Roll
to expand its presence in the $7.5 billion-a-year U.S. candy
market, said Ellen Gordon, president of the Chicago-based company.
   Tootsie Roll, maker of Tootsie Rolls, Tootsie Pops, Mason Dots
and Cella's chocolate-covered cherry candies, had 1987 sales of
$115 million and net income of $14.6 million, a 14 percent increase
over its 1986 net income.
   Charms has approved Tootsie Roll's tender offer and its plan to
create a Charms subsidiary, which will remain in New Jersey, Mrs.
Gordon said. The transaction should be completed by Sept. 30, she
said.
</TEXT>
