<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0496</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rallied this morning, moving
higher early in the session and then managing to hold on to most of
the early gains.
   Trading continued at a sluggish pace.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which slipped 0.89 on
Tuesday and fell nearly 38 points in the past three sessions, was
up 13.16 at 2,002.49 at noontime. It had been up nearly 17 points
earlier in the day.
   Advancing issues outpaced losers by a margin of 2 to 1 among
issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 803 up, 390 down
and 565 unchanged.
   Big Board volume amounted to 59.85 million shares as of noon on
Wall Street compared with 62.63 million shares at the same point on
Tuesday.
   The market has been trending lower this month, and some analysts
said it was due for a rebound.
   Jack Solomon, an analyst for Bear Stearns & Co., said the rise
appeared to reflect a technical reaction to ``the excesssive doom
and gloom'' that has weighed down stock prices for the past few
weeks.
   ``It is a release from excessively consistent selling
pressure,'' he said.
   But Robert O'Toole, manager of over-the-counter trading at
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., noted, ``Nobody is rushing in to buy.''
   He said some of the buying was by traders who had previously
agreed to sell borrowed stocks in expectation that prices were
going lower.
   Investors have generally shown little inclination to buy stocks
because they are fearful that the recent pace of economic expansion
is strong enough that inflation and interest rates are likely to
pick up.
   On Tuesday, the government reported that consumer prices were up
modestly in July while orders for durable goods tumbled.
   But while the reports sparked a mild rally in bond prices,
stocks failed to follow through. Prices in the bond market were
little changed today.
   Bear Stearns' Solomon said today's stock rally may partly
reflect a delayed reaction to bond price rise over the past few
days, however.
   He said a government report this morning that the nation's trade
deficit narrowed in the second quarter to $29.9 billion from an
imbalance of $35.2 billion in the first three months of the year
also helped the rally.
   Among actively-traded issues on the NYSE, Wickes was down \ at
12~, American Express was off \ at 28] and International Business
Machines was up | at 111{.
   Deere was up 1[ to 43}. On Tuesday, it reported its profit
tripled in the latest quarter.
   Some airline issues were higher. UAL, parent of United Airlines,
was up 1\ at 89, while AMR Corp. rose } to 42| and Delta Airlines
was up { at 46{.
   The NYSE index was up 0.74 at 146.68. At the American Stock
Exchange, the composite index was up 0.98 at 292.98.
