<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     08-24 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Pound End Lower In Choppy European Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar finished lower against most major
foreign currencies in thin, choppy European trading Wednesday,
pushed down by central bank intervention.
   Gold prices rose.
   Currency dealers said the dollar was pushed down by several
spurts of intervention from the central banks of West Germany,
Switzerland and Belgium, but it found strong buying interest at
about 1.8885 West German marks.
   The intervention involved the central banks of fewer countries
than on previous days, dealers said. But they said the central
banks that did intervene made it clear that they didn't want the
dollar above 1.90 marks.
   The pound also slumped, on fears of a deterioration in Britain's
trade deficit.
   In London, the pound fell to $1.6788 from $1.6795 late Tuesday.
It slumped to 3.18 marks from 3.20 marks.
   Dealers say they were increasingly worried that Thursday's
release of British trade figures would show a widening from June's
1 billion-pound, or $1.68 billion, deficit.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.8915 West German marks, down from 1.9060; 1.5950 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6055; 6.4250 French francs, down from 6.4635; 2.1370
Dutch guilders, down from 2.1440; 1,403.50 Italian lire, down from
1,407.50; and 1.2321 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2303.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.37 yen to a closing 134.30 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 134.25 yen.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $433.90 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $432.75. In Zurich, gold closed at a
bid $433.50 an ounce, compared with $433 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 59 cents to close at a bid $434
an ounce.
   Silver bullion prices rose in London to a late bid price of
$6.81 a troy ounce, compared with Tuesday's $6.74.
</TEXT>
