<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1405EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Asia-USTrade     08-24 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Asia-US Trade,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan, South Korea Express Regrets Over U.S. Trade Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan and South Korea expressed regrets Wednesday
over the U.S. trade bill that was signed Tuesday by President
Reagan, saying it has protectionist provisions.
   Reagan called the trade bill a step toward opening worldwide
markets to American products, but expressed displeasure with some
of the provisions.
   In Tokyo, Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said he regretted the
trade bill but hopes the U.S. government will implement the law
``in a manner to curb trade protectionism.'' He said previously
that he would ask Reagan to veto the package when the U.S. Congress
passed it earlier this month.
   Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno said Japan will promote the Uruguay
Round of trade talks in order to curb protectionist pressures in
the United States.
   Some of the nations that say the bill is protectionist are
themselves accused of being protectionist by the United States.
   Among other measures, the bill transfers authority from the
president to the trade representative to decide on measures to be
taken against what the United States considers unfair trade
practices.
   In South Korea, a Foreign Ministry statement accused the U.S.
trade bill of having ``all the protectionist elements which aroused
so much concern and protest from Korea and many other trading
nations.''
   ``We are particularly concerned with the likely
counter-reactions from U.S. trading partners,'' the statement said,
adding the legislation would encourage enactment of similar laws or
retaliation.
   The South Korean Foreign Ministry urged the U.S. administration
to ensure ``the law be implemented in such a way as not to
adversely affect the smooth growth of the Korea-U.S. trade
relationship.''
   The signing Tuesday climaxed months of negotiations between the
Reagan administration and Congress. Reagan vetoed a previous
measure because it contained a provision requiring a 60-day notice
to employees of plant closings and layoffs. Congress passed the
advance-notice provision as a separate bill, and it became law.
   The United States' record $171 billion trade deficit in 1987 was
a key reason behind congressional action to try to improve the U.S.
standing in the global marketplace.
   Of the overall U.S. trade deficit last year, up from $156.2
billion in 1986, the shortfall with Japan was again the largest at
a record $59.8 billion, up from $58.6 billion in 1986 and $49.7
billion in 1985.
   The deficit with Taiwan was $19.0 billion, up from $7.1 billion
in 1986, and the shortfall with South Korea was $9.9 billion, up
from $7.1 billion in 1986.
   Japanese International Trade and Industry Minister Hajime Tamura
said, ``I urge the U.S. government, in enforcing this law, to
maintain its policy of protecting free trade and never to give way
to the pressure of protectionists.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
