<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1426EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PosnerSentence     08-24 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Posner Sentence,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Prosecution Challenge to Posner's Probation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MILT SOSIN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Wednesday rejected a prosecution
complaint that probation for millionaire and convicted tax evader
Victor Posner gives the impression that the rich can buy their
freedom while the poor go to prison.
   Posner pleaded no contest in February to overvaluing land he
donated to a college. He received five years probation and a fine
of $4 million after agreeing to donate an additional $3 million to
a program for South Florida's homeless.
   Then-U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner challenged the sentence in
April, arguing that it would ``only emphasize that the rich can
trade money for liberty while the poor cannot.''
   But in a ruling released Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Eugene
P. Spellman, who had sentenced Posner, rejected the prosecution's
arguments. He emphasized that under the probation requirement, the
industrialist must devote 20 hours a week to the homeless project.
   ``Posner may have avoided prison, but his service obligations
will be so personally demanding and time-consuming that he is by no
stretch of the imagination a `free man,''' the judge wrote.
   In 1985 Posner, who runs a 40-company empire valued at $4
billion, was rated the nation's highest-paid executive with an
annual salary of $12.7 million. The judge said he conservatively
calculated that Posner's time was worth $3,200 an hour.
   ``As one of the highest-paid individuals in the United States,
this time commitment alone over five years is worth more than $16
million,'' Spellman wrote.
   ``There is no plausible punishment more reasonably related to
Posner and his crime than to have him roll up his sleeves and
dedicate a substantial part of his life to furthering a vital
charitable cause,'' said the judge.
   The prosecution had specifically attacked the requirement that
Posner donate $3 million to the homeless project, saying that
portion of the sentence was illegal.
   But Spellman noted that Posner had agreed to the donation no
matter what decision was made on the prosecution challenge, and
called the issue moot.
   In recent months Posner has been discussing plans for the
homeless project with a court-approved committee that will oversee
the effort. He has said he envisions a pilot project aimed at
providing homes, perhaps taking advantage of federal subsidies.
   Posner was convicted on 10 tax fraud counts for inflating the
value of land donated to Miami Christian College when writing the
charitable gift off on his income tax return.
   With the time he must spend on the homeless project, Spellman
noted, ``charity will no longer merely mean a tax writeoff to
Victor Posner.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
