<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ConferenceBoard     08-24 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Conference Board,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minnesota Business Dean Named President Of Conference Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Preston Townley, 49-year-old dean of the
University of Minnesota's business school, has been selected
president and chief executive of the Conference Board, the research
organization said Wednesday.
   Townley is a noted fund-raiser who led a $40 million campaign at
Minnesota and is president of the Harvard Alumni Association for
the 1988-89 term.
   In an interview, Townley said his goal is to make sure the
Conference Board's activities mesh with the desires of the senior
executives who make up its board of trustees.
   Townley has been dean of Minnesota's Carlson School of
Management since 1984. He helped secure a $25 million gift from
entrepreneur Curtis Carlson to the university, $18 million of which
went to the business school. In turn, the school was named after
Carlson.
   From 1964 to 1983, Townley held a variety of jobs at General
Mills Inc., headquartered in Minneapolis. He has also been active
in raising money for the arts, community organizations and the
Democratic party.
   Townley is to be formally elected by the Conference Board
trustees Sept. 22. He will succeed James T. Mills, who will be 65
in November and has served nearly seven years as president and
chief executive.
   The Conference Board, founded in 1916, is a non-profit,
business-supported research group with a staff of more than 350 in
the United States, Canada and Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
