<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Brazil-Loan     08-24 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Loan,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazil Gets $1.41 Billion Loan from IMF</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Monetary Fund on Wednesday
offered Brazil $1.41 billion in new credits to add to the $120.2
billion the nation is expected to owe at the end of the year.
   U.S. banks hold about $20 billion of Brazil's debt, which is the
biggest in the Third World. The U.S. government holds the biggest
block of shares in the international fund, to which Brazil already
owes $3.08 billion. The fund is owned by 151 countries.
   The government of Brazilian President Jose Sarney, hard hit by
inflation, may draw installments of the fund's ``standby
arrangement'' _ as the new loan is called _ through Feb. 28, 1990.
Under the fund's usual practice, reviews are held after each
installment to decide if the borrower has been performing as agreed
and whether the next installment can be drawn.
   The fund's credits go along with $5.2 billion being offered to
Brazil by banks worldwide to which it already owes about $68
billion. Brazil has 700 creditor banks, which have pledged 95
percent of the additional loans promised. Disbursal of such loans
is often withheld if the fund's disbursements are stopped.
   Interest on old debt already costs Brazil $10.2 billion to $10.4
billion a year. Much of the interest owed to banks was not paid
last year, but some payments have now resumed. The principal has
not been reduced in recent years, as is generally the case with
Third World debt, which is expected to reach a total of more than
$1.2 trillion by the end of the year.
   The fund said Brazil has pledged to cut the government's deficit
in 1988 to 4 percent of the country's gross national product and to
cut it again in 1989. The deficit amounted to 5.5 percent of GNP in
1987. The World Bank calculates that Brazil's total production in
1986 was worth about $250 billion, or $1,810 for each citizen.
   Brazil is promising to cut inflation, according to the fund's
announcement. Figures from Brazil say inflation reached a record
24.04 percent for the month of July and may run close to 1,000
percent for the year. By the fund's calculations, consumer prices
have been rising at an annual rate of about 500 percent in the
first four months of the year.
   The Brazilian government's program, as outlined by the fund,
aims to shrink differences of income among its people, to increase
savings, improve the country's surplus in world trade, reduce
barriers to imports, increase efficiency, reduce government
regulation, privatize state-owned industry and reform the financial
system.
   ``These reforms are expected to ... contribute to foster overall
economic growth,'' the fund said.
   Despite its economic problems Brazil already has one of the best
records for growth in the Western Hemisphere: 4.3 percent annually
for each citizen over the years 1965 to 1986, according to the
World Bank. Growth in the United States as only 1.6 percent over
the same period, but Americans earn almost $10 for every dollar the
average Brazilian makes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
