<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-24 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Sharply Higher; Freeze Fears Cited</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The corn market led grain and soybean futures to
a sharply higher close Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade
partly on fears of a freeze this weekend in the Midwest.
   Analysts were skeptical of the frost talk, which helped drive
corn futures prices up the permitted daily limit of 10 cents a
bushel.
   ``I find it hard to believe with all the hot weather we've
had,'' said Jerry Gidel, an analyst with G.H. Miller & Co., a
Chicago-based division of the British-owned trading company LIT
America Inc.
   He called the freeze talk ``crazy'' but acknowledged that some
meteorologists have predicted an early frost, which would do
further damage to corn and soybeans already damaged by the
summer-long drought.
   Crop futures also advanced on perceptions that rain was slowing
the wheat harvest in the Soviet Union, possibly reducing the amount
of wheat that will be harvested there, Gidel said.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 7{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.91 a bushel; corn was 3}
cents to 10 cents higher with September at $2.83} a bushel; oats
were 5 cents to 6{ cents higher with September at $2.53{ a bushel;
soybeans were 16 cents to 26{ cents higher with September at $8.31
a bushel.
</TEXT>
