<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     08-24 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0201</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A late-afternoon surge helped the stock market
post a big gain today, as stocks regained some ground lost over the
past three sessions.
   Trading remained relatively slow, however.
   The market has fallen fairly steadily this month, and some
analysts said it was due for a rebound.
   Jack Solomon, an analyst for Bear Stearns & Co., said the rise
appeared to reflect a technical reaction to ``the excesssive doom
and gloom'' that has weighed down stock prices for the past few
weeks.
   Robert O'Toole, manager of over-the-counter trading at Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc., said he detected no rush by big investors to
buy stocks.
   He said some of the rise could be attributed to buying by
traders who had previously agreed to sell borrowed stocks,
expecting prices were going lower.
   Solomon said a new government report that the nation's trade
deficit narrowed in the second quarter to $29.9 billion from $35.2
billion in the first three months of the year may have encouraged
some stock buying by taking some pressure off the Federal Reserve
to push interest rates higher.
</TEXT>
