<1ST_LINE>u f BC-AshlandSuit 1stLd-Writethru f0094 08-24 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ashland Suit, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0094,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ashland, Former Executives Settle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with four grafs to UPDATE with Ashland taking
fourth-quarter charge against earnings</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland Oil Inc. said Wednesday it would
take an after-tax charge of about $25 million in its fiscal fourth
quarter to cover the cost of settling a lawsuit brought by two
former executives.
   Company spokesman Roger Schrum said the charge against earnings
would amount to about 22 cents per share in the three months ended
Sept. 30.
   The announcement came after Ashland reached a settlement in
principle to pay $25 million to the former executives who claimed
they were fired for refusing to offer or cover up bribes to foreign
officials.
   U.S. District Judge William O. Bertelsman, who announced the
arrangement Tuesday in the four-year legal battle, said he had
picked the figure and applied ``constructive pressures'' on each
side to accept it.
   An eight-week jury trial of the case in Covington ended June 10
with a $69.5 million decision again Ashland, the biggest ever
verdict in Kentucky. Ashland later sought a new trial or a
different judgment.
   The jury award included damages for lost past and future wages
of $14.4 million for former vice president Bill McKay and $7.7
million for former vice president Harry Williams.
   Those amounts were tripled because of a finding that Ashland
violated the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act by
engaging in a pattern of illegal interstate activity to obtain oil
in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
   In addition, Ashland Chairman John R. Hall, Senior Vice
President Richard Spears and the company were assessed a total of
$3 million in punitive damages for their treatment of the two men.
</TEXT>
