<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1714EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-24 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Sinks; Gold Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar sank Wednesday with a slight push
from a few central banks after having resisted concerted official
efforts to lower it in previous sessions.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York said gold
was bid at $434.60 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $431.85
an ounce late Tuesday.
   Traders said the market was influenced by an article in
Wednesday's editions of the New York Times that quoted an unnamed
senior U.S. official as saying the Reagan administration believes a
further rise of the dollar could be troublesome.
   Also, Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita reportedly said the
dollar's recent rise against the West German mark was
``inexplicable.''
   Further undermining the dollar was a sale of hundreds of
millions of British pounds for West German marks, said Jerry Egan,
a senior trader for the Bank of Boston. He said the trade was done
by selling sterling for dollars and then selling dollars for marks.
The result was to lower the dollar against the mark, starting a
slide.
   The dollar's fall was fairly steady. Most times when the dollar
is falling it stages periodic rallies, or bounces, but Wednesday
``it was bouncing like a dead cat,'' Egan said.
   Currency dealers in Europe said there were spurts of
intervention by the central banks of West Germany, Switzerland and
Belgium.
   In London, the pound fell to $1.6788 from $1.6795 late Tuesday,
influenced by fears that Britain would report a bigger trade
deficit Thursday. But later in New York it rose to $1.6869 from
$1.6740 late Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.37 yen to a closing 134.30 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 134.25 yen. Later in New York, the dollar fell to
133.83 yen from 134.11 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday:
1.8820 West German marks, down from 1.9128; 1.5855 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6102; 1.2339 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2308; 6.3960
French francs, down from 6.4895; and 1,396.50 Italian lire, down
from 1,415.75.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday: 1.8915
West German marks, down from 1.9060; 1.5950 Swiss francs, down from
1.6055; 6.4250 French francs, down from 6.4635; 2.1370 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.1440; 1,403.50 Italian lire, down from
1,407.50; and 1.2321 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2303.
   Gold prices rose late in the trading day in reaction to the
weakness of gold. Gold's dollar price becomes cheaper for foreign
investors when the dollar's exchange rate falls.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell 59 cents a troy ounce to close at a bid
$434 an ounce.
   Later, gold rose in London to a late bid price of $433.90 a troy
ounce, compared with late Tuesday's $432.75. In Zurich, gold closed
at a bid $433.50 an ounce, compared with $433 late Tuesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $434.90 a troy ounce from $432.20 late Tuesday.
   Silver bullion prices rose in London to a late bid price of
$6.81 a troy ounce, compared with Tuesday's $6.74. On New York's
Comex, silver bullion for current delivery rose to $6.782 a troy
ounce from $6.730 late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
