<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2236EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AluminumTalks     08-24 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aluminum Talks,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early Contract Talks End In Disagreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The aluminum industry's bid for early labor
contract settlements failed Wednesday in Cincinnati, where
bargaining ended in disagreement over economic issues.
   Pittsburgh-based Aluminum Co. of America, the industry leader,
and Reynolds Metals Co. of Richmond, Va., opened talks Aug. 9 with
the United Steelworkers of America and the Aluminum, Brick and
Glass Workers.
   About 21,000 members of the two unions will continue working
under two-year contracts that don't expire until May 1989. Since
the two sides reached an impasse in the early talks they planned to
reopen the bargaining nearer the expiration date.
   ``The problem was that what they came up with on profit sharing
was very inadequate,'' said USW spokesman Charles Robb in
Pittsburgh.
   Alcoa offered to give union members a share of only those
profits that exceeded 6 percent of the value of its U.S. assets,
and Reynolds offered a share of those profits exceeding 10 percent
of shareholders' equity, he said.
   Under those proposals, ``In 1987, Reynolds' biggest profit year,
they would have shared slightly more than $600 per worker, and
Alcoa would have shared nothing,'' Robb said.
   Combined with other provisions, the companies' offers would have
represented hourly wage increases projected at 37 cents, he said.
   ``Our members gave up about 95 cents an hour in the current
contract,'' Robb said. ``Certainly we want our members to recoup
what they had given up since the companies are tremendously
profitable.''
   ``We offered both unions a four-year agreement featuring a
profit-sharing plan, an immediate insurance option and increased
pension benefits,'' said Alcoa Chairman Paul O'Neill.
   Alcoa reported 1987 profits of $200 million on sales of $7.77
billion and 1988 first-half profits of $416.3 million on sales of
$4.59 billion.
   Reynolds reported 1987 net earnings of $219.5 million on sales
of $4.32 billion and 1988 first-half profits of $204.9 million on
sales of $2.65 billion.
   The Pittsburgh-based USW represents about 4,000 Reynolds
employees at 21 locations in the United States and Canada and about
6,000 Alcoa employees at nine locations in the United States. The
ABGW represents about 4,000 Reynolds workers and about 7,000 Alcoa
workers.
   The two unions negotiate side-by-side on separate contracts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880824-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 1758EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   08-24 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Year's Incentives Color This Year's Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's automakers Wednesday reported a 13.2
percent dip in their mid-August sales of cars and trucks, but
analysts attributed much of the drop to the curtailment of buyer
incentives.
   ``Incentives were just coming in last year and there are no new
incentive programs right now,'' said analyst David Healy of the
investment firm Drexel Brunham Lambert Inc. in New York. ``So
Americans are buying the things.''
   The latest sales report, covering the Aug. 11-20 period, is
compared with daily sales from the same period a year ago.
   General Motors Corp.'s share of the U.S. market slipped during
the period to 46.4 percent, down from 54.3 percent during the same
period last year.
   Meantime, Ford Motor Co. boosted its share from 28.6 percent to
31.6 percent, and Chrysler Corp. increased its piece of the
industry's pie from 11.2 percent during mid-August 1987 to 13.6
percent during the same period this year.
   ``Chrysler and Ford seem to be eating GM's lunch,'' Healy said.
   Overall, car makers in the United States reported selling
298,580 cars and trucks during the nine selling days of this year,
compared with 343,845 vehicles bought during the same period last
year, when there also were nine selling days.
   For the month so far, car and truck sales were off 10 percent,
from 607,125 in 1987 to 578,643 this year. Domestic and foreign
automakers report sales for all of August in early September.
   Car makers offered some of their most attractive incentives last
year. But this year, as inventories have shrunk, automakers have
been less likely to offer special incentive plans.
   The car makers reported that for the year, sales of U.S.-made
cars and trucks are up 8 percent, from 7,092,789 last year to
7,699,649.
   Each of the Big Three reported dips in car sales during
mid-August, compared with the same period last year.
   General Motors Corp. said it sold 88,394 cars this year, down
30.3 percent from 126,887 during the incentive-bloated period last
year. Ford Motor Co. reported a 10 percent drop in sales to 60,184
from 66,907 a year earlier.
   Chrysler Motor Co. showed the smallest decrease, dropping 0.8
percent from 26,200 cars in mid-August 1987 to 25,985 during the
period this year.
   Meantime, Honda North America Inc. said it sold 9,259 cars
during mid-August of this year compared with 7,563 cars in the same
period last year _ a 22.4 percent increase.
   Nissan Motor Corp. USA's sales fell 4.5 percent during the
period from 4,380 cars in mid-August 1987 to 4,182 in the same
period this year. Toyota Motor Sales USA Inc. reported sales of
1,429 cars during the period this year compared with 1,188 last
year, an increase of 20.3 percent.
