<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EconomyRdp     08-24 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy Rdp,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quarterly Trade Deficit Shrinks, Stocks Up, Auto Sales Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   America's bulging trade deficit shrank 15 percent in the
April-June quarter, the government said Wednesday in a report that
strengthened Republican campaign claims of economic achievement but
didn't impress financial markets.
   Although the Commerce Department figures showed the biggest
quarterly improvement in more than five years, the dollar fell and
bonds weakened. The stock market rallied, but trading was light and
brokers attributed the gain to internal market influences that had
little to do with the general economy.
   The Commerce Department said the difference between what America
spends and sells abroad narrowed to a deficit of $29.9 billion in
the second quarter, compared with a deficit of $35.2 billion in the
first three months of 1988.
   Many economists regard the trade deficit as one of the most
visible weaknesses in the economy, reflecting a relentless
addiction to cheap imports and consequent difficulty for domestic
companies trying to compete. Democrats have attempted to make the
trade deficit an issue in the presidential campaign.
   But the improvement reported Wednesday suggested that U.S.
manufacturers are making strong gains in selling abroad. Some
economists are predicting the trade deficit will drop by close to
25 percent for the year as a whole, marking the first annual
improvement since President Reagan took office.
   Republicans are hoping voters will focus on the improvement,
which has already shown up in the Commerce Department's monthly
merchandise trade reports.
   But on Wall Street, the trade news was largely disregarded and
the volume of trading remained low. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrial stocks, which had lost nearly 38 points over the
previous three sessions, climbed 37.34 to close at 2,026.67 in what
brokers described as a technical recovery.
   In foreign-exchange trading the dollar, which ordinarily would
be expected to rally on improved U.S. trade figures, fell with a
slight push from selling by a few central banks concerned about its
recent rise.
   Traders said the currency market was influenced by an article in
Wednesday's editions of the New York Times that quoted an
unidentified senior U.S. official as saying the Reagan
administration believes a further rise of the dollar could be
troublesome.
   The dollar's decline was partly responsible for a poor showing
in the bond market, where traders are sensitive to changes in the
value of the U.S. currency because it directly affects the demand
for U.S. bonds by foreigners.
   The Treasury's key 30-year bond fell about $2.50 per $1,000 in
face amount and its yield, which moves inversely to price, rose to
9.39 percent from 9.37 percent late Tuesday.
   In other economic news, major automakers said mid-August sales
of U.S.-made cars and trucks fell by 13.2 percent from the same
period a year earlier, when sales were inflated by buyers taking
advantage of dealer incentives.
   Companies making cars in the United States reported selling
298,580 cars and trucks during the Aug. 11-20 period this year,
compared with 343,845 vehicles during the same period last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
