<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ComputerWhiz     08-24 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Whiz,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fallen Computer Whiz Pleads Innocent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS New 5th graf, Defense attorney ..., to UPDATE with
comments from defense attorney. Deletes outdated 13th graf pvs,
Defense attorney ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young computer whiz pleaded innocent
Wednesday to 11 counts of felony larceny stemming from an alleged
scheme to bilk six investors out of more than $500,000 to keep his
business operating.
   Tex Zachary Hildreth, 24, faces a maximum penalty of five years
in prison or a $25,000 fine and two years in jail on each charge if
convicted. He was ordered held in lieu of $100,000 bail at the
local jail.
   Hildreth, who fled to New Hampshire and attempted suicide with
his mother after authorities and creditors moved in on his software
firm Massdata Corp., had been free on $1,000 bail during a
two-month-long grand jury investigation.
   Norfolk County Superior Court Judge Andrew Gill Meyer approved
the prosecution's recommendation that bail for Hildreth be
increased because more indictments are expected in the case.
   Defense attorney Gregory Sullivan said he would ask during a
bail review hearing Thursday that Hildreth be allowed to post
$5,000 to $10,000 cash bail, which would be returned when he
appeared for trial, instead of paying a surety bond as requested,
which would not be returned.
   Mike McGorty, spokesman for the Norfolk County district
attorney's office, said Assistant District Attorney Dennis Mahoney
told the judge that Hildreth orchestrated ``a scheme of grand
proportion'' to get people to invest in his company.
   Mahoney, head of the county's white collar crime unit, told the
court Hildreth obtained loans by telling investors of a phantom
family trust that he would use to pay back their inestments.
   Hildreth told investors he would soon be eligible for funds from
the trust left to him when his father died, he said. But
investigators determined that Hildreth's father is still alive and
that the trust never amounted to more than $30,000.
   As Massdata slid into the red, Hildreth also allegedly used
falsified documents to obtain bank loans.
   ``As part of the investigation, we determined that certain banks
made loans based on papers presented by Mr. Hildreth and the
documents were allegedly fictitious or forgeries,'' McGorty said.
   ``This could stretch well beyond a million dollars,'' McGorty
said.
   The grand jury is also looking into a $400,000 loan to Hildreth
from the Rockland Trust Co.
   ``It appears that some of this money was being solicited to pay
off other investors and also some bank notes,'' McGorty said.
   After Hildreth and his mother, Rose, 50, fled Massachusetts with
creditors close behind, they were recaptured when an employee at
the Manchester, N.H., Holiday Inn reported a bloodied man wandering
about the lobby.
   Police found Hildreth, who apparently had slashed his wrists.
His mother and a bottle of non-prescription pills were found in
their hotel room along with what appeared to be suicide notes,
police said.
   Hildreth bought his first computer at the age of 16 and, with
the help of a mentor, rented office space to start his own software
firm at the age of 20.
   He quickly surrounded himself with symbols of success, including
a $220,000 Weymouth condominium, a $32,000 BMW, and a 50-inch,
$4,000 color TV.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
