<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MCCA-BellSouth     08-24 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MCCA-BellSouth,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MCCA Shareholders Approve Merger with BellSouth Corp.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stockholders of Mobile Communications
Corp. of America approved Wednesday the $676 million merger of the
Jackson-based company's local paging and cellular telephone
operations into BellSouth Corp., MCCA officials announced.
   The merger agreement provides that other MCCA operations _
including nationwide paging, air-to-ground and marine
communications and telephone answering services _ will be spun off
into a new publicly held company, according to a news release
issued by MCCA. The as yet unnamed new company also will be based
in Jackson.
   BellSouth reported revenues of $12.27 billion in 1987, up 7.2
percent from 1986. The latest figures for MCCA show revenues of
$93.6 million for 1987, up from $70.8 million for 1986.
   The merger and spin-off will become effective as soon as federal
and state regulatory and judicial approvals have been received.
MCCA Chairman John N. Palmer, who will be chairman of the new
spinoff company, said he expected all required federal and state
approvals to be received by late in the fourth quarter of 1988.
   MCCA shareholders will receive the equivalent of $28.75 in
BellSouth stock and one share in the new spinoff company for each
share of Class A or Class B MCCA stock held, he said. Since there
are about 23.5 million shares outstanding, the value of the
BellSouth stock is about $676 million.
   The new company's primary operating subsidy will be National
Satellite Paging, a nationwide paging and voice mail system
headquartered in Washington, D.C.
   MCCA provides personal mobile communications services in 100
cities and 34 states and the District of Columbia.
</TEXT>
