<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CM&WBailout     08-24 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CM&W Bailout,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Approves $14 Million State Bailout for CM&W Railroad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge approved Wednesday a
$14 million state bailout of the Chicago, Missouri & Western
Railway.
   Citicorp and Heller Financial Inc., which are owed more than
$100 million by the railroad, had opposed the rescue plan and
sought to have the railroad shut down and its assets sold.
   But U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge John Schwartz said in a written
decision that the public interest required the railroad to continue
to operate while its court-appointed trustee, Daniel R. Murray,
works out a reorganization plan.
   ``The history of this railroad, the lenders' relationship to it,
as well as the history of this case, demand this opportunity be
given to the trustee if the public interest is not to be damned,''
Schwartz concluded.
   A spokeswoman for Illinois Gov. James R. Thompson, who put
together the rescue package of grants and loans, applauded the
decision to keep the CM&W running.
   The creditors' attorney, Neal Wolf, was out of his office and
not immediately available for comment.
   The railroad operates freight service over its entire 632-mile
line between Kansas City, Mo., and Joliet, with trackage rights
extending the final 40 miles to Chicago.
   The 157-mile Amtrak route between Joliet and Springfield is used
by 300,000 people annually, according to Thompson's office.
   The creditors had argued that even under the best of
circumstances, the railroad's earnings would not come close to
paying even the interest on the loans.
   CM&W filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of
federal bankruptcy laws on April 1, listing debts of $131.8 million
and assets of $103.5 million.
   On July 29, Schwartz allowed CM&W to accept $1 million of the
proposed bailout to keep the railroad rolling through the
completion of bankruptcy proceedings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
