<1ST_LINE>u f AM-DroughtHay 1stLd-Writethru f0217 08-24 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Hay, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0217,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Stricken Iowa Farmers Begin Cutting Hay in Idaho</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with plans to cut hay Thursday,
CORRECT number of farmers to 64 sted 65. Picks up 8th graf pvs `The
harvest...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Offers of food, lodging, money and
equipment continued to pour in Wednesday for a group of Iowa
farmers who have come to Idaho to cut free hay for their
drought-starved livestock.
   Meanwhile, organizers of the hay harvest said they've received
calls from farmers and farmer groups in North Dakota, Minnesota and
Iowa asking whether there was enough hay to feed their livestock as
well.
   ``When we put out the notice, we didn't realize we were going to
get such a tremendous response,'' said Mike Tracy, director of
information for the Idaho Farm Bureau. ``It's turned into a
monumental task.''
   Organizers of the hay harvest had worried there wouldn't be
enough machinery to keep the Iowans busy, but offers of equipment
began pouring into the Farm Bureau office here Tuesday after a Farm
Bureau official appealed on television for donations.
   Tracy said the 64 Iowans would begin cutting hay on Thursday.
   The tired contingent Iowans arrived late Tuesday in two
Greyhound buses donated by the transportation company for the
1,600-mile trip west.
   The men, women and teen-agers stayed overnight in rooms donated
by three motels while Farm Bureau and National Farmers Organization
officials scouted about 4,500 acres of hay on pasture land placed
in the government's Conservation Reserve Program.
   ``They really like what they're seeing,'' Tracy said. ``They're
real pleased with the quality.''
   The harvest could provide as much as 5,000 tons of hay. As of
the first of this week, 76 percent of the hay crop in Iowa was
considered in poor condition by the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
   The Iowans, who plan to harvest, bail and ship for about 10
days, faced an Aug. 31 deadline to be off the reserve lands, which
are under the control of the USDA.
   ``A lot of us guys are just plain out of hay,'' said Don
Tibbals, an Albia, Iowa, dairy farmer. ``The USDA finally realized
that and released the conservation reserve program lands.''
   ``A lot of farmers are feeding their winter hay now,'' said
Junior McCall of Clarinda, Iowa. ``We usually don't have to start
(feeding) hay until December,'' added Larry Keller of Nunia, Iowa.
   The Iowans will cut mostly grasses planted to prevent erosion on
the reserve lands in northern and eastern Latah County, about 30
miles east of Moscow, Tracy said.
   The hay is to be shipped back to Iowa on rail cars donated by
the Burlington Northern Railroad.
   Details were still being worked out on getting the hay to
loading points and how it will be distributed when it arrives in
the Midwest, said McCall, who made the trip with his son, Jeff.
   ``Hopefully, it will be dropped off at different spots,'' he
said.
   Help for the Iowa farmers came from fraternities at the
University of Idaho and Washington State University, which have
offered to help harvest the hay, as did Future Farmers of America
and other farm organizations, Tracy said.
   Local restaurants and Granges have donated food to feed the
field workers. Three banks in Chariton, about 45 miles south of Des
Moines, put up cash for meals along the way.
   ``We haven't had to pay for anything yet,'' said Keller.
   Norman Plank, an Idaho Farm Bureau official, estimated 200
boxcar loads of hay might be moved.
   The 4,500 acres could be expected to produce about 5,000 tons of
hay, said Dan Harwood of Colfax, Wash., a National Farmers
Organization representative.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
