<DOCNO> AP880824-0306 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 2354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ThriftPanel     08-24 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Thrift Panel,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investors Flock To `How To' Seminar on Thrift Investment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELISABETH DUNHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financiers who have acquired troubled
savings and loans told a capacity crowd of high-stakes investors
Wednesday that the thrift industry is the investment ``bonanza'' of
the next decade.
   More than 350 investors packed a conference room at the Fairmont
Hotel to hear three nationally-known investors share their insight
on how to make money buying into the beleaguered thrift industry.
   The daylong event was sponsored by the Federal Home Loan Bank of
San Francisco, which hopes to lure investors with at least $1.5
million to spare into purchasing an ailing thrift.
   ``This will be your bonanza in the next decade _ lucky you,''
said Preston Martin, chairman of Wespar Financial Services Inc. and
former vice chairman of the Federal Reserve.
   Martin, who is involved in several investment groups, including
that of former U.S. Treasury Secretary William E. Simon, appeared
with investment banker Alan E. Rothenberg and Stephen T. McLin,
president of San Francisco's America First Financial Corp.
   The panel members are touting thrift investment because they say
the competition will help their own businesses thrive and will
improve the health of the whole industry.
   ``It's important to get this problem solved,'' said McLin.
``It's going to help the health of the entire industry. The sooner
we get this thing fixed, the better it's going to be for
everybody.''
   The symposium also featured Federal Home Loan Bank Board
Chairman M. Danny Wall, who told listeners it was important to
build up the industry's capital.
   ``We see (that) more and more of our attention should be given
to the savings side,'' Wall said. ``This country has got to do more
about capital expansion if we want to continue to be competitive in
this world.''
   Thrifts are attractive investments in several aspects, according
to the Federal Home Loan Bank of San Francisco. Unlike commercial
banks, they are relatively easy to acquire, and there are few
restrictions on what types of businesses may acquire an ailing
thrift.
   Furthermore, they provide flexibility in investment powers,
including broad powers for real-estate-related diversification, and
are relatively easy to expand geographically, under federal laws
allowing thrifts to branch in up to three states.
   In its latest acquisition, DP Holdings Inc., the investment
group headed by Martin and Simon, received federal approval Tuesday
to acquire two California savings and loan institutions, including
one that is insolvent.
   DP Holdings will raise up to $207.5 million in new capital to
finance the acquisition and will get a federal assistance package
totaling an estimated $565 million.
   McLin, whose limited partnership in May acquired Eureka Federal
Savings & Loan Association, a troubled San Francisco-area thrift,
said that to successfully take over a thrift an investor must have
capital, good management and patience.
   ``We went into (Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp.) with
the willingness to invest $100 million _ and we had this in cash,''
he said, describing the Eureka acquisition.
   ``Conversely, if you're short on capital you'd better be very
long on management. If you can go in and hit them with a proven
track record, then it's possible without creating more of a joint
venture framework,'' McLin said.
   Regulators are trying to sell 259 thrifts. A much larger number
are technically insolvent but have not yet been taken over by
federal officials.
   Last week in Atlanta, a similar symposium attracted 600 people.
   Bank Board officials have struggled to bring new capital into a
thrift industry battered by bad loans, and see the interest in the
symposiums as a sign that enthusiasm among investors may be growing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
